        "response": "I'll dig into this for you. Tiny houses in Portland have some specific rules, and the answer depends heavily on your lot's zoning, so let me check both the general regulations and your specific property.Now let me look up the specific zoning and characteristics of this property.Let me try to pull up the specific property on PortlandMaps directly.Lots of neighbors on this street are R7 zoning. Let me verify the specific property.Let me try to fetch the specific Redfin listing for this address directly.Confirmed the property: 1 bed/1 bath, 960 sqft, built 1947. Now let me check the specific R7 zone requirements for ADUs.Short answer: **Yes, almost certainly** \u2014 but the most useful path depends on whether you want a permanent structure or something faster and lighter. Let me lay out what I found, with a few things you probably don't know that change the calculus.\n\n## What your specific lot looks like\n\nYour property at 831 SE 174th Ave is a 1 bed/1 bath, 960 sqft single-family home built in 1947. Every neighboring property I could check on SE 174th in 97233 is **R7-zoned** (1142, 1621, 1711, 1772, 1415, 2150 SE 174th all show R7), and Portland's official zoning code groups your neighborhood (Centennial/Hazelwood) into R7. I'd put high confidence on R7 for your lot, but **verify it yourself** at portlandmaps.com before spending a dime on design. R7 is one of the most ADU-friendly zones in Portland.\n\n## Three real paths, ranked by speed-to-livable\n\n**Path 1: Tiny house on wheels (THOW) parked on your lot \u2014 fastest, lightest**\n\nThis is a path most people don't realize exists. Portland treats tiny houses on wheels as \"occupied recreational vehicles\" under Chapter 33.260 of the Portland Zoning Code, and you're allowed one on a lot that already has a house. No building permit for the structure itself. You'll need an electrical permit for a dedicated 20-amp GFCI circuit/pedestal connection and a plumbing permit if you connect to sewer