        "response": "I have the property data. Now let me check Portland's current tiny house and ADU regulations.Let me get specifics on R7 zone setbacks and the Aircraft Landing overlay since both apply here.Let me verify the current SDC waiver status and what the \"h\" Aircraft Landing overlay means for this site.Yes, you can build a tiny house at 831 SE 174th Ave, and your lot is actually a strong candidate for it. But before the answer: a quick flag worth raising upfront.\n\n**Heads up on ownership.** Multnomah County records currently show this property owned by Karam & Janoura, with a 2020 sale price of $240K. If you're researching it as a potential acquisition rather than a property you already own, the constraints below would transfer to whoever owns it. If you've recently bought it and the assessor just hasn't updated yet, ignore this note.\n\n## What you've got\n\nYour lot is **0.19 acres (~8,276 sq ft)** with a **960 sq ft house from 1947** in the Centennial neighborhood. The zoning is **R7 (Residential 7,000)** with an **\"h\" Aircraft Landing overlay** (related to Troutdale Airport flight paths; for a single-story tiny house this almost certainly won't bind, but verify the specific height ceiling at this location with a planner). No flood, landslide, or wildfire hazard zones; sewer through City of Portland BES; water through Rockwood Water PUD (not Portland Water Bureau, which matters for utility connection planning).\n\n## Three real paths, in plain terms\n\n**Path 1: Detached ADU on a foundation (most common \"tiny house\" path).** This is the cleanest legal route. Because you already have a primary house, R7 imposes no minimum lot size for a single ADU; you just need frontage on a city-maintained street (174th qualifies). Specific limits for your lot:\n\n- Max ADU living area: **720 sq ft** (75% of your 960 sq ft house, since that's smaller than the 800 sq ft cap)\n- Max height: 20 ft outside setbacks, 15 ft within setbacks\n- Must be either \u226540 ft from the front lot line or located behind the existing house\n- No additional parking required\n- Combined accessory structure footprint capped at 15% of lot (\u22481,240 sq ft)\n\n**Path 2: Two detached ADUs.** Since 2021 (RIP1), R7 lots \u22655,000 sq ft can have **two ADUs** alongside the primary house. You're at 8,276 sq ft, so you qualify. Same 720 sq ft / 20 ft / siting rules per unit, and one of the two must meet visitability standards (no-step entry, accessible bathroom, \u2265200 sq ft accessible living area).\n\n**Path 3: Tiny house on wheels (THOW).** Portland treats THOWs as RVs, not buildings. One occupied THOW is allowed on a residential lot that already has a primary dwelling. It must remain mobile (wheels stay on), parked \u22655 ft from the house, and have a dedicated 20-amp GFCI electrical hookup. Cannot be a short-term rental. This is the fastest, cheapest path but the unit doesn't add appraised value or count toward density.\n\nThere are also wilder options your lot could technically support (cottage cluster needs \u22657,000 sq ft in R7 \u2014 you qualify; up to 16 detached units, no ADUs allowed in that path), but those are full development plays, not \"tiny house\" scope.\n\n## The thing most people miss right now\n\nPortland City Council passed Ordinance 192082 in July 2025, creating a **temporary SDC exemption window for new housing units running Aug 15, 2025 through Sept 30, 2028**. SDCs (system development charges) typically run $15K\u2013$30K+ on a new ADU. There are two stacking programs:\n\n- The long-running **ADU SDC Waiver** (10-year covenant, no short-term rental) \u2014 still active, no expiration\n- The **temporary citywide SDC exemption** for new dwelling units \u2014 different program, runs through Sept 2028\n\nIf you're going to build, the 2026\u20132028 window is meaningfully cheaper than building post-2028. Don't sit on this if it's actually on your roadmap.\n\n## Practical next steps\n\nThe single highest-leverage move is the **free 15-minute planner consultation** through Portland Permitting & Development at 503-823-7300, or an \"Early Assistance\" meeting for deeper review. Bring the property ID **R337949** and state ID **1S3E06AB 8800**. Ask specifically: (1) the exact height ceiling imposed by the \"h\" overlay at this lot, (2) whether the existing 1947 house has any unpermitted additions that could complicate ADU permitting (the property had only one bathroom of record, worth verifying), and (3) sewer connection requirements since BES may require a separate or upsized lateral.\n\nFor permits, you'll use **Development Hub PDX** online. Note that you cannot do the electrical work yourself on an ADU even as the homeowner; that requires a licensed electrical contractor. The general construction work you can DIY with the Owner Doing Work form.\n\n---\n\nTwo things I can do from here if useful: I can save a structured summary of this research (with the property IDs, code section references, and SDC links) into your Obsidian vault under `project-docs/` so it's there next time you pick this up, and/or I can pull the actual permit history for this address to check whether the existing house has any open or unresolved permits that would complicate things. Want either or both?",
