n or virtual appointment, the **Early Assistance** program, **Customer Service** phone line, etc.), and what I should bring or know before contacting them. Cover at least:\n   - **BDS (Bureau of Development Services)** \u2014 permits and zoning questions\n   - **BES (Bureau of Environmental Services)** \u2014 sewer and stormwater\n   - **Portland Water Bureau** \u2014 water service\n   - **PBOT (Portland Bureau of Transportation)** \u2014 driveway / street work\n   - **Urban Forestry (under Portland Parks & Recreation, PP&R)** \u2014 trees\n   - **PF&R (Portland Fire & Rescue)** \u2014 fire access if it applies\n\n7. **Realistic cost and timeline ranges**, translated into plain language. Permit fees, **SDCs**, design/engineering, utility hookups, construction. Give ranges, not single numbers, and translate (\"SDCs alone for a new dwelling unit in Portland are often in the range of a new economy car\"). Tell me how long each phase usually takes \u2014 application review, plan check, inspections, construction \u2014 in weeks or months, and where the typical delays come from.\n\n8. **Common mistakes Portland homeowners make on tiny house / ADU projects** \u2014 a real \"what you might get wrong\" section. Examples I've heard about: assuming a tiny house on wheels can be lived in permanently, buying plans before checking zoning, removing a tree without a tree permit, not realizing the lot is in an environmental overlay, missing the sewer connection cost.\n\n**Format the answer like this, in this order:**\n\n1. **Plain-English answer first** \u2014 3 to 5 sentences answering whether I can build a tiny house at this address and what the biggest catches are. No citations, no jargon, no table.\n2. **What \"tiny house\" means here** \u2014 short section walking me through the legal categories in plain English.\n3. **What your address likely allows** \u2014 a short read of the zoning and overlays for 831 SE 174th Ave with a clear \"verify this on PortlandMaps before spending 