ched ADU must either sit behind the rear wall of the main house, or be at least 40 ft from the front lot line.\n- Maximum size: 800 sq ft (since 75% of your 2,156 sq ft house = ~1,617, the 800 cap binds).\n- Maximum height: 20 ft if it's outside the setbacks, 15 ft if any part sits inside a side or rear setback.\n- Detached accessory structures together can't cover more than 20% of the lot, and the ADU's footprint can't exceed the main house's footprint.\n- No additional parking required.\n\n**The corner-lot wrinkle (this is the part most people miss).** On a corner lot, the *front lot line* is the shorter of the two street frontages, regardless of where your front door is. The other street frontage is treated as a side street. So:\n- If 52nd Pl is your shorter street, 52nd Pl is your \"front\" for zoning, even if the house addresses to Belmont.\n- That changes which wall counts as the \"rear wall\" for ADU placement (it's the wall furthest from your front lot line).\n- And if you ever want to use the *setback exception* to push an accessory structure into a side or rear setback, the worksheet adds a corner-lot-only condition: the structure must be at least 20 ft from the side street lot line. That can quietly eliminate a chunk of buildable area on a corner.\n\nPull a tape measure on both street frontages; whichever is shorter is your \"front.\"\n\n**Three things that go above the question you asked:**\n\n1. **Your existing detached garage is probably the highest-leverage path.** Garage-to-ADU conversion in Portland is permitted with a building permit, and an *existing* structure that doesn't currently meet setbacks is generally allowed to stay where it is for the conversion (you'd just need to meet the ADU-specific standards: 800 sq ft cap, height limits, exterior standards if over 15 ft, plus building/energy code for habitability). That sidesteps the setback question almost entirely. The \"oversized one-car garage\" mentioned in the listing is exactly the kind of structure people convert.\n\n2. **A basement ADU dodges the size cap entirely.** If your basement is part of a primary structure that's at least five years old (yours is, by a wide margin), a basement ADU is *exempt* from the 800 sq ft / 75% rule. The Redfin description mentioned an unfinished basement with \"amazing ceiling height\" \u2014 that's potentially the easiest, cheapest, fewest-setback-questions path of all, since basement ADUs have no exterior placement issues.\n\n3. **Free pre-approved plans.** Portland publishes four free pre-approved detached-ADU plan sets (gable/shed roof \u00d7 slab/crawlspace combinations) at the [ADU Permits page](https://www.portland.gov/ppd/residential-permitting/home-projects/accessory-dwelling-units). They're not right for every lot, but they speed up review noticeably if one fits. Worth a look before commissioning custom plans.\n\n**My suggested next step,** given the userPreferences \"double-check before recommending\": confirm zoning on PortlandMaps, then book a free 15-minute appointment with a city planner (503-823-7300, or [ppd/early-assistance](https://www.portland.gov/ppd/early-assistance)). Bring the lot dimensions, the existing garage footprint, and a question about which path (garage conversion / basement ADU / new detached) makes most sense given your specific corner-lot orientation. They'll give you a definitive answer in 15 minutes that no document can.\n\nIf you can paste back what PortlandMaps shows under the Property panel (Base Zone, Overlay, Lot Size, Comprehensive Plan), I can re-run the numbers against your actual zoning rather than assumed R5.",
