        "response": "ADU Planning Guide: 5112 SE Belmont St\nProperty: 5112 SE Belmont St, Portland, OR 97215 Tax Property ID: R194819 | State ID: 1S2E06BA 17100 Prepared: May 5, 2026\n\nHow to read this guide. Plain-language explanation comes first; the code citation follows in parentheses so you can verify every claim. I pulled property-specific data directly from the City of Portland's PortlandMaps API for this address; I'll flag clearly where address-specific data wasn't available and where you should verify yourself.\n\n\nAt-a-glance: your property snapshot (verified from PortlandMaps, May 2026)\nItem\nValue\nSource / why it matters\nBase zone\nR5 (Residential 5,000)\nPortlandMaps zoning record. This is the foundation of everything.\nOverlays\nNONE\nNo design, historic, conservation, environmental, scenic, or plan-district overlays apply. This is the cleanest possible permitting path.\nComprehensive plan designation\nSingle-Dwelling 5,000\nMatches base zoning; no rezone pressure.\nPlan district\nNone\n\n\nHistoric / conservation district\nNone\n\n\nNeighborhood\nMt. Tabor\nMt. Tabor Neighborhood Association is the recognized NA.\nCouncil district\nDistrict 3\n\n\nLot area (approximate)\n~5,344 sq ft\nComputed from the City's tax-lot polygon; the exact dimensions and area should come from a survey or assessor record.\nHouse (year built / size)\n1957 / 2,156 sq ft living area\nThis matters: house-age >5 years unlocks the basement-ADU exemption from the 800 sq ft cap (33.205.040.C.1).\nAverage slope\n15%\nBelow the 20% threshold that triggers alternative R5 height/setback rules; above the 10% threshold that may trigger Title 24 grading/geotech requirements.\nSteep-slope area flag\nTRUE\nTitle 24 Building Code may require a soils/geotech report; this is mostly a building-permit consideration, not zoning.\nLandslide hazard area\nFalse\n\n\nFlood hazard\nNone\n\n\nLiquefaction zone\nn/a\n\n\nCombined sewer basin\nStark (combined sewer)\nSanitary and storm flow share the same pipe; expect on-site stormwater management requirements. Property is eligible for \"Eastside CSO\" Clean River Rewards discount.\nHydrologic soil group\nB (moderately well drained)\nReasonable for infiltration-based stormwater (drywells, drainage trenches).\nHeritage tree on site\nNone\n\n\nWellhead protection area\nFalse\n\n\nRecent permits on file\nTree-planting (right-of-way) Nov 2025; electrical 2023, 2024; mechanical 2022\nNo prior ADU permit.\nUnderground storage tanks\nNone on site (legacy USTs at neighboring corner properties on Belmont/Taylor)\nNot your problem directly, but flags that historical commercial uses existed nearby; relevant only if you ever excavate near a shared property line.\n\n\nVerify yourself: go to https://www.portlandmaps.com/, enter the address, expand \"Permits & Zoning\" \u2192 \"Zoning & Districts\", and \"Hazards.\" That's the same source I used. Free, authoritative, and what BDS plan reviewers look at.\n\n\n1. Zoning and what's allowed on the lot\n1a. Base zone: R5 (Residential 5,000)\nYour lot is R5, which is Portland's most common low-density residential zone. R5 is one of six \"single-dwelling zones\" defined in Chapter 33.110 (full list at 33.110.020). Despite the \"single-dwelling\" name, R5 today allows quite a bit more than one house thanks to the Residential Infill Project (RIP1, effective Aug 2021) and follow-on amendments. In R5 you can build any of these (Table 110-2 in 33.110.200):\n\nA house\nAn attached house (sharing a wall with a neighbor)\nAn ADU (governed by Chapter 33.205)\nA duplex (corner lots automatically; other lots subject to 33.110.265.D)\nA triplex (subject to 33.110.265.E)\nA fourplex (subject to 33.110.265.E)\nA multi-dwelling structure (subject to 33.110.265.F)\nA manufactured home\nA houseboat\nA congregate housing facility\n1b. Overlays: none apply\nNo \"a\", \"d\", \"h\", environmental, scenic, or plan-district overlays apply to this lot. I checked the PortlandMaps record directly. This is unusual luck for an SE Portland lot and saves you a lot of complication.\n1c. Historic / conservation review\nThe lot is not in a Historic or Conservation District; the house is not a Historic Landmark, Contributing Resource, or Conservation Landmark. No design or historic review will be triggered (Chapters 33.445 and 33.846 don't apply).\n1d. ADU rules: Chapter 33.205 applies\nYes, 33.205 applies. Here's what it says for your specific situation, an R5 lot with a house:\n\nNumber of ADUs allowed (33.205.020.B):\n\nOne ADU is allowed by right (33.205.020.B.1.a), as long as your lot complies with 33.110.202 \"When Primary Structures are Allowed.\" Your lot does (it has an existing primary structure).\nTwo ADUs are allowed (33.205.020.B.2) because your lot meets the R5 minimum lot area of 3,000 sq ft in Table 205-2, has frontage on a maintained street (Belmont), and is not in the Constrained Sites \"z\" overlay. If you build two ADUs, at least one must be detached from the primary structure.\n\nThat second point is genuinely useful: the 5,344 sq ft lot is comfortably above the 3,000 sq ft floor for two ADUs. Whether two pencil out economically and physically (given lot coverage limits below) is a separate question, but the zoning permits it.\n\nMaximum size (33.205.040.C.1):\n\nThe ADU's living area can be no more than 75% of the primary dwelling's living area or 800 sq ft, whichever is less.\n\nPrimary dwelling = 2,156 sq ft. 75% = 1,617 sq ft.\n800 sq ft is less.\nYour ADU is capped at 800 sq ft of living area.\n\nImportant exception: if you convert a basement (or any part of the primary dwelling) into an ADU and the primary dwelling has been on the site for at least 5 years, the 800 sq ft cap does not apply. Your house was built in 1957, so this exception is available. A basement conversion ADU could be larger than 800 sq ft.\n\nAlso new in 2025: the city has clarified that you can request an Adjustment Review (Chapter 33.805) to exceed 800 sq ft. Recently approved adjustments have allowed ~1,000 sq ft when design and lot-coverage criteria were met. Discretionary review takes ~8-10 weeks, no guarantee of approval, and there's an additional fee.\n\nMaximum height: 20 ft for a detached or connected ADU (33.110.245.C.1). This is the same cap that applies to garages and other covered accessory structures. (The previous 18 ft cap was raised to 20 ft in 2021.)\n1e. About short-term rentals\nADUs can be Type A short-term rentals (rental of bedrooms in the ADU; you live on-site) or Type B short-term rentals (rental of the whole ADU; specific standards in 33.815.040.B.1). See Chapter 33.207 Accessory Short-Term Rentals.\n\nCritical interaction with SDC waiver: if you take the ADU System Development Charge waiver (which is the standard play; saves ~$12,000-$19,000), you sign a 10-year covenant prohibiting any structure on the property from being a short-term rental. Even renting a bedroom in the main house counts as a violation, with a penalty of 150% of the waived fees. Decide early whether you want STR flexibility or the SDC savings.\n\n\n2. Setbacks: the core question\n2a. R5 base zone setbacks (Table 110-4 in 33.110.220)\nFor the primary structure in R5:\n\nSetback\nRequired minimum\nFront building\n10 ft\nSide building\n5 ft\nRear building\n5 ft\nGarage entrance\n18 ft (the door, not the garage walls)\n\n\nMaximum height for the primary structure: 30 ft (Table 110-4).\n2b. ADU setbacks: this is where it gets specific\nADUs in R5 follow a layered set of rules. There are three rule layers stacked on top of each other:\n\nLayer 1: ADU-specific siting rule (33.205.040.C.2). A detached or connected ADU must be either:\n\n(a) Set back 40 ft from the front lot line, or\n(b) Located behind the rear building wall of the primary dwelling (the wall furthest from the main entrance).\n\nThis is the \"stay out of the front yard\" rule. You can't put an ADU in front of or beside your house unless it satisfies (a) or (b).\n\nLayer 2: base-zone covered accessory structure rules (33.110.245.C). Default ADU setbacks are the same as the primary-structure setbacks: 10 ft front / 5 ft side / 5 ft rear. Maximum height 20 ft.\n\nLayer 3: the reduced-setback option for small accessory structures (33.110.245.C.2.b). R7, R5, and R2.5 zones permit you to build right up to (or close to) the side and rear lot lines if all of these are met:\n\nThe structure is at least 40 ft from a front lot line (and \u226520 ft from a side street lot line on a corner lot).\nThe footprint does not exceed 24 ft x 24 ft (576 sq ft footprint), excluding eaves.\nIf more than one structure is in the setback, combined length along each property line is \u2264 24 ft.\nThe structure is no more than 15 ft tall, and the walls are no more than 10 ft tall (excluding the gable).\nThe setback portion is screened from adjoining lots by a fence or landscaping (L3 or F2 standards in Chapter 33.248) unless walls fully enclose it.\nNo doors or windows on walls within the setback that face the adjacent lot line.\nNo rooftop deck.\nDormers set back \u2265 5 ft from the side and rear lot lines.\n\nPlain-English summary for your lot: if you put a detached ADU behind the rear wall of the house AND the ADU is at least 40 ft from Belmont AND the footprint is \u2264 24'x24' AND height is \u2264 15 ft AND wall height \u2264 10 ft (with no windows facing the neighbor on those reduced-setback walls), you can effectively build with zero or near-zero side and rear setbacks. This is the standard \"backyard cottage\" recipe. If you go taller (15-20 ft, e.g., to fit a loft) you must use full base-zone setbacks (5 ft side, 5 ft rear) AND meet the design compatibility rules in 33.110.245.C.4 (matching exterior materials, roof pitch, trim, windows, eaves to the primary house).\n2c. Setbacks: detached vs. attached vs. conversion\nDetached ADU (its own building): rules in 2b above. The 40 ft front setback or \"behind rear wall\" rule applies (33.205.040.C.2). Reduced setback option in 33.110.245.C.2.b is available.\nAttached ADU (sharing a wall with the house): the new combined structure must meet the primary-structure R5 setbacks (10/5/5/18 from Table 110-4). The 40 ft front / behind-rear-wall rule still applies (33.205.040.C.2 says \"detached AND connected\").\nConversion of basement / interior of house: no setback issues because no expansion of the building footprint. This is the simplest path. Basement conversions in a house \u22655 years old are also exempt from the 800 sq ft size cap (33.205.040.C.1).\nConversion of an existing detached structure (e.g., a 1957 garage, if there is one): the existing structure's nonconforming location is grandfathered, and a separate provision (33.110.245.C.2.c, the garage-conversion path) lets you reuse a pre-2005 garage in a setback as long as it's \u2265 40 ft from the front lot line and meets specific conditions. If you have a detached garage, this is often the cheapest ADU path because foundation, walls, and roof already exist.\n2d. How taller ADUs interact with setbacks\nADU height\nSetback regime\nDesign rules\n\u2264 15 ft and walls \u2264 10 ft\nReduced side/rear setbacks via 33.110.245.C.2.b\nNone of the matching-finish rules apply\n> 15 ft, \u2264 20 ft\nFull R5 setbacks: 10 ft front / 5 ft side / 5 ft rear\nMatch primary structure on materials, roof pitch, trim, windows, eaves (33.110.245.C.4)\n\n\nIn short: going from 15 ft to 16 ft of height costs you the reduced-setback option AND triggers design compatibility rules. This single distinction drives most ADU floor-plan decisions in Portland.\n2e. Lot coverage and building coverage\nMaximum building coverage for all covered structures combined (Table 110-5 in 33.110.225):\n\nLot size 5,000 sq ft to 20,000 sq ft: 2,250 sq ft + 15% of lot area over 5,000 sq ft.\nYour ~5,344 sq ft lot: 2,250 + 15% \u00d7 (5,344 - 5,000) = 2,250 + 51.6 \u2248 2,302 sq ft total combined building coverage.\n\nAdditional cap on accessory structures (33.110.245.C.3):\n\nCombined coverage of all detached and connected accessory structures: no more than 15% of the lot area.\nYour ~5,344 sq ft lot: 15% \u00d7 5,344 = ~801 sq ft for all accessory structures combined.\nAlso: an accessory structure's coverage cannot exceed the primary structure's coverage.\n\nWhy this matters in practice for your lot: if your house's footprint is, say, 1,500 sq ft (likely ballpark for a 2,156 sq ft 1.5-story 1957 house), you'd have roughly 800 sq ft of remaining building-coverage budget. That's enough for a single 24'x24' (576 sq ft) detached ADU footprint with margin to spare. It's tight but workable. You should measure your existing house footprint (or get it from Multnomah County assessor records or a survey) before assuming a specific ADU footprint will fit.\n2f. Required outdoor area (33.110.240)\nYour lot must preserve a contiguous outdoor area of at least 250 sq ft (10x10 ft minimum dimension, actually a 12x12 ft square must fit in it for R5; Table 110-4). It can't be in the front building setback. This is rarely the binding constraint, but worth checking when you're juggling a footprint, a deck, and an ADU on a small lot.\n\n\n3. Related rules you probably didn't think to ask about\n3a. Trees (Title 11, Chapter 11.50)\nTitle 11.50 governs trees during development. Important threshold: lots under 5,000 sq ft are exempt from tree preservation requirements. Your lot is ~5,344 sq ft, so the tree code likely applies to you, but it's close enough to the threshold that I'd flag this for verification by Urban Forestry.\n\nWhat 11.50 means in practice:\n\nA tree plan is required as part of your development permit (11.50.070).\nAll private trees \u2265 12 inches DBH (diameter at breast height) on your site, and all city trees \u2265 6 inches DBH, must be shown.\nYou must preserve at least 1/3 of non-exempt trees \u2265 12 inches DBH within the development impact area (11.50.040.C.1).\nFor trees you don't preserve, you pay into the Tree Planting and Preservation Fund (Table 50-1).\nFY 2025-26 mitigation rate: $472 per DBH inch for trees \u2265 20 inches removed in development. A single 24-inch tree = ~$11,328 in fees. Multiple large trees = quickly $20,000-$50,000.\nTrees \u2265 36 inches DBH require notice to the neighborhood association before removal.\nRoot Protection Zones during construction are roughly 1 ft of radius per inch of trunk diameter; you can't trench, grade, or build inside the RPZ without arborist oversight (11.60.030).\n\nAction: walk the lot, measure every tree \u2265 6 inches DBH, including those overhanging from neighbors, and any street trees. Photograph them. You'll need this anyway for the tree plan, and large trees often dictate where the ADU can physically sit. If a tree must come out, factor mitigation into your budget early.\n3b. Stormwater / sewer (Title 17, BES rules)\nYour property is in the Stark combined sewer basin: sanitary and storm runoff go to the same pipe. New impervious surface (ADU roof, paths, driveway extensions) typically triggers on-site stormwater management.\n\nKey references:\n\nCity of Portland Stormwater Management Manual (SWMM) is the operative document; it's updated periodically by BES. New construction generally must \"manage\" runoff through approved facilities (drywells, swales, rain gardens, stormwater planters, ecoroofs, etc.).\nTitle 17, Public Improvements, Chapter 17.32 (Public Sewer and Drainage System) governs sewer connections and rates.\nTitle 17.36 covers Sewer User Charges and connection fees.\nSystem Development Charges (SDCs) are levied separately by sewer/water/transportation/parks bureaus (see section 3g).\nYour lot is eligible for the Eastside CSO Clean River Rewards discount on the BES bill if you manage stormwater on-site.\n\nSewer lateral check: the site already has a sewer lateral (PortlandMaps shows it). The combined gravity main runs in Belmont (compkey 140255). Before adding fixtures, your contractor should ensure the existing lateral is in good condition and sized to carry one or two additional dwelling units. A sewer scope (camera inspection) costs $150-$300 and is cheap insurance. Replacing a failed lateral can run $5,000-$15,000+ depending on depth and length.\n3c. Building (Title 24), plumbing (Title 25), electrical (Title 26), mechanical (Title 27)\nPortland adopts the Oregon Residential Specialty Code (ORSC) for one- and two-family dwellings, plus state plumbing, electrical, and mechanical codes. Title 24-27 are the local administration of these.\n\nYou will need:\n\nBuilding permit (Title 24): structural, foundation, framing, insulation, weatherproofing, energy code compliance.\nPlumbing permit (Title 25): fixtures, drains, water service, sewer connection.\nElectrical permit (Title 26): service entrance, panel work, outlets, lighting.\nMechanical permit (Title 27): HVAC, hot water, gas, ventilation.\nBES Connection Permit (sewer hookup; sometimes called a sewer connection permit) if you're adding a new connection or upsizing.\n\nThese can be combined: BDS calls a combined ADU package an \"ADU project\" and you submit one application covering all four trade permits plus the building permit. You can also use pre-approved ADU drawings (sometimes called \"stock plans\") for faster review.\n\nImportant for your lot's steep-slope flag: Title 24 may require a soils investigation report and geotechnical recommendations when grades exceed 10% with > 5 ft vertical change, especially if you're cutting into a hillside for foundations. Confirm at intake whether your foundation design needs a stamped geotech report. A geotech report runs $1,500-$4,000.\n3d. FAR and density bonuses\nR5 has FAR limits (Table 110-4):\n\n1 dwelling unit: 0.5:1\n2 dwelling units (including the ADU): 0.6:1\n3+ dwelling units: 0.7:1\nWith \"preserving existing dwelling unit\" bonus: 0.7:1 for 2 units (33.110.210.D.2)\n\nTo qualify for the preservation bonus, your existing house must have received final inspection at least 5 years ago (it has; it was built in 1957) AND you must alter no more than 25% of the existing street-facing facade.\n\nFor your 5,344 sq ft lot:\n\n0.5:1 FAR = ~2,672 sq ft total floor area allowed (1 unit)\n0.6:1 FAR = ~3,206 sq ft (2 units, no bonus)\n0.7:1 FAR with bonus = ~3,741 sq ft (2 units, preservation bonus)\n\nYour 2,156 sq ft house plus an 800 sq ft ADU = 2,956 sq ft, comfortably under the 2-unit FAR with or without bonus. FAR is unlikely to be a binding constraint for a single ADU on this lot.\n\nDensity: 33.205.050 says ADUs are counted in minimum density calculations but not maximum density calculations. Your R5 lot would only trigger minimum density (2 dwelling units required) if the lot were \u2265 10,000 sq ft (33.110.205.B.2). Yours isn't, so this doesn't apply.\n3e. Parking\nNo off-street parking is required for an ADU in Portland, anywhere in the city (Chapter 33.266 has been amended; minimum off-street parking for residential uses was eliminated). Existing required parking for the primary dwelling must be maintained or replaced on-site only if it was previously required by code, which is rare on older R5 lots.\n\nIn practical terms, you can pave or not pave a parking pad, build a driveway extension or not, and the city won't force the issue. PBOT does still require curb cuts to comply with transportation standards if you change the curb (Title 17 again).\n3f. Short-term rental rules (Chapter 33.207)\nType A ASTR (host present, \u2264 5 bedrooms): renting up to 2 bedrooms in your ADU for less than 30 days is allowed with permit. Owner-occupancy of the primary dwelling is required.\nType B ASTR (host not present, or > Type A limits): subject to 33.815.040.B.1 standards.\nAll ASTRs require a separate ASTR permit and an Inspection.\nSDC waiver = 10-year prohibition on ANY STR on the property. Strictly enforced; recorded covenant; 150% repayment penalty for violation.\n3g. System Development Charges (SDCs) and the ADU SDC waiver\nSDCs are one-time fees assessed at building-permit issuance to fund infrastructure capacity. Roughly four bureaus charge SDCs:\n\nWater (PWB)\nSewer / stormwater (BES)\nTransportation (PBOT)\nParks (PP&R)\n\nTypical full SDC for a new ADU in Portland: ~$13,000-$22,000 combined, depending on fixture units, size, and current rates. Rates change annually each July 1.\n\nADU SDC Waiver Program: in place since 2010, extended indefinitely in 2018 with the STR-prohibition condition. If your ADU is owner-occupied or rented month-to-month-or-longer (no STRs), you can get the full SDC fees waived by signing a 10-year covenant. Apply through the Revenue Division (aducovenant@portlandoregon.gov). Application has a ~99% approval rate when instructions are followed.\n\nNew temporary SDC exemption (Aug 15, 2025 - Sept 30, 2028): Portland adopted a 3-year exemption for new dwelling units (single-family, duplex, triplex, fourplex, multifamily). ADUs are explicitly excluded from this temporary exemption (Chapter 17.14.070). For an ADU, you continue to use the existing ADU SDC waiver. So this is informational only; it doesn't change your path.\n\nAlso worth knowing: Portland has periodically offered up to $15,000 cash incentives for owners committing to long-term rental (no STR). This program changes annually; check the Portland Housing Bureau and Prosper Portland sites at the time you're ready to apply.\n\n\n4. Permits and process\n4a. Permit types you'll need\nFor a typical detached ADU:\n\nBuilding permit (under it: structural, energy, fire, framing, insulation review).\nPlumbing permit (sub-permit, often issued under the same project).\nElectrical permit (sub-permit).\nMechanical permit (sub-permit).\nBES connection permit (sewer hookup).\nWater service permit (Portland Water Bureau) if you're upgrading or adding a meter.\nPBOT public works permit if you're touching the curb, sidewalk, or right-of-way (e.g., new driveway curb cut).\nTree permit (Title 11) if any regulated tree is to be removed; otherwise, the tree plan is reviewed as part of the building permit.\nErosion control permit (Title 10) for sites that will disturb 500+ sq ft of soil during construction. Most ADU projects need this.\nADU SDC Waiver application (Revenue Division, separate from BDS).\n\nFor a basement/interior conversion: simpler. You skip exterior site work, BES connection (usually), and possibly PBOT and tree permits. Building, plumbing, electrical, and mechanical sub-permits still apply.\n4b. What triggers what; what can be combined\nBDS issues a combined \"ADU project\" application that bundles building + sub-permits.\nPre-approved ADU drawings dramatically speed up review (a few weeks instead of months).\nTree review is part of the building permit, not separate.\nBES connection can be applied for in parallel with the building permit; typically issued before plumbing rough-in.\nThe SDC Waiver application is separate; submit it early in the permitting process, not after fees are assessed.\n4c. Pre-application / Early Assistance\nStrongly recommended for your situation. Portland offers two free or low-cost options:\n\nFree 15-minute appointment with a city planner: book online, ask zoning-specific questions. Best for \"is this allowed\" type questions.\nEarly Assistance meeting: more substantive, typically 1 hour, costs a few hundred dollars (current fee on the BDS schedule), and you get written feedback you can rely on. Best when you have draft site plans.\n\nWhy I'd recommend it for you: the steep-slope flag, the lot near the tree-code threshold (~5,344 sq ft), the combined sewer basin, and the question of one vs. two ADUs all benefit from a preliminary conversation. An hour now saves weeks of rework later.\n4d. Typical timeline\nApproximate, generally accurate as of 2025-2026:\n\nStep\nTime\nSchematic design and code research\n2-4 weeks\nConstruction drawings\n4-8 weeks\nPermit submittal to issuance (with pre-approved plans)\n4-8 weeks\nPermit submittal to issuance (custom plans)\n8-16 weeks\nConstruction (detached new build)\n4-8 months\nFinal inspections\n1-3 weeks\nTotal, custom detached ADU\n9-15 months\nTotal, basement conversion\n6-9 months\n\n\nIf you trigger an Adjustment Review (e.g., to exceed 800 sq ft) add 8-10 weeks.\n4e. Typical cost ranges (Portland, 2025-2026 ballparks)\nThese are estimates from third-party builders and city fee schedules; your specific project may vary substantially.\n\nItem\nBallpark\nBuilding/trade permit fees (1-time)\n$4,000 - $10,000\nSDCs (if NOT taking the waiver)\n$13,000 - $22,000\nSDCs WITH waiver\n$0\nGeotech report (if steep-slope triggers it)\n$1,500 - $4,000\nSewer scope (camera inspection of lateral)\n$150 - $300\nTree mitigation (if removing trees \u2265 12\")\n$472/DBH inch on trees \u2265 20\", trees 12-19\" charged at 2x replacement-tree cost\nConstruction, detached new ADU (turnkey, ~600-800 sq ft)\n$200,000 - $350,000\nConstruction, basement conversion (~600-1,000 sq ft)\n$80,000 - $200,000\nConstruction, garage conversion\n$100,000 - $200,000\n\n\nVerify current SDC and permit fee schedules at https://www.portland.gov/ppd/current-fee-schedules before final budgeting.\n\n\n5. Sequenced action plan: what to do in what order\nHere is a numbered checklist starting from \"today.\" Bureaus are noted in bold.\n\nVerify property data at https://www.portlandmaps.com/. Search your address. Confirm the zoning, overlays, hazards, and utilities match what's in this guide. This guide pulled the same data on May 5, 2026, but verify yourself before relying on any specific number.\n\nRead the BDS ADU page and Detached Covered Accessory Structures Worksheet. Free PDFs; takes an hour. Source: https://www.portland.gov/ppd/zoning-land-use/zoning-code-overview/adu-zoning. Bureau: Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D).\n\nWalk the lot with a tape measure. Document: existing house footprint dimensions; distance from house to each property line; locations and trunk diameters (DBH = ~4.5 ft above grade) of every tree \u2265 6 inches; existing driveway, paved areas, and outbuildings; rough north arrow.\n\nScope the existing sewer lateral. Hire a plumber (~$150-$300) for a camera inspection. Get a written report. Bureau: Bureau of Environmental Services (BES) (for context); you're working with a private plumber here.\n\nDecide the ADU type early: detached new build vs. attached addition vs. basement conversion vs. garage conversion (if you have a garage). This decision drives everything else. Typical economics: basement conversion cheapest, garage conversion next, detached new build most expensive but most flexible and resaleable.\n\nBook a free 15-minute planning appointment with PP&D for zoning questions. https://www.portland.gov/ppd/zoning-land-use/free-15-minute-appointments-permit-code-and. Bureau: PP&D zoning desk.\n\nOptional but recommended: schedule an Early Assistance meeting with PP&D. ~$500 fee (verify current schedule). Bring a rough site plan. Get written feedback that you can rely on through permitting. Bureau: PP&D.\n\nHire a designer or builder. Get 2-3 bids from Portland-experienced ADU specialists. Look for someone who's done ADUs in your zone in the last 12 months. Ask for references and to see their permit-issuance time.\n\nDecide on the SDC waiver. If you commit to no STR for 10 years, apply through the Revenue Division (aducovenant@portlandoregon.gov) early in the design phase. Saves $13K-$22K. Bureau: Revenue Division (separate from PP&D).\n\nSchematic design + tree plan. Your designer produces a site plan showing setbacks, building footprint, parking, tree protection zones, stormwater management, and outdoor area.\n\nIf a regulated tree must be removed, weigh the mitigation fee against re-siting the ADU. Bureau: Urban Forestry (questions: 503-823-4489).\n\nConstruction drawings + structural calcs. If steep-slope-related geotech is required, commission a soils report at this stage.\n\nSubmit the building permit application through PP&D's online portal (Development Hub at https://www.portland.gov/ppd). Bundle the trade permits in one application. Pay intake fees. Bureau: PP&D.\n\nSubmit BES connection permit if a new sewer/storm connection is needed. Bureau: BES.\n\nErosion control permit if disturbing > 500 sq ft of soil. Bureau: PP&D (administered under Title 10).\n\nPBOT public works permit if you're cutting a new driveway, modifying the sidewalk, or doing any work in the right-of-way. Bureau: PBOT.\n\nAddress plan review comments (typically 2-3 rounds; faster with pre-approved plans).\n\nPermit issuance and pay fees / SDC waiver applied. Print permits and start work.\n\nConstruction with rough and final inspections at each trade phase. Schedule via PP&D's IVR/web system.\n\nFinal inspection and Certificate of Occupancy.\n\nAddress-numbering for the ADU (if separate mailing address): apply through PP&D after framing inspection.\n\nRecord the ADU SDC Waiver covenant (Multnomah County) if applicable; this happens automatically through the Revenue Division.\n\nUpdate your homeowner's insurance to add the ADU as a covered structure and consider landlord liability if you'll rent it.\n\nRegister as a landlord with the City Revenue Division (Residential Rental Registration program) if you'll rent the ADU long-term.\n\n\n6. Common gotchas in Portland (and what specifically to watch on your lot)\n6a. General Portland gotchas\nFront-yard placement. People assume \"behind the house\" means anywhere not in the front yard. The code is precise: the rear building wall is the wall furthest from the main entrance. If your house has an entrance on a side, your \"rear wall\" might not be where you think.\nSetback line vs. building line. The reduced-setback option in 33.110.245.C.2.b is permissive but strict on every condition. Miss any one (windows facing the side neighbor, dormers within 5 ft, footprint > 24'x24', wall height > 10 ft) and you lose the entire reduced setback.\nHeight calculation on sloped lots. Height is measured from \"average grade,\" not from the front of the building. On a sloped lot, average grade can be lower than you expect, which can push your ridgeline above the 20 ft cap. 33.930 has the measurement rules.\nTree code surprises. A neighbor's overhanging tree's RPZ extends onto your buildable area. You can be required to protect a tree you don't own.\nSewer lateral failures. Older Portland lateral sewers (cast iron, clay) are often near end-of-life. A failed lateral discovered during ADU plumbing rough-in can add weeks and $5K-$15K. Scope it before you design.\nSDC waiver covenant scope. Renting a bedroom in your main house on Airbnb violates the covenant on the entire property. People miss this.\nStormwater on small lots. With a combined sewer basin (yours), BES is increasingly insisting on retention/infiltration even on small additions, not just discharge. Plan for a drywell or rain garden footprint.\nPermit-package sequencing. People submit their building permit and then realize their ADU needs the SDC waiver AND a separate erosion control permit AND a tree review AND a BES connection. Bundle all of this from the start.\nEnergy code compliance (Oregon ORSC). The code requires increasingly tight envelope and HVAC performance. Designs from even 3-4 years ago may not pencil today without tweaks.\n6b. Specific to SE Portland / older neighborhoods\nLegacy lots. Karlinda Terrace plat (your subdivision's name in the legal description) was platted before modern lot-size standards. The \"N 1/2 OF LOT 1&2\" legal description means your lot is the north half of two original platted lots (likely 50' x 107' = 5,350 sq ft, consistent with my polygon estimate). Half-lots can complicate property line adjustments later if you ever wanted to split.\nNonconforming structures. Portland houses from the 1940s-1950s are often nonconforming to current setbacks (built before today's R5 standards). Check whether your existing house meets current 10/5/5 setbacks. If not, the \"established building line\" exception in 33.110.220.D.5 may help, but it's specific.\nUnderground storage tank (UST) legacy. PortlandMaps shows USTs on file at 4940 SE Belmont, 4914 SE Belmont, 5024 SE Belmont, 5300 SE Belmont, and 5016 SE Taylor (all within a few hundred feet). None on your lot. Mostly historic gas stations. Not your direct issue, but if you're excavating near a shared property line with one of these former-commercial corners, your excavator may flag it.\nSteep slope flag. Even at 15% average slope, your lot is flagged as a steep-slope area. This is a Title 24 building-code consideration (potential geotech requirement) more than a Title 33 zoning consideration. Don't let a contractor wave it off; ask in writing whether a soils report is needed at intake.\nCombined sewer basin. Stormwater management requirements are more stringent (and the on-site retention options sometimes more limited) in CSO basins. Conversely, Clean River Rewards offers an ongoing utility-bill discount if you manage stormwater on-site. If you're going to install a drywell or rain garden anyway, make sure your designer documents the credit application.\nGlencoe Elementary is 145 ft away. Construction noise rules in Title 18 (Noise Control) restrict hours; school-adjacency may add weight to neighbor complaints. Plan deliveries and noisy work outside school hours.\nBelmont street trees and overhead utilities. Verify that your construction-access plan doesn't damage either. Pruning of street trees requires a city permit.\n\n\n7. Accuracy caveats and what to verify\nWhere this guide may diverge from your specific situation, and where to verify:\n\nItem\nCaveat\nVerify at\nLot dimensions and exact area\nI computed ~5,344 sq ft from the City's tax-lot polygon (Web Mercator projection). The actual area is the assessor's record or a survey.\nMultnomah County Assessor's office or a survey. PortlandMaps shows the polygon.\nExisting house footprint\nNot in the API response. Estimate only.\nMultnom