else on top. If your fence sits on a retaining wall, height is measured from the higher side.\n\n## Setback requirement\n\nThis is where most homeowners trip up; \"setback\" means two different things in this context:\n\n1. **Fence-to-property-line setback**: there is none. You can build directly on the side and rear property lines. On the front, you can also build right on the front lot line; you just can't go above 3.5' there.\n2. **The \"front building setback\" zone**: this is the strip between your front lot line and where your house is required to sit back from the street (typically 10 feet in R5, though averaging with neighbors can change it). The 3.5' height cap applies *anywhere inside that strip*, even on the side property lines within it. Once you're past that imaginary setback line going toward the back of the lot, you can jump up to 8 feet on the side fence.\n\nSo in practice on a typical R5 lot: the front ~10' of your side fences must also step down to 3.5'; behind that, they can rise to 8'.\n\n## Things I'd flag specifically for your property\n\n**NE 33rd is the big one.** It's a major arterial, and Portland's right-of-way on arterials often extends 5\u201310 feet behind the sidewalk. The actual front property line is almost never at the curb and frequently isn't even at the back of the sidewalk. Building a fence on what *looks* like your front line can easily put it in PBOT's right-of-way, which is a tear-it-out situation. Before you place a single post on the 33rd-facing side, call PBOT at 503-823-7002 (they'll help locate the right-of-way line for free) or pay a licensed surveyor to mark it.\n\n**If you're on or near a corner**, vision clearance triangles apply at the intersection (Title 17). Inside that triangle, fences are typically capped much lower than 3.5' so drivers can see across. This is enforced separately from the zoning fence rules.\n\n**Permits**: a wood fence at 7 feet or under is *exempt* from a building permit but still must comply with zoning (heights, setbacks, right-of-way). You need a permit for: wood >7', masonry/concrete >4', chain link/woven wire >8', any pool barrier, or any fence >8' (which also requires engineering).\n\n**Materials gotcha**: any wood touching concrete or within 6\" of the ground must be pressure-treated or naturally rot-resistant (cedar, redwood). This catches a lot of DIY rebuilds.\n\n**Property line reality check**: Multnomah County's Office of Survey Records has plats but not exact line locations. The only way to know your true line is a survey by a licensed Oregon surveyor (typically $500\u2013$1,500). Worth it before you build, especially if you'll share costs with a neighbor; a misplaced fence becomes a legal headache that long outlives the wood.\n\n**Free 15-minute appointment**: Portland BDS offers a free planner consultation that will give you definitive answers for your specific address (book through portland.gov; in-person at 1900 SW 4th, Tues/Thurs).\n\nIf you tell me whether your front entrance faces NE 33rd (vs. a side street), and whether the lot is mid-block or corner, I can sharpen the front-setback number and flag any vision-clearance issues.",
