        "response": "I'll look this up properly for you. Portland's fence rules depend on your specific zoning, so let me check your property first rather than giving you generic info.Got the property details. It's zoned **R5 (Residential 5,000)** in Beaumont-Wilshire, with one overlay \"h\" (Aircraft Landing \u2014 affects building heights but not fences). No historic district, no conservation overlay. Now let me verify the current fence rules from Portland's actual code.Let me fetch the actual fence regulation text.Let me also fetch Portland's official fence brochure to verify the R5 setback numbers and confirm everything.I have everything I need. Both sources are official City of Portland documents (Title 33.110.275 and Brochure 3), so I'm confident in these numbers. Let me build you a quick visual since the rules depend on which part of your lot we're talking about, then give you the answer in plain English.## The answer for your property\n\nYour lot at 3220 NE 33rd Ave is zoned **R5 (Single-Dwelling 5,000)**. It's a mid-block lot, no historic district, no plan district. There's an \"h\" (Aircraft Landing) overlay on the property, but it only restricts tall buildings near flight paths; it has no effect on residential fences.\n\nMaximum fence heights without a permit:\n\n- **Front yard (along NE 33rd Ave): 3.5 ft** within the front building setback, which is the first 10 ft from your front lot line\n- **Side yards: 8 ft** within the 5-ft side setbacks (one on the north lot line, one on the south)\n- **Back yard: 8 ft** within the 5-ft rear setback\n- **Outside any setback** (the buildable middle): can go taller, but anything over 7 ft requires a building permit, and over 8 ft requires engineering\n\nSetback summary for R5: **10 ft front, 5 ft side, 5 ft rear** (per Title 33.110.220).\n\n## A few things worth knowing before you build\n\n**The 3.5 ft front limit only applies inside the 10 ft setback.** Beyond that 10 ft strip, even in your front yard, you can go to