        "response": "I'll start by pulling up the actual zoning and overlay data for your address, then research the current fence rules. Let me load the Portland Maps tools first.Got the address-specific data. One important correction up front: the property is actually in **Beaumont-Wilshire**, not Alameda. Now let me look up the current Portland fence code to make sure I cite the right rules.I have the chapter structure. Now I need to get the actual fence section (33.110.275). Let me fetch the next portion.Let me also verify the sight-distance and vision clearance rules, plus check whether there's an alley behind this lot.Let me check whether there's an alley behind the property and what streets bound it.I have everything I need. Here's your answer.\n\n---\n\n# Fence rules for 3220 NE 33rd Ave\n\n## Confirmation: yes, I looked up your specific address\n\nI pulled the actual zoning record for **3220 NE 33rd Ave** from PortlandMaps. One small surprise up front: your property is in the **Beaumont-Wilshire** neighborhood, not Alameda. Alameda is a few blocks west; the official neighborhood line runs roughly along NE 33rd Ave in places, so it's a very common mix-up. The zoning rules are the same either way (your zone is **R5**, the most common single-family zone in Portland), but I wanted to flag it so you don't get bounced if you ever say \"I live in Alameda\" to the city.\n\nYou can verify any of this yourself in about three minutes at **portlandmaps.com**: type your address into the search bar, click your house, and look at the \"Zoning\" panel on the right. You should see \"R5\" and one overlay code, \"h\" (more on that below; it doesn't affect fences).\n\nTwo other quick corrections before we get into it:\n\n- The fence section of the zoning code you mentioned, **33.110.255**, was renumbered in 2020. The current section is **33.110.275**. (33.110.255 is now about flag lots, which doesn't apply to you.)\n- The bureau you'll deal with used to be called **Bureau of Development Services (BDS)**. As of 2023 it was renamed to **Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D)**. A lot of older websites and brochures still say BDS; it's the same office, same phone number.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The short version (read just this if you're in a hurry)\n\nIn your **back yard and side yards**, you can build a fence up to **7 feet tall** with no permit needed; you can go up to **8 feet** with no permit if it's chain-link or woven wire, but anything taller than 7 feet in wood or solid material needs a building permit. In your **front yard** (the strip between your house and NE 33rd Ave, which is roughly the first 10 feet in from the sidewalk), the fence can only be **3 feet 6 inches tall**, no matter what it's made of. Fences must sit **entirely inside your property line**; they can't go on the strip of city-owned land between the sidewalk and the street. **Replacing a fence in the same spot at the same height doesn't need a permit**, and a typical 6-foot wood fence on the side and back of your lot is permit-free. Your property has no historic, conservation, or design overlay, so the standard rules apply cleanly.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The details, broken out by location\n\n### Front yard (the part facing NE 33rd Ave)\n\nYour \"front yard\" for fence purposes is the area between your front property line (which is roughly at the back edge of the sidewalk; more on that below) and an imaginary line **10 feet inside your property** running parallel to the street. That 10-foot strip is called the **front building setback**, the area where the city requires open space in front of your house.\n\nInside that front strip, **the fence can be at most 3 feet 6 inches tall (3 ft 6 in)**, period (PCC 33.110.275). That's a low picket fence, basically. The material doesn't matter; solid cedar, chain link, decorative iron, lattice, all are capped at 3'6\". And remember, the **3'6\" includes any topper**: a 3-foot picket fence with a 1-foot lattice on top counts as 4 feet, which is over the limit.\n\nIf you go past that 10-foot line and onto the part of the side or back of your yard that's actually behind the front of your house, you can go up to 7 or 8 feet (see below).\n\n**Sight visibility at your driveway**: Even though the city doesn't have a hard sight-triangle rule for mid-block driveways like yours, you're still responsible for not blocking driver visibility (PCC 33.266.130). The practical rule of thumb is: if you're putting a 3'6\" solid fence next to your driveway entrance, set it back a few feet from the curb cut so you can see oncoming bikes and pedestrians. NE 33rd Ave is a busy collector street, so this matters more on your block than on a quiet side street.\n\n**Where the fence can sit in relation to the sidewalk**: Your fence has to be **entirely inside your property line, including the post footings**. The edge of the sidewalk is *not* your property line. There's almost always a strip of city-owned land between the sidewalk and your actual front yard (the **planting strip** or **right-of-way**); see the section near the bottom on this. You cannot build any fence in that strip without a special permit from PBOT, which is rarely granted for fences.\n\n**Hedges count as fences when they're tall.** A solid hedge in your front yard taller than 3'6\" is technically a code violation under the same fence rule, though enforcement is usually complaint-driven. Trees and shrubs that are clearly individual plantings, not a continuous wall, are governed by the tree code (Title 11), not the fence code.\n\n**Retaining walls change the math.** If you build a fence on top of a retaining wall, the city measures fence height **from the higher side of the wall**, not the lower side. So a 2-foot retaining wall with a 4-foot fence on top counts as a 4-foot fence on the high side, but the wall itself plus the fence may total 6 feet on the low side, which can affect both the permit and what the neighbors see.\n\n### Side yards (between your house and the neighbors on either side)\n\nIn R5, the **side building setback is 5 feet**, meaning the city requires a 5-foot strip of open space along each side of your house.\n\nThe fence rule splits the side yard into two parts:\n\n- The part of the side yard that's **forward of the front of your house** (in line with the front of your house, between your house and the street): this is treated as part of the front setback, so the **3'6\" cap** applies there.\n- The part of the side yard that's **alongside or behind the front wall of your house**: you can go up to **7 feet (wood/solid) or 8 feet (chain-link or woven wire)** with no permit. Material matters here only for what triggers a permit, not for the height limit itself; a wood fence at 7'6\" is allowed but needs a permit, while a chain-link fence at 7'6\" is allowed without a permit (PCC 24.10.072.B).\n\nPractical translation: if your house sits 15 feet back from the front property line, the first ~15 feet of fence on each side of your house can only be 3'6\" tall. From there back to your rear property line, you can have your full 6- or 7-foot privacy fence.\n\n### Back yard\n\nYour back fence can be up to **7 feet tall** (wood or any solid material) with **no permit required**, or up to **8 feet** if it's chain-link or woven wire. Going taller than 7 feet in wood requires a building permit. Going taller than 8 feet in any material requires a permit *and* an engineer's design (PCC 24.10.072.B and Brochure 3).\n\n**Alley question**: Many Beaumont-Wilshire blocks have alleys, but I couldn't confirm from the city's data whether your specific block does. Verify on PortlandMaps; if there's a thin gray strip behind your lot on the basemap, that's an alley. **If your back lot line abuts an alley, the rear setback for your house drops to zero** (PCC 33.110.220.D.9), and a fence can sit right on the lot line. You still can't build a fence *in* the alley itself; the alley is public right-of-way managed by PBOT. Watch for sight visibility at the alley exit; same logic as a driveway.\n\n**Material differences again**: solid wood, vinyl, or concrete fences all share the 7-foot no-permit limit. Chain-link and woven wire get an extra foot (8 feet no-permit) because they're see-through. Lattice toppers count toward total height; if you want a 6-foot solid fence with a 1-foot lattice topper, that's a 7-foot fence, which is right at the no-permit limit. A 6-foot fence with a 2-foot lattice topper is an 8-foot fence and needs a permit.\n\n### Quick comparison\n\nHere's the same information in one table, since you're comparing three locations on the same set of dimensions. **In plain words: your front yard is locked at 3'6\", and side and back can go to 7 or 8 feet depending on material, with retaining walls measured from the high side.**\n\n| Location | Max height (no permit) | Max height (with permit) | Where the fence can sit |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Front yard (within 10 ft of front property line) | 3 ft 6 in, any material | 3 ft 6 in is also the cap with a permit; you can't exceed it | Inside your property line, behind the planting strip |\n| Side yard, forward of front of house | 3 ft 6 in (treated as front) | Same; can't exceed 3'6\" | Inside your property line |\n| Side yard, alongside or behind house | 7 ft (wood/solid), 8 ft (chain-link/wire) | Up to height of base zone, with engineering | Inside your property line, may sit on lot line |\n| Back yard | 7 ft (wood/solid), 8 ft (chain-link/wire) | Up to 30 ft (zone max), with engineering and permits | Inside your property line; may sit on lot line; 0 ft setback if alley behind |\n\n---\n\n## 3. Zoning and overlays for your address\n\nYour property is **R5 (Residential 5,000)**, which is Portland's standard single-family residential zone, named for the historical 5,000-square-foot minimum lot size. This is by far the most common zone in close-in northeast Portland and applies to most of Beaumont-Wilshire.\n\nYou have **one overlay**: the **\"h\" Aircraft Landing overlay** (your full zone code reads \"R5h\"). This is a height-restriction overlay tied to flight paths around PDX. It limits how tall buildings and structures can be to keep airspace clear. **It has zero practical effect on a residential fence**; the height ceiling under \"h\" is in the hundreds of feet here. I'm only mentioning it because you'll see it on PortlandMaps and it sounds dramatic.\n\nYou have **none** of the things that would change your fence rules:\n\n- No **historic district** (no Alameda Park or Irvington-style historic protection)\n- No **conservation district**\n- No **design overlay**\n- No **environmental overlay**\n- No **plan district**\n- No **National Register district**\n\nSo the standard R5 fence rules apply cleanly.\n\n**How to verify yourself, in under 5 minutes**: Go to **portlandmaps.com**, type **\"3220 NE 33rd Ave\"** in the search bar, click your property on the map, and on the right side click \"Zoning.\" You should see \"R5\" as the base, \"h\" as the overlay, and empty rows for historic, conservation, plan district, and design. If anything in those rows is filled in, the rules in section 4 still apply but additional rules may stack on top.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Which Portland City Code Titles govern this\n\n**Title 33 \u2014 Planning and Zoning** is the main rulebook for fence height, where it can sit, and what counts as \"fence\" (lattice toppers, hedges that act as fences, etc.). The specific section for fences in single-family zones is **PCC 33.110.275**. The setback rules for buildings (which define the \"front building setback\" the fence rules reference) are at **PCC 33.110.220**.\n\n**Title 24 \u2014 Building Regulations** is the rulebook for whether a fence needs an actual building permit, separate from zoning. The exemptions from needing a permit (for fences 7 feet and under in wood, 4 feet and under in masonry, or 8 feet and under in chain-link) are at **PCC 24.10.072.B**.\n\n**Title 11 \u2014 Trees** is the rulebook that kicks in if a tree (yours or a city-owned street tree) is in the way of where you want to dig post holes. Most front-yard trees in Portland between the sidewalk and the street are city-owned street trees and protected by **PCC 11.50** and **11.60**. Damaging roots without an Urban Forestry permit can mean fines.\n\nIf you ever go above 8 feet of fence (or build a retaining wall over 4 feet with a fence on top), you also pull in the **Oregon Residential Specialty Code**, which is the state-level structural code Portland enforces.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Do you need a permit? Plain-language thresholds\n\nThree different answers depending on what you're building:\n\n**No permit needed if all of these are true:**\n\n- The fence is 7 feet tall or less and made of wood, vinyl, or similar material; OR\n- The fence is 8 feet tall or less and made of chain-link or woven wire; OR\n- The fence is 4 feet tall or less and made of masonry or concrete\n\n\u2026AND it sits entirely on your property, AND it's not in your front building setback above 3'6\", AND it doesn't enclose a swimming pool. This covers ~95% of residential fence projects in Portland, including a standard 6-foot cedar privacy fence.\n\n**Building permit required if any of these are true (PCC 24.10.072.B):**\n\n- The fence is taller than 7 feet in wood or solid material\n- The fence is taller than 8 feet in any material (also requires an engineer's design)\n- The fence is taller than 4 feet in masonry or concrete\n- The fence encloses a swimming pool, hot tub, or spa (regardless of height)\n- The fence sits on top of a retaining wall over 4 feet tall (the wall itself triggers a permit)\n- The fence is electric or has barbed wire (these are heavily restricted in residential zones; barbed wire is essentially banned in single-dwelling zones except for agricultural use, and electric fences are not allowed for residential perimeter fencing)\n\n**A privacy fence with a lattice topper**: lattice counts toward total height. A 6-foot fence + 1-foot lattice = 7 feet, no permit. A 6-foot fence + 2-foot lattice = 8 feet, permit needed.\n\n**Replacing an existing fence in the same spot, same height, same material**: no permit needed, treated as maintenance. If you're going taller, moving the line, or changing the structure, the new fence has to meet current code.\n\n**A fence over a retaining wall**: the city measures from the high side of the wall. A 6-foot fence on a 3-foot retaining wall is a 9-foot structure as the neighbors see it from the low side, but for code purposes it's a 6-foot fence (no permit) plus a 3-foot retaining wall (no permit, since under 4 feet). If the retaining wall is over 4 feet, it needs its own building permit.\n\n---\n\n## 6. What to do next, in order\n\n**Step 1. Verify your zoning and property lines yourself (free, 5 minutes).**\nGo to **portlandmaps.com**, search your address, click \"Zoning,\" and confirm \"R5\" base + \"h\" overlay + no other overlays. While you're there, click \"Property\" and look at the lot lines on the basemap. **Have ready**: just your address. **Cost**: free. **Time**: 5 minutes.\n\n**Step 2. Locate your actual property line, especially in front (free or paid, depending on how confident you want to be).**\nThe sidewalk is NOT your property line. PBOT can tell you for free where the **right-of-way line** is, which gives you a pretty good estimate of your property line in front (about a 5-minute call). **Contact**: Portland Bureau of Transportation (PBOT), 503-823-7002. **Have ready**: your address. **Cost**: free.\nFor a precise legal property line on all sides, hire a licensed surveyor. **Cost**: roughly $700\u2013$1,200, about the cost of a decent appliance. **Time**: 1\u20133 weeks for the survey to get scheduled and completed. **This step is optional but cheap insurance** if your fence will sit close to a neighbor's line.\n\n**Step 3. Schedule a free 15-minute appointment with a city planner (free, recommended).**\nThis is the single best thing you can do, and most homeowners don't know about it. A real planner will look up your property and answer specific questions before you spend a dollar on materials. **Contact**: Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D), book at portland.gov/ppd/early-assistance/15-minute-question-appointments, or call 503-823-7300. **Have ready**: your address, a rough sketch of where you want the fence and how tall, the fence material. **Cost**: free. **Time**: 15-minute call, scheduled within 1\u20132 weeks.\n\n**Step 4. (Only if your fence triggers a permit.) Apply online for the building permit.**\n**Contact**: PP&D online permitting, portland.gov/ppd. **Have ready**: a site plan (a sketch of your lot showing where the fence goes, distances to property lines, and existing structures), a fence elevation drawing showing height, materials, post spacing, and footing depth. For a fence over 7 feet, you'll need a stamped engineer's drawing. **Cost**: typically $200\u2013$400 for a residential fence permit, about the cost of a nice dinner out for two. **Time**: about 2\u20134 weeks for issuance for a simple fence.\n\n**Step 5. Call before you dig (free, required by Oregon law).**\nBefore any post hole gets dug, you must call **Oregon 811** (\"Call Before You Dig\") at **811** or **503-246-6699**, or request online at digsafelyoregon.com. They'll mark underground gas, water, electrical, and cable lines for free within 2 business days. Skipping this and hitting a gas line is a serious problem; it's also free, so just do it. **Cost**: free. **Time**: one call (10 minutes), then 2 business days for marking.\n\n**Step 6. (If digging near a street tree.) Clear it with Urban Forestry (free).**\nStreet trees in Portland are city-owned and root protection is real. If your fence post holes will be within about 10 feet of a street tree, call the **Tree Hotline** at **503-823-8733** before you dig. **Cost**: free. **Time**: one call.\n\n**Step 7. Build the fence.** A pro contractor for a typical 6-foot, 100-foot-long cedar fence is roughly $4,000\u2013$8,000 in Portland depending on grade, installed; that's about the cost of a solid used car. DIY the materials run $1,500\u2013$3,000 plus a couple of weekends of labor; roughly two summer weekends for a fit and patient builder, three or four if you're learning as you go. Fence pros are heavily booked May through August in Portland; expect a 4\u20138 week wait for a contractor in summer, versus 2\u20133 weeks in late fall or winter.\n\n**Step 8. Schedule the inspection (only if you pulled a permit).**\n**Contact**: PP&D 24-hour inspection line, **503-823-7000**. You'll need your IVR/permit number. **Cost**: included in permit fee. **Time**: inspectors usually come within 1\u20133 business days of request.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Script for calling the city\n\nHere's the actual sentence to read or paste in. Use this on the phone to PP&D General Inquiries (**503-823-7300**) or in your 15-minute appointment:\n\n> \"Hi, I own a home at **3220 NE 33rd Ave, 97212**, in the Beaumont-Wilshire neighborhood. PortlandMaps shows my zoning as R5 with the 'h' overlay. I'd like to build a **[6-foot cedar]** fence in my **[back and side yards]** and a **[3-foot picket]** fence in the **[front]**. Can you confirm: (1) the fence can sit on or just inside my property line on the side and back, (2) the front fence is capped at 3 feet 6 inches in the front 10 feet, (3) I don't need a building permit at these heights with these materials, and (4) there are no special overlay or plan district rules I'm missing? Also, can you tell me the width of the public right-of-way along NE 33rd Ave so I know where my front property line actually is?\"\n\nThat covers it in one shot and prevents you from getting bounced between PP&D and PBOT. **If they say the right-of-way question is for PBOT, that's correct**; call **PBOT at 503-823-7002** for the right-of-way width specifically.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common gotchas (the mistakes that actually cost Portland homeowners money)\n\n**The sidewalk is not your property line.** This is the single biggest mistake. The city right-of-way usually extends from the curb back about 6 to 12 feet, which often means the sidewalk *and* a strip of grass on the house side of the sidewalk are public land. If you build right up to the back edge of the sidewalk, you may be 5+ feet inside the city's right-of-way, and PBOT can require you to tear it out. Always confirm with PBOT before building anywhere within ~12 feet of the curb.\n\n**Hedges count as fences when they form a wall.** A solid laurel hedge in your front yard at 6 feet tall is a code violation, even though you didn't \"build\" anything. The city rarely enforces this proactively but a complaining neighbor can trigger a notice.\n\n**Removing a \"tree on your property\" without checking who owns it.** Almost every tree between the sidewalk and the street is a **street tree**, owned by the city, and removing it without an Urban Forestry permit is a $1,000+ fine plus replanting cost. Even on the house side of the sidewalk, large trees may be regulated by Title 11.\n\n**Damaging tree roots when digging post holes.** Hand-digging within the root zone of a street tree (roughly 10 feet from the trunk) requires Urban Forestry sign-off. Power-augering through tree roots can kill a 60-year-old tree, and you may be on the hook for a multi-thousand-dollar replacement.\n\n**Assuming your neighbor has to chip in for a shared fence.** Portland is clear on this: shared fences are a private matter between neighbors. Your neighbor is not legally required to pay half, allow you onto their side to install, or even agree to the project. If your existing fence sits on the property line, you both technically share it; if you tear it down without their consent and they liked it, that's a civil dispute the city will not get involved in. Talk to them in writing before you do anything.\n\n**Building tall fences too close to a driveway and creating a sight-line problem.** A 6-foot solid fence right at the curb cut on a busy street like NE 33rd makes it impossible to see oncoming bikes when you back out. The city's vision-clearance rules technically only kick in at street intersections, but you can get sued in a private case if a fence you built blocks a driver's view of a pedestrian. A common-sense practice: step the front fence section down to 3'6\" for the last 5\u201310 feet before your driveway exit.\n\n**Pouring footings that extend into the right-of-way or onto the neighbor's lot.** The footing is part of the fence; if your post is right on the line, the concrete blob below ground may extend across it. Set posts at least 6 inches inside the line.\n\n**Forgetting that NE 33rd Ave is a major street.** Some city setback and visibility rules are stricter on collector and arterial streets than on quiet residential streets. NE 33rd is a \"Neighborhood Collector\" by classification. None of this changes the basic 3'6\" front-fence rule, but it's worth mentioning to PP&D when you call.\n\n**Building in summer permit-rush.** PP&D plan-review wait times stretch out from May through August. A simple fence permit that takes 2 weeks in February can take 4\u20136 weeks in July. If you don't need the permit (most fences don't), this isn't an issue; if you do, plan ahead.\n\n---\n\n## 9. Friendly accuracy caveats\n\nA few things worth double-checking before you spend money:\n\n- **Verify the zoning yourself on PortlandMaps before you commit.** I pulled it from the same database the city uses, and as of today your zone is R5 with the \"h\" overlay and nothing else, but zoning can change with code updates and you want to confirm on the day you start your project. Type your address into portlandmaps.com.\n- **Don't trust me on the alley question.** I couldn't confirm whether your specific block has an alley behind it from the data I had. If your back yard backs onto another house's back yard, no alley; if there's a 12\u201316 foot strip of pavement behind the lot, that's an alley. PortlandMaps' aerial view will show this clearly.\n- **Property lines are legal facts that only a survey can establish.** PBOT can give you the right-of-way width, which gets you a good estimate, but a property survey is the only way to know for sure where your line actually is. If your fence will sit within 12 inches of where you think the line is, get the survey.\n- **Code numbers and fees change.** I cited the current section numbers as of today. The rules described here are stable (the current fence section was renumbered in 2020 but the underlying limits have been the same for years), but always confirm with PP&D before pulling a permit.\n- **The 15-minute appointment is the safest answer to all of this.** A planner looking at your specific address will catch anything I missed.\n\n---\n\n## A note on the planting strip and the city's land in front of your house\n\nThe strip of land between the sidewalk and the street (or, on streets without curbs, the unimproved area between the sidewalk and your property line) is called the **planting strip** or **furnishing zone**, and the legal designation is **public right-of-way (ROW)**. It's owned by the city and managed by **PBOT (Portland Bureau of Transportation)**. You generally can't build any fence, wall, or permanent structure there without a special permit from PBOT, which is rarely issued for residential fences.\n\nWhat you *can* do in the planting strip without a permit: maintain landscaping, plant approved street trees (with Urban Forestry permission), and do basic upkeep. What you *can't* do: build a fence, install permanent posts, pour concrete, or otherwise treat it like your yard.\n\nTo find out exactly how wide your right-of-way is along NE 33rd Ave, **call PBOT at 503-823-7002**. They'll look up your block and tell you the answer in about five minutes. This is free.\n\n---\n\n## A note on trees and Urban Forestry\n\nIf a tree is anywhere near your fence line, **Urban Forestry** is the part of Portland Parks & Recreation that has jurisdiction. The hotline is **503-823-8733**.\n\nYou'll want to call them if:\n\n- You'd be digging within roughly 10 feet of any tree larger than ~6 inches in diameter, especially street trees\n- You think the tree is in the way of your fence and might need to be pruned or removed\n- You're not sure if a tree on your property is regulated under the city's tree code\n\nSpring and early summer (April\u2013June) is when Urban Forestry is busiest, with a ~2-week response window for non-emergency calls. Late fall is faster.\n\nThe general rule of thumb: never cut a root larger than 2 inches in diameter on a street tree without Urban Forestry's sign-off. Hand-dig (don't auger) within 5 feet of a street tree trunk.\n\n---\n\n## A note on shared fences with neighbors\n\nPortland's position is that **the city does not get involved in shared-fence disputes**. The city enforces zoning (height, location, setback) and building code (structural safety); everything else is between you and your neighbor.\n\nThat means:\n\n- Neither of you is legally obligated to share the cost of building or replacing a fence on your property line\n- Neither of you can force the other to allow access to their side for installation or maintenance\n- If a fence sits exactly on the property line, both households share ownership and either can act on it (which can get messy)\n- Encroachment (a fence that's a few inches over the line) is a civil property issue, not a city issue\n\nThe friendly route: a written agreement before you build, even a one-page email confirming who pays what and where the fence sits.\n\n---\n\n## What a typical 6-foot back/side fence costs and takes in Portland\n\nFor a roughly **100 linear feet** (the side and back of a typical 5,000-square-foot lot like yours) **6-foot cedar privacy fence**:\n\n- **Contractor-installed**: $4,000\u2013$8,000 total, depending on whether you're getting basic or premium grade. That's about the cost of a decent used car. For just side and back of your lot (call it 100\u2013120 feet), $5,000\u2013$6,500 is a fair midrange Portland quote in 2026; significantly higher than that and you're paying for premium materials or an expensive contractor.\n- **DIY materials only**: $1,500\u2013$3,000. About 2\u20134 weekends of evenings and Saturdays for someone who's reasonably handy and patient. First-time fence builders should plan for 4 weekends.\n- **Timeline if hiring**: book in late winter (February\u2013March) for a spring install; expect 4\u20138 weeks of contractor wait time in May\u2013August, 2\u20133 weeks November\u2013February.\n- **Cheapest month to build**: November through February, after the rainy ground softens for digging but before the spring rush. Wood prices also tend to be lower late-fall.\n- **Most expensive month**: June\u2013July, peak demand, contractors at capacity.\n\n---\n\n## 10. Glossary\n\n**BDS / PP&D** \u2014 Bureau of Development Services, renamed in 2023 to Portland Permitting & Development. Same office, handles building permits and zoning questions. Phone: 503-823-7300.\n\n**PBOT** \u2014 Portland Bureau of Transportation. Owns and manages streets, sidewalks, and the right-of-way (the city-owned strip between the sidewalk and the street). Phone for right-of-way questions: 503-823-7002.\n\n**Urban Forestry** \u2014 A division of Portland Parks & Recreation that regulates trees on public property and on private property over a certain size. Phone: 503-823-8733.\n\n**PCC** \u2014 Portland City Code. The city's complete rulebook, organized by Title (broad subject) and section (specific rule). \"PCC 33.110.275\" means Title 33, Chapter 110, Section 275.\n\n**Setback** \u2014 How far inside your property line a structure has to sit. The \"front building setback\" is the strip of yard between your front property line and where your house can legally start; in R5 zones, it's 10 feet.\n\n**Right-of-way (ROW)** \u2014 The strip of land owned by the city for streets, sidewalks, and utilities. It usually includes the sidewalk and a planting strip on the house side. You can't build permanent structures here without special permission.\n\n**Planting strip** \u2014 Common name for the part of the right-of-way between the sidewalk and the street (or sometimes between the sidewalk and your front property line). City-owned; you maintain it but can't build on it.\n\n**Lot line / property line** \u2014 The legal boundary of your property. Almost never the same as the edge of the sidewalk.\n\n**Zoning overlay** \u2014 An extra layer of rules added on top of your base zone (in your case, R5). Your one overlay is \"h\" (Aircraft Landing), which has no effect on residential fences.\n\n**Base zone** \u2014 Your primary zone designation, which determines most of the rules for what can be built. Yours is R5, single-family residential.\n\n**Plan district / historic district / conservation district** \u2014 Special districts that overlay extra design rules on top of base zoning. Your property has none of these, which is why standard R5 rules apply cleanly.\n\n**Vision clearance** \u2014 City rules requiring sight visibility at intersections and driveways. The hard rules apply at street corners; common-sense visibility applies at private driveways.\n\n**Engineering / engineered design** \u2014 A drawing stamped by a structural engineer licensed in Oregon. Required for any fence taller than 8 feet and for some unusual designs (heavy masonry, fences on retaining walls). Adds $300\u2013$800 to a project.\n\n---\n\nIf you want me to draft your site plan sketch (the simple diagram PP&D wants if you do end up needing a permit), I can walk you through that next; it's basically a top-down drawing of your lot with the fence line, distances to property lines, and the house labeled.",
