      "enrichedQuestion": "I live at 3220 NE 33rd Ave, Portland, OR 97212, and I want to know the maximum fence height allowed on my property \u2014 front yard, back yard, and side yard \u2014 and whether there's any setback requirement (how far the fence has to sit from my property line, the sidewalk, or the street). I also want to know if I need a permit before I build or replace a fence, and whether anything about my specific property or neighborhood would change the answer.\n\nPlease write your answer for a regular Portland homeowner with no background in city code, zoning, or permitting. Aim for an 8th-to-10th grade reading level. Treat me as smart but unfamiliar with how the city works. Use everyday words wherever possible \u2014 say \"how far the fence has to sit back from the property line\" before you say \"setback,\" and \"the part of your yard between the house and the street\" before \"front setback area.\" If you would not use a word in conversation with a neighbor over the fence, define it the first time you use it. Keep paragraphs short. Use bolded keywords inside sentences instead of dense tables. Only use a table if you're comparing three or more fence locations on the same dimensions, and put a one-sentence plain-English summary above the table. Do not use words like \"shall,\" \"promulgated,\" or \"thereunder.\"\n\nPlease structure your answer this way:\n\n1. **Lead with a plain-English summary (3\u20135 sentences) that directly answers my question first.** No citations, no code numbers, no jargon in this opening \u2014 just tell me, in everyday language, what I can build in each part of my yard and whether I need a permit. I should be able to read only this paragraph and walk away knowing what to do.\n\n2. **Then give me the details, broken out by location:**\n   - **Front yard** (the part facing NE 33rd Ave): max height, any rules about how see-through it has to be, anything about corner-vision or sight-distance rules at intersections or driveways, and how close to the sidewalk or street it can sit.\n   - **Side yards** (between my house and the neighbors on either side): max height, and any rules about the part of the side yard that's in front of the house vs. behind it.\n   - **Back yard**: max height, and anything about alleys if there's one behind my property.\n   - For each, explain whether the fence material matters (solid wood vs. chain link vs. open lattice on top), and whether retaining walls or hedges count toward the height.\n\n3. **Tell me the zoning and any overlays for this specific address.** This property is in the Alameda neighborhood in Northeast Portland, which I believe is a single-family residential zone, but please confirm. Flag any historic district, conservation district, environmental overlay, or design overlay that could change the fence rules for my address \u2014 and tell me how to verify on PortlandMaps myself. If the zoning could be different from what I assume, say so up front.\n\n4. **Tell me which Portland City Code Titles govern this** \u2014 I understand fence rules are mostly in **Title 33 (Zoning Code)**, with possible cross-references to **Title 11 (Trees)** if a hedge or tree is involved, and **Title 24 (Building Regulations)** if the fence is tall enough to need a structural permit. Cite specific section numbers (for example, \"PCC 33.110.255\") in parentheses *after* the plain-English explanation, not in front of it. Every code citation should follow a sentence that already explained the rule in normal words.\n\n5. **Tell me clearly whether I need a permit, and what triggers one.** Specifically: at what fence height does a building permit kick in? Does replacing an existing fence in the same spot need a permit? Does a fence over a retaining wall change the rules? What about an electric fence, barbed wire, or a privacy fence with a lattice topper? If the permit rules depend on height, give me the height thresholds in plain language.\n\n6. **Give me a numbered \"what to do next\" list, in the exact order I should do it.** For each step, tell me:\n   - Who to contact (name the bureau and what they actually do \u2014 e.g., \"Bureau of Development Services, or BDS, which handles building permits and zoning questions\")\n   - The website, phone number, or counter to use\n   - What to bring or have ready (address, site plan sketch, property survey, fence height/material)\n   - Roughly what it costs (translate dollar amounts into something I can plan around, like \"about the cost of a nice dinner out\" or \"about a week's groceries\")\n   - Roughly how long it takes (e.g., \"one phone call, 15 minutes\" or \"about one weekend's worth of evenings to fill out\")\n   - Mark clearly which steps are **free**.\n\n7. **Give me a \"what to ask the city\" script** \u2014 the actual sentence or two I can read aloud on the phone or paste into an email to the bureau. Not just \"call BDS\" \u2014 write out the literal words: \"Hi, I own a home at 3220 NE 33rd Ave and I want to build a [X]-foot [material] fence in my [front/side/back] yard. Can you tell me\u2026\" Include the specific questions I should ask so I don't get bounced between departments.\n\n8. **Give me a \"common gotchas\" section in plain language** \u2014 the specific mistakes Portland homeowners make with fences. For example: building before checking the property line, assuming the sidewalk edge is the property line when it isn't, putting a tall fence too close to a driveway and blocking driver sight lines, removing a street tree thinking it's on their property, building a hedge that grows past the height limit, or not knowing the neighbor co-owns a shared fence. Tell me what to watch out for *before* I spend money or pour a post.\n\n9. **Friendly accuracy caveats.** Frame these as a friendly warning, not a legal disclaimer. For example: \"Zoning for your specific address can vary block by block \u2014 confirm on PortlandMaps (portlandmaps.com) before you spend money on materials or a contractor.\" Tell me what I should personally verify and where.\n\n10. **A glossary at the end** defining every acronym or technical term you used more than once: at minimum **BDS** (Bureau of Development Services), **PBOT** (Portland Bureau of Transportation), **Urban Forestry**, **PCC** (Portland City Code), **setback**, **right-of-way / ROW**, **zoning overlay**, **lot line**, and any others you introduced. One sentence each, plain English.\n\nA few extra things I'd find helpful but are easy to forget:\n- If my fence would sit anywhere near the sidewalk or street, tell me about the strip of city-owned land between the sidewalk and the street (sometimes called the **planting strip** or **right-of-way**) and whether I'm allowed to build on it. Name which bureau owns that question (PBOT, I think) and how to reach them.\n- If a tree is in the way \u2014 mine or a street tree \u2014 tell me what Urban Forestry's role is and whether I need their sign-off before digging post holes near roots.\n- If my neighbor and I are sharing a fence on the property line, mention briefly what Portland says about shared fences and what's a city issue vs. a private property-line issue between neighbors.\n- If there's anything seasonal (e.g., permits taking longer in summer, or tree-root rules being stricter in certain months), flag it.\n- Tell me what a reasonable total cost and timeline looks like for a typical 6-foot backyard fence in Portland \u2014 translated into everyday terms (\"about the cost of a used car,\" \"roughly one summer's worth of weekends\") \u2014 so I know if a contractor's quote is reasonable.\n\nPlease confirm at the top of your answer whether you were able to look up the actual zoning for 3220 NE 33rd Ave, or whether you're answering based on the typical zoning for the Alameda neighborhood. If you couldn't pull address-specific data, say so plainly and tell me how to check it myself in under five minutes on PortlandMaps."
