        "response": "For your address, there's a quick online path and a formal records request path; for a home on SE Ladd Ave you'll probably want both, plus some bonus resources I'll get to in a moment.\n\n**The quick path: PortlandMaps**\n\nGo to portlandmaps.com, search 1719 SE Ladd Ave, click into the property, then open the **Permits & Zoning** section. You'll see active and historical building, trade, land use, and code enforcement records from roughly 2000 to today. There's also a **Historic Permits** subsection that often has scanned older records, and a **Historic Plumbing** section worth checking (it can document original sewer connections and even cesspool records). For any permit issued after June 1, 2012, the actual plans and applications are viewable for free; you just need a free City of Portland account.\n\n**The formal path: Public Records Request**\n\nFor anything older than what shows up on PortlandMaps (especially permits issued before mid-2012), submit a Public Records Request through Portland Permitting & Development at portland.gov/ppd/public-records. They use a GovQA portal. Have the property address and the Property ID ready (the \"R Number\" from PortlandMaps' Assessor Detail). They'll respond within five business days about scope and any fees.\n\nFor active code-enforcement cases, call the Property Compliance Help Line at 503-823-2633.\n\n**One thing worth flagging**\n\n1719 SE Ladd Ave sits inside Ladd's Addition, which became one of Portland's first Historic Conservation Districts in 1977 and was added to the National Register of Historic Places in 1988. That has real implications: any exterior alteration visible from the street (doors, windows, roofs, similar character-defining elements) typically triggers Historic Resource Review, with its own forms, fees, and timeline. If the records pull is part of planning a project, factor that in early; rear or non-character-defining work usually has more flexibility.\n\n**The deeper path (since you live in one of the most documented neighborhoods in Oregon)**\n\nMost Ladd's Addition houses were built between 1905 and 1930, and the neighborhood is unusually well-archived. Permits are just one slice. A few resources that go well beyond the city records:\n\n- **Historic Resource Inventory of Portland (1984)**, held at the Oregon Historical Society research library. Arranged by street address; each listed building gets legal description, date built, architectural style, and first owner. Ladd's is heavily represented.\n- **Digital Sanborn Maps, 1867 to 1970**, free with a Multnomah County Library card via multcolib.org. Shows your home's footprint, construction materials, and number of stories at multiple points in time. Sheets 701 to 799 of the original Portland atlases cover East Portland and Ladd's Addition specifically.\n- **Portland City Directories** (Multnomah County Library and OHS). Pre-internet phone books; you can trace who lived at 1719 SE Ladd Ave year by year for over a century, often with their occupations and workplaces.\n- **Multnomah County Assessment & Taxation**, 501 SE Hawthorne Blvd, Suite 175. They keep microfilm with construction date and ownership history; bring the exact address.\n- **Architectural Heritage Center** (visitahc.org). Portland-specific research archive with photographs, ephemera, and an extensive list of online databases curated for this exact use case.\n- **Oregon Historic Sites Database** via SHPO (heritagedata.prd.state.or.us). Worth checking whether your specific house has its own record beyond just being a contributing property in the district.\n- **Block Book of Portland (1907)** at OHS. Documents land ownership at a snapshot during the early build-out of the neighborhood.\n\nA couple of evenings with the Sanborns, a city directory or two, and the Historic Resource Inventory will usually let you piece together who built the house, who lived in it through each decade, what construction materials and additions show up over time, and how the lot evolved. For a Ladd's home specifically, the trail tends to be unusually rich.\n\nAll of the above are official government or established nonprofit archives; nothing requires paying a third-party \"house history\" service, which is good because most of those just resell what the libraries above offer for free.",
