        "response": "Let me actually pull your property's records right now rather than just describing the process \u2014 Portland has a lot of this online already.Now let me verify the current Portland process for requesting older records \u2014 the digital trail here only goes back to 2004 but the house was built in 1911.Good news: I went ahead and pulled them for you. Here's what's already sitting in the digital record on PortlandMaps, plus the formal process for everything else.\n\n## What's already online (free, no request needed)\n\nThe City has 6 permits on file digitally for R200340 / 1S1E02CA 3100:\n\n| Year | Permit # | Type | Description | Status |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 2019 | 2019-242222-ET | Electrical | 20-space 100A sub in garage + NEMA 14-50 (EV outlet) | Final approved |\n| 2014 | 2014-198902-ET | Electrical | \"MOD 3 CIR\" | **VOID** |\n| 2014 | 2014-197300-MT | Mechanical | Install gas furnace + add A/C | **VOID** |\n| 2013 | 2013-209630-PT | Plumbing | Inside sewer line connection | Final approved |\n| 2013 | 2013-206680-PT | Plumbing | Sewer service line repair, ~40 ft on property | Final approved |\n| 2004 | 2004-020466-PT | Plumbing | 60 ft water service + 2 backflow preventers | Final approved |\n\nTwo flags worth noting from your own records: the **2014 furnace/AC permit and the 2014 electrical mod are both VOID**, meaning they were issued but not finaled. If that gas furnace or AC actually got installed, you'd have unpermitted work on the books; if they were just abandoned applications and nothing happened, no problem. Worth verifying against what's physically in the house.\n\nThere's also a **scanned Historic Plumbing Permit** (\u224850 KB document, ID 654019) attached to the property. For a 1911 house this is the goldmine record: it typically lists the original sewer/cesspool connection date, the original property owner, and pre-1931 address (Portland renumbered every address in 1931). To grab it: go to portlandmaps.com, search the address, expand Permits & Zoning \u2192 Historic Plumbing, sign in with a free City of Portland account, and download.\n\n## The formal request for everything else\n\nFor permits **before 2012** (beyond the historic plumbing scan), and any plans/drawings the City still has, you file a Public Records Request with Portland Permitting & Development:\n\n1. Go to portland.gov/ppd/public-records and create a free account at the request portal\n2. Submit a Records Request \u2192 Public Records Request \u2192 Type: Public \u2192 Service area: Community and Economic Development \u2192 Bureau: Permitting and Development\n3. Pay the **$8 minimum fee per address** (charged at submission, doesn't guarantee they find anything)\n4. Expect **2+ weeks** turnaround\n\nPhone: 503-823-7300 (M\u2013F 8a\u20135p). The Permit Center at 1900 SW 4th Ave also takes 15-min in-person research appointments Tue/Thu 8a\u20134p, which is honestly faster for one address than waiting on a written request.\n\n## What PPD won't have (and you'll probably want)\n\nPPD's records start fading well before 1911. The original 1911 building permit, if it survived, lives at the **Portland Archives & Records Center (PARC)**, run by the City Auditor \u2014 separate bureau, separate request system, much deeper holdings:\n\n- 1800 SW 6th Ave, Suite 550 (PSU campus). Appointment only: Tue/Thu 12\u20134p, Wed 9a\u20131p\n- parc@portlandoregon.gov / 503-865-4100\n- Free hi-res scans, up to 20 items per remote request via their PARC Records Request form\n- They also have the 1863\u20131986 Portland City Directories \u2014 useful for tracing every occupant of your house by year\n\n## Bonus context, since it's a 1911 Ladd's Addition house\n\nA couple things worth knowing that go beyond the records question:\n\n**Ladd's Addition is a National Register Historic District.** Your legal description (\"LADDS ADD, BLOCK 12, LOT 22\") confirms it. This matters for future permits: any exterior change visible from the street usually triggers a Historic Resource Review through PP&D's Land Use Services, and the Historic Landmarks Commission meets the 2nd and 4th Monday of each month. Worth knowing before you plan windows, siding, roofing, or anything in the front yard. Your zoning is R5 (Single-Dwelling 5,000).\n\n**For a 1911 house, three non-City sources fill in what permits won't tell you:**\n\n- **Sanborn Fire Insurance Maps** (1908, 1924, 1928 editions cover Ladd's Addition) \u2014 these are essentially scaled floor-plan footprints showing building shape, materials, and outbuildings at specific points in time. Free at the Multnomah County Library or Library of Congress online.\n- **Oregon Historical Society research library** has the 1907 Portland Block Book and 1914/1922/1928 Portland Realty Atlases \u2014 ownership snapshots. Free to use.\n- **Multnomah County Library's NewsBank database** (free with library card) has the digitized Oregonian back to 1861. Searching the original owner name from your historic plumbing scan often surfaces the build announcement, sometimes the architect, and obituaries that explain what happened to the house across owners.\n\nIf you want, I can also pull the sewer as-builts for your block (the 1913 Plumbing Permit referenced an inside sewer line, and the original cesspool may still be referenced in the connection record), or check whether your address falls inside any environmental hazard overlays. Both are one query away.",
