        "response": "# Building Records Request Guide: 1719 SE Ladd Ave, Portland, OR 97214\n\nA homeowner-friendly, citation-rich playbook for pulling permit, plan, sewer, and historic-resource records on this property.\n\n> **Accuracy caveat up front.** This guide reflects the post-reorganization Portland system. The Bureau of Development Services (BDS) was phased out and replaced by **Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D)** effective June 1, 2024 (Ordinance creating PP&D was passed May 2024; PP&D absorbed development-review functions from PBOT, BES, Water, Parks, Urban Forestry). Some old links still say `portlandoregon.gov/bds/...` and that's normal; redirects mostly work, but the bureau name to use today is PP&D. I've flagged anything where this transition matters.\n\n---\n\n## What I already pulled for your specific property\n\nBefore you spend a dime on a records request, here's what I retrieved from PortlandMaps' API for this exact address (`Property ID R200340`, `State ID 1S1E02CA 3100`, Tax Lot 22 Block 12 of Ladd's Addition):\n\n### Property baseline\n- **Year built:** 1911 (assessor) / 1910 (Oregon SHPO record). One-year discrepancies are common; SHPO is usually the more historically accurate source.\n- **Square feet:** 2,192 (assessor) / 2,974 (recent MLS listing). The assessor undercount is typical for older homes with finished basements or upper-floor space the county hasn't recaptured.\n- **Zoning:** R5 (Residential 5,000) base zone. No overlay zones detected (no design-overlay, no environmental, no plan-district).\n- **Historic district:** **Ladd's Addition Historic District (code \"LA\")** \u2014 a National Register Historic District since 1988, and one of Portland's earliest residential historic districts (originally a Conservation District designated 1977, later upgraded).\n- **Historic resource classification:** **Contributing.** This is the key piece for renovation planning. Contributing status means the house meaningfully reinforces the district's historic character, and exterior alterations get more scrutiny than for non-contributing structures.\n- **Historic resource name on file with Oregon SHPO:** **\"North, H.R., Residence.\"** SHPO record number 49624, viewable in the Oregon Historic Sites Database (heritagedata.prd.state.or.us/historic \u2014 search by address).\n- **Council District:** 3\n- **Most recent recorded sale:** 8/4/2025 for $1,000,000\n\n### Permit history I pulled (6 records, all that exist in PP&D's database)\n| Year | App # | Type | Description | Status |\n|------|-------|------|-------------|--------|\n| 2004 | 2004-020466-PT | Plumbing | 60 ft water service + 2 backflow preventers | **Final approved** |\n| 2013 | 2013-206680-PT | Plumbing | Sewer service line repair, ~40 ft, on property only | **Final approved** |\n| 2013 | 2013-209630-PT | Plumbing | Inside sewer line connection | **Final approved** |\n| 2014 | 2014-197300-MT | Mechanical | Install gas furnace + add A/C | **VOID** \u26a0\ufe0f |\n| 2014 | 2014-198902-ET | Electrical | Modify 3 circuits | **VOID** \u26a0\ufe0f |\n| 2019 | 2019-242222-ET | Electrical | 100A subpanel in garage + NEMA 14-50 receptacle (EV outlet) | **Final approved** |\n\n**Two flags worth investigating:** the 2014 furnace/AC install and the 2014 electrical circuit work both went to **VOID** status. \"Void\" can mean the application was abandoned before issuance, or the permit lapsed. If the MLS listing's mention of \"central air conditioning\" reflects work that actually got installed, it may have been done under different permits later, or it may be unpermitted. **Worth checking** before you do any related work, because the electrical void in particular sat next to live circuits.\n\n### Sewer findings\n- Your property connects to a **combined sewer** (sanitary + stormwater in the same main) along SE Ladd Ave; the nearest manhole assets reference Job 6069 (\"SE Maple Ave / Mulberry Ave btwn 12th / 16th \u2014 Alder Basin\"), Job 20151 (\"Ladd's Addition\"), and Job E10368 (\"Sunnyside South & Ladd's Add Recon & GS\").\n- **Historic sewer boards** exist as scanned files for your quarter sections (3231 and 3232) \u2014 both BES Sewer Boards and pre-1980 PBOT/Maintenance Operations Sewer Boards. These are exactly the \"sewer cards\" people refer to and they're already digitized; you can view them via PortlandMaps under Utilities \u2192 Sewer & Environmental \u2192 Sewer Assets.\n- **No sewer easements** burden your taxlot.\n\n### What's *not* on file\n- **No active or historical Land Use Review (LUR) cases** on this taxlot. That means no Historic Resource Review files, no Type II/III land use decisions specific to your property are sitting at PP&D for retrieval. (The current owner since 1990s-or-earlier has not done anything that triggered formal land-use review; alterations were either exempt or done with trade permits only.)\n- **No code enforcement cases** visible in PortlandMaps.\n\n### Why this matters for your records request strategy\nMost of what you'd typically pay for in a records request \u2014 permit history, sewer records, zoning info, historic district status \u2014 is **already free on PortlandMaps** for this property. The records request becomes valuable mainly for: (a) pre-1990s plumbing/sewer records not yet scanned, (b) any drawings or plans submitted with the older permits, (c) original Certificate of Occupancy if one exists for a 1911 build (unlikely; see below), and (d) anything from the void 2014 permits to understand what happened.\n\n---\n\n## 1. The actual records request process (current, as of 2026)\n\nStep-by-step, in the order you should do them:\n\n### Step 1 \u2014 PortlandMaps first (free)\nGo to **portlandmaps.com**, search the address, and explore these panels:\n\n- **Permits & Zoning \u2192 Permits.** Lists all permits (the 6 you saw above for this property). Each Application Number is clickable for activity logs and inspection results.\n- **Permits & Zoning \u2192 Permits, Land Use & Code Enforcement \u2192 Historic Plumbing.** This is the section that shows scanned old plumbing/sewer-connection cards if they exist.\n- **Utilities \u2192 Sewer & Environmental \u2192 Sewer Assets.** Shows pipes, manholes, lateral connections, plus links to historic sewer boards (the scanned PDFs/JPEGs for your quarter section).\n- **Permits & Zoning \u2192 Zoning & Districts.** Confirms historic district + base zone. Click \"More\" to see the SHPO link.\n\nFor permits issued **June 1, 2012 through December 2023**, the actual scanned plans and applications are also viewable for free on PortlandMaps. (For your property the only permit in that window with potentially-attached docs is the 2013 sewer pair and the 2019 EV outlet permit. The 2004 permit predates this window and would need a request.)\n\n### Step 2 \u2014 eFiles for older or active land use cases\n**efiles.portlandoregon.gov/Search.** This is the City Auditor's Efiles system. Useful for:\n- Completed land use decisions from 2017, and 2020\u2013present (search by case number like `21-001350 LU`)\n- City ordinances and historical city records\n- *You don't have any LUR cases here, so this is mostly informational for context if a neighbor has a relevant file.*\n\n### Step 3 \u2014 Plumbing Permits and Code Appeals search (legacy database)\n**portlandoregon.gov/bds/plumbing_permits/** \u2014 old database (still online despite the BDS name in the URL). Searches the full plumbing permit history including pre-2003 building, electrical, mechanical, and plumbing **code appeals**. Worth a quick search if you suspect any code appeals were filed historically on this property.\n\n### Step 4 \u2014 Formal records request (only if Steps 1\u20133 didn't get you what you need)\nUse the **Portland Public Records Request portal**: **portlandor.govqa.us/WEBAPP/_rs/supporthome.aspx**\n\nProcess:\n1. Create a free GovQA account (or log in if you have one).\n2. Records Request Center \u2192 \"Submit a Records Request\" \u2192 \"Public Records Request.\"\n3. Type of Requester = **Public**.\n4. Service Area = **Community and Economic Development**.\n5. Bureau = **Permitting and Development**.\n6. Describe what you want as specifically as possible (give the IVR numbers if you have them; you do, from the table above).\n7. Pay the **$8 minimum per address** research fee at submission.\n\nBackup paper path if the portal doesn't work: mail a completed **Uniform Public Records Request form** plus a **Copyright Indemnification form** (required because plans may be copyrighted by the original architect/draftsperson and the City must be indemnified) to:\n\n> Public Records Coordinator\n> Portland Permitting & Development\n> 1900 SW 4th Avenue, Suite 5000\n> Portland, OR 97201\n\n### Step 5 \u2014 Specialty paths for specific record types\n- **Open code-enforcement / property-compliance cases:** call **503-823-2633** (Property Compliance Help Line) for active cases; submit a records request for closed ones. PP&D's Property Compliance Division maintains these.\n- **Sewer records (BES-side):** most are already on PortlandMaps; for septic system records (relevant only on the small number of Multnomah County properties not on city sewer; not yours), submit a records request to PP&D, which now holds septic records.\n- **Liquor / cannabis:** not applicable to a single-family home.\n- **State Historic Preservation Office records (the H.R. North Residence file):** see Section 3.\n\n### What's free online vs. what needs a formal request\n| Available free on PortlandMaps / eFiles | Requires formal records request ($8 min) |\n|------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|\n| Permit list, status, inspection results (yours: 6 permits since 2004) | Plans/drawings for permits **before June 1, 2012** |\n| Permit plans & applications **June 2012 \u2013 Dec 2023** | Plans/applications for permits **after Dec 2023** (per current PP&D backlog notice) |\n| Historic plumbing cards (scanned, for many older properties) | Pre-digitization records that haven't been scanned (often microfiche or off-site) |\n| Sewer assets, historic sewer boards by quarter section | Septic records (rare, not yours) |\n| Zoning, overlays, historic district | Records about closed code enforcement |\n| Land use decisions 2017, 2020\u2013present in eFiles | Aggregated permit data older than Oct 2021 |\n\n---\n\n## 2. What records actually exist and where (for a Ladd's Addition home)\n\n### Permit history (building, electrical, plumbing, mechanical)\nAlready covered above. Yours is clean except the two void 2014 permits. PP&D's permit database starts comprehensively in the late 1990s; gaps before that are normal. Trade-permit codes you'll see on Portland records:\n- **`-PT`** = Plumbing Trade\n- **`-ET`** = Electrical Trade\n- **`-MT`** = Mechanical Trade\n- **`-BT`** = Building Trade (no examples on your property)\n- **`-LU`** = Land Use Review\n\n### Original building plans / drawings / blueprints\n**For a 1911 home, plans are usually not in city files.** The City's plan retention practices weren't standardized until much later, and a one- or two-family dwelling permit in 1911 typically generated only a brief permit card with no architectural drawings retained. **Realistic expectation:** do not expect to find blueprints for the original construction. If anything exists it'd be:\n- A scanned permit card (one or two pages, basic data)\n- Possibly later as-builts from major remodels (none on your property)\n\nBetter sources for original drawings of homes like this: the **Architectural Heritage Center** in Portland (private archive), the **Oregon Historical Society Research Library**, and the **University of Oregon Special Collections** (which holds many Portland architects' papers). The H.R. North Residence isn't a known signature commission, so the chance of plans surviving privately is low but not zero.\n\n### Inspection records and Certificates of Occupancy\n- **Inspection records** are tied to each permit and visible on PortlandMaps. For your 6 permits, you can already see \"Final Inspection Approved\" status. To get inspector notes/details, request the file.\n- **Certificate of Occupancy:** Modern COs are issued for new construction or change-of-use under PP&D's Residential CO Program Guide. **A 1911 single-family home would not have a Certificate of Occupancy on file.** That program didn't exist for ordinary residential construction at the time. Don't waste a records request asking for one unless a major change-of-use happened later (and yours hasn't).\n\n### Sewer connection / plumbing records (Title 25)\n- Active records: PortlandMaps Sewer Assets panel.\n- Historic sewer boards (the \"sewer cards\"): already scanned for quarter sections 3231/3232 \u2014 accessible from PortlandMaps directly. Look for `BES Sewer Boards` and `PBOT/MO Sewer Boards (Pre 1980)` file links.\n- **Title 25** of Portland City Code (Plumbing Regulations) governs current plumbing work; legacy records are held by PP&D.\n- **PCC Chapter 17.32** is the BES sewer-connection chapter; it governs how connections are made today. **ENB-4.17** is the BES administrative rule for sewer connection and lateral repair permitting.\n\n### Electrical permit history (Title 26)\n- All electrical permits are in the PortlandMaps permit list (your `-ET` permits).\n- **Title 26** of Portland City Code (Electrical Regulations) adopts the Oregon Electrical Specialty Code.\n- For pre-2003 electrical code appeals: use the legacy Plumbing Permits and Building Code Appeals search.\n\n### Open or expired permits, code violations, unresolved cases\n- **PortlandMaps Permits panel** flags any non-final permits.\n- For your property, the two 2014 voids are expired/abandoned, not \"open\" in the active sense. There are **no open code enforcement cases** I can see.\n- For active code-enforcement details: Property Compliance Help Line **503-823-2633**.\n- **PCC Title 29** (Property Maintenance Regulations) is the basis for most non-zoning enforcement actions if any ever come up.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Historic district considerations (this is the big one)\n\n### What you're actually subject to\nLadd's Addition is governed by **PCC Chapter 33.445 (Historic Resource Overlay Zone)** with review procedures in **PCC Chapter 33.846 (Historic Resource Reviews)** and underlying procedures in **PCC Chapter 33.730**. Because your property is **Contributing** to the Historic District, here's the practical layered framework:\n\n- **Exempt work** (no historic resource review needed): interior remodels (with no exterior visibility), fences, low decks, roof vents that meet specific standards, and most \"no exterior change\" projects. See **33.445.320.B** for the complete exemption list and **33.445.320.B.11** for solar panels.\n- **Community Design Standards path** (objective standards, no discretionary review): set out in **33.445.620 / .640**. Faster, cheaper, but the project must fit predefined boxes.\n- **Historic Resource Review** (discretionary, Type II/III procedure): when your project doesn't qualify for an exemption or the Community Design Standards. This is the path that generates the case files you asked about. Procedures: **33.730** (general land-use procedures) and **33.846** (HRR-specific).\n- **Demolition Review:** mandatory for demolition of a contributing resource per **33.445.330**. Non-trivially, \"demolition\" can include large-scale removal even if a structure remains; check the definition in **33.910** and the demolition-delay rules.\n- **Design Guidelines** that apply to projects requiring HRR: the **\"Ladd's Addition Conservation District Design Guidelines (1990)\"** \u2014 note the historical-quirk filename, since the area was originally a Conservation District before being designated a National Register Historic District in 1988. The 1990 guidelines remain the governing design guideline document.\n\n### Records this generates\nFor your specific property, no LUR cases exist (confirmed), so there are no Historic Resource Review files specific to your address. If you plan a project requiring HRR, the case file gets created at that point and lives in eFiles once decided.\n\n### What's at the City vs. at SHPO\n- **City of Portland (PP&D / BPS):** zoning maps, the historic district designation ordinance, current overlay-zone records, any HRR / demolition review case files, current Historic Resource Inventory listings.\n- **Oregon SHPO (State Historic Preservation Office, part of Oregon Parks and Recreation Department / Oregon Heritage):** the **Oregon Historic Sites Database** including the \"H.R. North Residence\" record (#49624) for your property, the National Register nomination file for **Ladd's Addition Historic District as a whole** (1988 nomination), Reconnaissance/Intensive Level Survey forms, federal and state tax incentive case files (if any historic rehabilitation tax credit was ever taken on this property).\n- **National Park Service (federal):** the National Register listing itself.\n\n### How to request SHPO records\nMost SHPO information is online at **heritagedata.prd.state.or.us/historic** (free, no login needed). For records beyond what's online \u2014 original 1988 district nomination forms, individual Historic Resource Record forms \u2014 contact:\n> Oregon SHPO\n> National Register Program: ORSHPO.NationalRegisterProgram@oprd.oregon.gov\n> 725 Summer St NE, Suite C, Salem, OR 97301\n> 503-986-0690 (general SHPO line)\n\n### A renovation-specific surprise\nBecause your property is a **Contributing resource in a National Register Historic District**, you may be eligible for the **Oregon Special Assessment of Historic Property** program (a property-tax freeze for qualifying rehabilitation) and the **federal 20% Historic Rehabilitation Tax Credit** if you ever do an income-producing rehabilitation (e.g., the home becomes a rental or short-term rental, with limits). Both are administered through SHPO. Worth a phone call to SHPO if a major rehab is on your horizon.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Specific code citations (with plain-language meaning)\n\n| Citation | What it covers | What it means for you |\n|---|---|---|\n| **PCC Title 24** (Building Regulations) | Adopts Oregon Structural & Residential Specialty Codes by reference; defines permit requirements; sets up PP&D's enforcement authority. **24.10** is administration/enforcement. | The framework for any structural/building permit; sets out when you do or don't need a permit. |\n| **PCC Title 25** (Plumbing Regulations) | Adopts Oregon Plumbing Specialty Code; governs water, drain-waste-vent, sewer connections on private property. | Anything wet inside your foundation footprint. Your 2004 water service and 2013 sewer permits live here. |\n| **PCC Title 26** (Electrical Regulations) | Adopts Oregon Electrical Specialty Code. | All wiring, panels, EV outlets. Your 2019 garage subpanel + EV outlet falls here. |\n| **PCC Title 27** (Heating and Ventilating Regulations) | Adopts Oregon Mechanical Specialty Code. | Furnaces, AC, ductwork, vents. Your 2014 voided furnace/AC permit was here. |\n| **PCC Title 29** (Property Maintenance) | Minimum residential maintenance standards; basis for Property Compliance enforcement. | If a neighbor complains or an inspector cites you, this is usually the cited title. |\n| **PCC Title 33** (Planning and Zoning) | Zoning code; overlays; land-use procedures. | Sets your R5 zoning, the LA historic district, what reviews any project triggers. |\n| **PCC 33.445** (Historic Resource Overlay Zone) | Definitions of historic resources, when HRR is required, exemptions, demolition rules. | Your day-to-day historic-district rules. |\n| **PCC 33.445.320** | Specifically: when historic resource review is required in a Historic District; exemptions. | The lookup table for \"do I need to apply for review for this project?\" |\n| **PCC 33.445.330** | Demolition review for contributing resources. | If you ever consider a demo or major removal, you must go through this. |\n| **PCC 33.730** | General Type I/II/III/IV land use procedures. | The procedural mechanics when something needs review (notice, comment, decision). |\n| **PCC 33.846** | Historic Resource Reviews (the application-side rules). | What you submit, what gets evaluated, what the criteria are. |\n| **PCC 33.910** | Definitions used throughout Title 33. | Defines \"Contributing,\" \"Historic District,\" \"Demolition,\" etc. |\n| **PCC Chapter 17.32** | Public sewer/drainage permits, connections, maintenance. | If you ever need to repair a lateral or connect to a main, this and ENB-4.17 apply. |\n| **ENB-4.17** | BES administrative rule: sewer connection and lateral repair permitting. | Day-to-day sewer permitting rule (UC and UR permits). |\n| **ORS 192** (specifically ORS 192.311\u2013192.478) | Oregon Public Records Law. | The legal basis for the records request itself. **ORS 192.355(4)** allows the City to keep some confidentiality (e.g., complainant identity in code-enforcement cases). |\n| **ORS 358.475\u2013358.545** | Oregon historic-property special assessment statute. | The state property-tax-freeze program for rehabilitated historic property. Administered by SHPO. |\n\n---\n\n## 5. Costs and timeline\n\n### Fees (PP&D records, current)\n- **$8 minimum research fee per address.** Required at submission, non-refundable, doesn't guarantee records will be found. Source: PP&D Public Records page.\n- **Additional fees beyond the $8** if the search/review is complex; PP&D estimates and asks for your agreement before doing extra work.\n- **Paper-copy printing costs** if you request mail delivery or paper output.\n- **No fee** for a sewer-access permit (different thing; mentioned only because you might see it referenced).\n\n### Timeline\n- PP&D currently warns: **\"two weeks or more\"** for building permit records due to staffing and backlog. Realistic expectation for a property like yours: 2\u20136 weeks.\n- For a Ladd's Addition contributing property where some records may be on microfiche or off-site, lean toward the longer end.\n- **No formal expedited option** for records requests like this. PP&D does have an **Applicant Paid Overtime** option for plan review (not records requests), where you pay reviewer overtime; it's not for getting old records faster.\n- **State law clock:** ORS 192.329 requires \"as soon as practicable and without unreasonable delay.\" There's no hard SLA, but the City must acknowledge within 5 business days.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Common gotchas Portland homeowners miss\n\n1. **\"The absence of a record is not proof work was permitted.\"** Your records will only show what the City has. Old work done without permits leaves no paper trail. The reverse is also true: a missing permit doesn't mean work was illegal; for a 1911 home, lots of pre-modern wiring/plumbing was installed before permits even existed in their current form.\n2. **Pre-1970s drawings are usually missing.** The city's drawing retention is inconsistent before then. For your 1911 build, expect a permit card at most; expect no architectural drawings.\n3. **Microfiche/off-site delays.** For older permits not yet scanned, retrieval requires staff to physically pull microfiche or visit a warehouse; this is the source of long timelines.\n4. **\"Permit history\" \u2260 \"sewer card\" \u2260 \"plumbing record.\"** These are three different things; you may need to request all three:\n   - *Permit history* = the trade permits (PT/ET/MT/BT) for work done on the property.\n   - *Sewer card / sewer board* = the BES quarter-section diagram showing your sewer lateral connection point and any recorded changes; held by BES/PP&D and partially scanned on PortlandMaps.\n   - *Historic plumbing record* = older internal-plumbing permits/inspections, sometimes including original cesspool conversion records (Ladd's Addition was built in the cesspool era and converted in stages; original cesspool/septic-to-sewer conversion may be documented).\n5. **Void permits \u2260 no work was done.** Void status means the permit was never issued or lapsed; if work happened anyway, it's unpermitted. Your two 2014 voids are worth investigating before you do related work.\n6. **\"Historic Permits\" link on PortlandMaps.** This is where the older trade-permit cards appear; it's separate from the modern Permits panel. For a 1911 home, this is where your useful historical trail mostly lives. Click both panels.\n7. **Public Records Law vs. city procedures.** ORS 192 is the legal basis; the GovQA portal is a city procedural overlay. If the city won't release something they should under ORS 192, you can file a **petition for review with the District Attorney** (ORS 192.411). This rarely matters for routine permit records.\n8. **PP&D \u2260 BDS in URLs but \u2248 in practice.** Some forms still bear the BDS name. They still work. Use them.\n9. **Multnomah County also holds property records** (deed, easements, surveys) separate from the City. For a deep dive into what's recorded against title, you go to the County. Ladd's Addition platting documents from 1891 are at the County.\n10. **Lead and asbestos disclosures** for pre-1978 homes (yours, by 67 years) are state/federal not city; ask if you also want pointers there.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Who to contact\n\n| Need | Contact |\n|---|---|\n| **PortlandMaps lookup help** | portlandmaps.com (no contact needed); or 503-823-7300 (PP&D main) |\n| **Formal records request** | portlandor.govqa.us \u2014 online portal; or 503-823-7300; mail to Public Records Coordinator, PP&D, 1900 SW 4th Ave, Suite 5000, Portland OR 97201 |\n| **PP&D general** | 503-823-7300, M\u2013F 8am\u20135pm |\n| **Active code-enforcement / property compliance** | 503-823-2633 (Property Compliance Help Line) |\n| **Sewer / BES side records (if not on PortlandMaps)** | BES Development Services 503-823-7761 |\n| **Historic / land-use specific (15-min planner consult