n property and what my options are (legalization permits, \"code-comply\" permits, leaving it alone, disclosing at sale)\n   - Whether **Ladd's Addition** has any historic district or conservation overlay that affects records, plan availability, or what I can do to the house \u2014 Ladd's Addition is on the National Register, so call out anything historic-district-specific\n   - Whether my property's **zoning** (likely a residential zone in Southeast Portland) changes which records exist or where to look\n   - Cost and timeline implications: rough fees for records requests, plan copies, microfilm retrieval, and how long BDS typically takes\n   - Privacy and access \u2014 are building records public? Can a neighbor pull mine? Can I pull records on a house I'm thinking of buying?\n\n5. **A \"common gotchas\" section** for Portland homeowners pulling building records, in plain language. Things like: PortlandMaps not showing very old permits, microfilm being the only copy of pre-1990s plans, \"finalized\" not always meaning \"passed final inspection\", confusion between **address** and **tax lot ID**, and records being split across bureaus.\n\n6. **Specific code section numbers** for any rule you cite \u2014 but only as a parenthetical after the plain-English explanation, never as the lead. For example: \"The city has to keep building records and make them available to the public (Title 24, Portland City Code Chapter 24.10), and Oregon's public records law backs that up (ORS 192.311\u2013192.478).\" Cover the relevant Titles (likely **Title 24 Building Regulations**, **Title 33 Zoning Code** if historic-district records come up, and any administrative rules about records retention and public records requests).\n\n7. **Friendly accuracy warnings**, not legal disclaimers \u2014 for example: \"Permit records before the early 1990s may only exist on microfilm and can take longer to pull,\" or \"Always verify what you find on PortlandMaps against a formal BDS records request