 *\"detached uncovered vertical structure\"*; the same category as trellises and arbors. Lightly regulated. It does not count toward your building coverage (which only counts impervious overhead structures), and it does not count toward floor area ratio (FAR).\n\nA **covered pergola** (polycarbonate panels, fabric canopy, louvered aluminum that closes, shingled mini-roof) is a *\"detached covered accessory structure\"*; the same category as a shed or carport. It triggers building coverage and the 20-ft height cap, and you'll need to keep it inside the buildable area unless it qualifies for a setback exception.\n\nThis is the lever most homeowners don't realize they're pulling.\n\n## The permit-free thresholds (Oregon state code, applied by Portland)\n\nFor a freestanding pergola: no building permit if it's \u2264 200 sq ft and \u2264 15 ft tall.\n\nFor a pergola attached to your house and covering a patio: no building permit if it's \u2264 200 sq ft, average roof height \u2264 12 ft, and at least 3 ft from any property line.\n\n200 sq ft is roughly 14\u00d714 or 12\u00d716; plenty for a dining-and-lounging space. Important caveat: skipping the *building* permit doesn't skip *zoning*. Setbacks, building coverage, and FAR still apply, and you may still need a small zoning permit if the structure changes the building footprint.\n\n## Setbacks for your property\n\nR5 zone (the most common designation around your address) typically requires 10 ft front, 5 ft side, 5 ft rear for primary structures, and accessory structures can sometimes go closer to side and rear lot lines if certain conditions are met. R2.5 (also present in your area) is more permissive.\n\nA useful loophole: an *open* pergola counted as an \"uncovered vertical structure\" is allowed inside required building setbacks if it's no larger than 3 ft in width/depth and no taller than 8 ft. So a slim, traditional pergola can hug a fence line. Bigger than that and the full setback rules apply. There's also a specific carve-out allowing a single arbor up to 6 ft wide, 3 ft deep, and 8 ft tall in the front setback (probably not what you want, but good to know).\n\n## Your specific situation, things to flag\n\nYour lot is 4,792 sq ft, just under the 5,000 sq ft R5 standard, so the FAR math is tight. The 2022 listing for your home mentions a \"new backyard shed\" already on the property; that shed counts as an existing accessory structure and eats into both the 20% accessory-structure-coverage cap and your overall FAR allowance. Worth measuring before you size the pergola.\n\nAlso worth knowing: there's a one-time 250 sq ft FAR exception per 5-year period for properties whose primary structure passed final inspection at least 5 years ago. Your house was built in 1988, so this is available if you ever need it for something more substantial.\n\n## Verify your exact zoning before committing\n\nI tried to pull your zoning directly but couldn't reach the live data from where I sit. The two-click verification: go to **portlandmaps.com**, search \"4773 SE 52nd Ave\", and click \"Permits & Zoning\" \u2192 \"Zoning & Districts\". You're looking for the base zone (likely R5 or R2.5) and any overlay letters (like \"a\", \"d\", or others). Overlays can change setback or design rules. While you're there, also check for any environmental overlay (rare on this block but worth a glance) and any \"z\" constrained-sites overlay.\n\n## Above-and-beyond bits\n\n**Free 15-minute zoning consultation.** Portland Permitting & Development offers a free 15-minute appointment with a planner who can confirm your zoning, setbacks, and whether your specific design needs a permit. Call 503-823-7300 to schedule. This is the single highest-leverage thing you can do; it's free and will save you from any surprises. They'll also tell you whether your block has any plan-district quirks.\n\n**Design hack if you want maximum flexibility.** Build it open (no impervious roof). You get shade from rafter spacing, climbing plants, or a removable shade cloth, while the structure stays in the lightly-regulated category. You can always add a removable canopy later for events. This keeps it out of building-coverage and FAR math entirely.\n\n**HOA / CC&Rs.** Your property is in Mt. Scott-Arleta and doesn't appear to have an HOA based on typical patterns for that neighborhood, but check your title docs for any recorded covenants from the original 1988 subdivision. Permit-free at the city level doesn't mean permit-free at the deed level.\n\n**Practical sequence.** Verify zoning on PortlandMaps, measure existing shed footprint, sketch a 12\u00d716 or 14\u00d714 open pergola sited at least 5 ft from side/rear lot lines, then call PP&D for the free 15-min consult to confirm. If everything checks out, you can build without a building permit; just keep it open-roof and within the thresholds above.\n\nIf you want, share what PortlandMaps shows for the zoning and I can tighten the setback numbers and confirm the exact FAR/building-coverage math for your situation.",
