        "response": "I have everything I need. Let me build you a visual of your property with the buildable zone, then give you the full answer.Yes, you can put up a pergola. Your property is in good shape for it: zoned **R5 (Residential 5,000)**, no historic district, no overlay zones, no environmental constraints, no plan district. The path is clean. Here's what your lot looks like with the setbacks applied:## The rules, in plain English\n\n**Setbacks (how far from property lines):**\n- 10 ft from SE 52nd Ave (front)\n- 5 ft from each side property line\n- 5 ft from the rear property line\n\n**Do you need a building permit?** Probably not, if the pergola is:\n- 200 sqft or smaller in footprint, AND\n- 15 ft or shorter in height, AND\n- non-habitable and detached\n\nThat covers the typical 12\u00d716 or 10\u00d712 backyard pergola. Bigger or taller and you're into a building permit. Either way, you still need to obey the setbacks \u2014 the permit exemption and the zoning rules are separate things.\n\n**Important nuance most people miss: \"covered\" vs \"uncovered\" matters a lot.**\n\nA traditional pergola with an open-slat / lattice top is classified as a *detached uncovered vertical structure* (Portland code calls these \"trellises, arbors and other garden structures\"). A pergola with a solid roof, polycarbonate panels, or a fixed fabric canopy is treated as a *detached covered accessory structure* \u2014 stricter rules, more likely to count as impervious surface for stormwater. If you want the open beam look, you have more freedom. If you want shade you can sit under in a downpour, expect more scrutiny.\n\n## Things to check before you buy lumber\n\nA few items that aren't obvious from \"can I build a pergola\" but will save you headaches:\n\n**Your tree history.** A tree removal permit was applied for at this address in 2016 but expired without a final inspection (application 2016-176242). Portland's tree code (Title 11) requires lots to maintain a minimum tree density and treats removed-but-not-replaced trees as an outstanding obligation. If you dig footings near where a tree used to be, or the pergola location intersects an existing tree's root protection zone, that record could resurface. Worth a 5-minute phone call to Urban Forestry (503-823-8733) to see if anything's still flagged before you commit to a location.\n\n**Building coverage and FAR.** Your house is 810 sqft on a 4,792 sqft lot \u2014 comfortably under R5's caps. A pergola with an open top doesn't add to building coverage (no impervious roof), but a solid-roofed one would. You're nowhere near limits either way.\n\n**Soil and anchoring.** Portland Maps shows your soil as well-drained, hydrologic group B, with bedrock at 6 ft. Translation: standard concrete pier footings (think Sonotube + post anchor) will work fine. No special engineering needed for a typical pergola.\n\n**Stormwater.** You're in the Taggart B/C combined sewer basin. An open pergola is invisible to stormwater rules. A roofed one would need to drain to a permeable area, not the gutter system, if it's over 200 sqft.\n\n**The free expert call.** Portland Permitting & Development offers free 15-minute appointments with a planner. For a project this size it's overkill, but if you're hesitating between \"open lattice\" and \"solid roof\" or want certainty about the setbacks for a corner of the lot, it's the highest-leverage 15 minutes you can spend: [portland.gov/ppd](https://www.portland.gov/ppd) \u2192 \"15-Minute Question Appointment.\"\n\n## Practical next steps\n\n1. **Pick the size.** Stay under 200 sqft and 15 ft tall to skip the building permit. A 12\u00d716 (192 sqft) hits the sweet spot.\n2. **Mark the corners with stakes** at least 5 ft from any side/rear property line and 10 ft from SE 52nd. If you're not sure exactly where your property lines are, a fence line is *not* a reliable proxy \u2014 Portland recommends a licensed surveyor for any work near the line.\n3. **Decide covered 