        "response": "I'll dig into this properly for you. Since you gave me an actual address, I'm going to look up the real property data through Portland's official systems first, then verify the current pergola rules through Portland's code, rather than guessing from neighborhood patterns. Give me a few minutes.Now let me verify the current pergola permit rules from Portland's official sources:I have everything I need. Let me load the diagram module so I can draw you a visual of your lot's setback rules, then put it all together.Here's the answer, in plain English first, then the details.\n\n## The short version\n\nYes, you can almost certainly put up a pergola at 4773 SE 52nd Ave. Your property is in a regular single-family residential zone called **R5**, with no historic, environmental, or design overlays to worry about (which is great news; those are the things that complicate small projects). For a typical backyard pergola that is freestanding, no taller than 15 feet, smaller than 200 square feet, kept at least 5 feet from your side and back property lines, and at least 10 feet from your front property line on SE 52nd Ave, you generally do not need a building permit, though you may still need a quick zoning permit. Once you start attaching it to the house, going bigger or taller, adding a solid roof, or putting it in your front yard, the rules get stricter and you'll likely need permits.\n\nLet me show you what your lot looks like in terms of the rules, then walk through everything else.Now the full walkthrough.\n\n## What's specific to your property\n\nI pulled your property up on Portland's official **PortlandMaps** system (portlandmaps.com), which is the city's authoritative database. Here is what it says, in plain language:\n\nYour lot sits in the **R5 zone** (full name: \"Residential 5,000,\" which means single-family neighborhoods with minimum lots around 5,000 square feet). The city actually classifies your block as part of the **Woodstock** neighborhood, not Foster-Powell; SE 52nd Ave is the boundary between the two, and the city's records put you on the Woodstock side, though most people in the area use the names loosely. This doesn't change any of the rules; it's just a useful little fact.\n\nYour lot is about **50 feet wide by 100 feet deep**, so right around 4,800 square feet (a classic Portland city lot). Your home (built in 1988) is 810 square feet, leaving you a lot of yard to work with. The front of the property faces west onto SE 52nd Ave, and the lot extends 100 feet east into the block, so your back yard is on the east side.\n\nThe really good news: **your property has no overlay zones**. Overlays are extra layers of rules that get stacked on top of the base zone. The most common ones in Portland are:\n\nA **historic district** or **conservation district** would mean you'd need design review for almost anything visible from the street. Yours has none. An **environmental overlay** (often labeled \"c\" or \"p\") would protect natural resources like streams, wetlands, or steep slopes; yours has none. A **design overlay** (a \"d\" zone) would require design review even outside historic areas; yours has none. A **plan district** (like Eastmoreland or Laurelhurst) would add neighborhood-specific rules; yours has none. None of those apply to you, which makes a pergola project simpler than it would be in many parts of Portland.\n\nA few other things worth knowing that I dug up on your specific lot. Your property has **no flood hazard, no landslide hazard, and no steep slope concerns**, so soil and drainage rules will be straightforward. There is **no heritage tree** registered on your lot. There is, however, a **2016 tree permit** on file at your address (a removal-with-replanting permit, now expired), which suggests a tree was removed and a replacement was planted somewhere on the property; if the replacement is still alive and is now 12 inches across or bigger, the tree code rules I describe below could apply to it. Your sewer lateral connects from the south side (the line runs in SE Long Street, with a branch coming up to your house roughly 10 feet underground), and the city's records show one **sewer backup history** at the address, so you'll want to know roughly where that line runs before you set any post holes (more on this in the \"gotchas\" section).\n\n## Permits \u2014 what you need and what triggers them\n\nThe very condensed version: a small open backyard pergola usually slips under both permit thresholds. The moment it gets bigger, taller, attached, or covered, you need permits.\n\nTwo different rule books apply to your project, and they ask different questions.\n\nThe **building code** (Portland City Code Title 24, which is the city adopting the **Oregon Residential Specialty Code**) cares about whether the structure is safe \u2014 wind loads, post anchoring, that sort of thing. Under that code, you do not need a building permit for a freestanding (detached) pergola that is one story, has a footprint of 200 square feet or less, is no taller than 15 feet measured to the average roof height, and sits at least 3 feet from any property line. For a pergola that is **attached** to your house (bolted to the wall with a ledger board), the threshold is similar but slightly different: 200 square feet or less, 12-foot average roof height or less, and 3 feet or more from any property line. (Reference: Building Official Determination 21-05 and BOD 21-01, which apply Oregon Residential Specialty Code section R105.2.)\n\nThe **zoning code** (Portland City Code Title 33, specifically Chapter 33.110 for single-family zones) cares about *where* the structure sits and *how big* it is in proportion to the lot. Even if you are exempt from the building permit, **you may still need a zoning permit** to confirm your pergola meets setbacks, height, and lot coverage rules. The city is straightforward about this; PP&D (Portland Permitting & Development, the bureau that handles these reviews; renamed from BDS, the Bureau of Development Services, in July 2024) treats the zoning permit as a quick check rather than a full plan review.\n\nA simple way to think about the lines you might cross:\n\nIf your pergola is **bigger than 200 square feet** of footprint, you cross into building permit territory. (PCC Title 24; ORSC R105.2.) About 14 feet by 14 feet is roughly 200 square feet, so plan around that if you want to stay exempt.\n\nIf your pergola is **taller than 15 feet** (detached) or 12 feet average roof height (attached patio cover), same answer \u2014 building permit. (PCC Title 24.)\n\nIf you **attach the pergola to your house**, even a small one, the city looks at the connection point more carefully because it affects your house's framing and waterproofing. Small attached pergolas can still be permit-exempt, but the threshold is lower (12-foot average roof height instead of 15), and inspectors are more likely to want to see how you attached it.\n\nIf you **add a solid roof** (real roofing material instead of open beams or slats), it stops being a pergola in the city's eyes and starts being a \"patio cover,\" which has its own rules under Title 24 and under PCC 33.110.245 (detached and connected covered accessory structures). Solid roofs also create new impervious area, which has stormwater consequences.\n\nIf you build it in your **front yard** (the area between the house and SE 52nd Ave), the city is much pickier. Front yards have to stay relatively open in single-family zones, and small accessory structures generally can't be in the front 10 feet at all. (PCC 33.110.220 and 33.110.245.)\n\nIf your pergola goes **over a deck that's more than 30 inches off the ground**, the deck itself triggers a building permit regardless of the pergola, so the whole thing gets permitted together. (Oregon Residential Specialty Code; this is consistent across Oregon.)\n\nFor most regular backyard pergolas in your situation, you'll either need no permits, or just a quick zoning permit. Plan for a building permit if you cross any of the lines above.\n\n## Trees\n\nPortland is serious about trees. The rule book is **Title 11**, and it's run by **Urban Forestry** (a team that used to live under Portland Parks & Recreation and is now mostly merged into PP&D as part of the 2024 reorganization, though tree expertise still sits in Urban Forestry within Parks).\n\nTwo situations matter for your pergola.\n\n**If you're not disturbing any tree's roots**, you generally don't have to do anything for trees. \"Not disturbing roots\" means no digging, no construction staging, no driving heavy equipment within the **root protection zone** of any regulated tree. The root protection zone is roughly 1 foot of radius for every inch of trunk diameter; so a 12-inch tree has a 12-foot RPZ around it.\n\n**If your pergola posts will be in the root zone of a sizable tree**, you cross into Title 11 territory. The threshold is set in PCC 11.50.020 and 11.50.030: you need to deal with the tree code if your project disturbs more than 100 square feet within the root protection zone of a **private tree 12 inches or bigger** in diameter (measured at breast height, abbreviated DBH), or a **City tree 6 inches or bigger**, or a **street tree 3 inches or bigger**.\n\nA **regulated tree** in plain English is any tree the city tracks. **Street trees** are the ones in the planting strip between sidewalk and curb (the city basically owns them even though they're on your frontage). **City trees** are on city-owned property, like in the right-of-way or in parks. **Private trees** are everything else on your lot. Heritage trees are a separate, more protected category; you don't have any.\n\nPractical advice: if there's a mature tree anywhere near where you're thinking of putting the pergola, get out a tape measure and check the trunk diameter at about 4.5 feet off the ground (that's \"breast height\"). If it's 12 inches or more, sketch a circle around it with a radius equal to the diameter in feet. If your pergola posts fall in that circle, you'll likely need a tree review as part of your permit, which Urban Forestry handles. **The 2016 tree permit** I found on your property suggests a tree was planted there about nine years ago \u2014 depending on species, that tree might or might not have hit the 12-inch threshold yet. Worth a quick measurement before you start.\n\nIf a tree needs to be removed for the pergola, that's a separate Tree Permit under PCC 11.40, and Urban Forestry has to approve it. Removing a regulated tree without a permit is one of the more expensive mistakes you can make in Portland; mitigation fees run around $472 per inch of trunk diameter, and there are daily penalty options too. Always call Urban Forestry first if there's any tree question.\n\n## Setbacks, lot coverage, and yard rules\n\nYour zoning code uses the word **setback** to mean \"the strip along each property line where you're not allowed to build.\" For your R5 lot, the rules from Title 33 Table 110-3 are:\n\n**10 feet from the front property line** (the line along SE 52nd Ave). (PCC 33.110.220, Table 110-3.) Your pergola has to sit at least that far back from the sidewalk side of your lot.\n\n**5 feet from each side property line** (north and south). (Same table.)\n\n**5 feet from the rear property line** (the back of your lot). (Same table.)\n\n**Lot coverage** is the share of your lot that's covered by buildings. It's calculated as the footprint of your house plus the footprint of any other roofed structures, divided by the total lot size. Your house is 810 square feet on a 4,800-square-foot lot, so you're at about 17% coverage. A 200-square-foot pergola would push you to about 21%. The R5 zone has a maximum building coverage that varies with lot size (Table 110-5); you have plenty of room. There's also a separate rule that *all detached accessory structures combined* cannot exceed 20% of the lot, which for you is about 960 square feet \u2014 way more than a pergola. (PCC 33.110.225 and 33.110.245.)\n\nIt absolutely matters whether the pergola is in the front yard or the back yard. The setbacks alone push it into the back: 10 feet from the front means a pergola right next to your front porch is generally not allowed. Beyond that, Portland's zoning code wants front yards to feel open, so accessory structures in front yards are heavily restricted. **Keep it behind the house** and you avoid almost all of these issues.\n\nThere's a useful exception worth knowing about: a small pergola **can encroach into the side or rear setbacks** (closer than 5 feet to those property lines) if it meets a specific list of conditions in PCC 33.110.245.C.2.b. Roughly: it has to be no more than 24 feet by 24 feet, no more than 15 feet tall overall, walls no more than 10 feet, screened by a fence or wall, with no doors or windows facing the neighbor, no rooftop deck, and at least 40 feet from the front lot line. A typical pergola easily clears those bars, so if you want to put it close to the back fence, you can \u2014 just keep it 3 feet from the line for the building code, which is the harder of the two limits.\n\n## What to do next, in order\n\nHere is the order I'd actually go in.\n\n1. **Verify everything yourself on PortlandMaps.** Go to portlandmaps.com, type in 4773 SE 52nd Ave, and click around the \"Permits & Zoning\" and \"Property\" sections. This costs nothing and takes 15 minutes. You're double-checking the zone (R5) and the absence of overlays. This is the step where you catch anything I might have gotten wrong.\n\n2. **Sketch a rough site plan.** Just paper and pencil is fine. Draw your lot to scale (50 feet wide on 52nd, 100 feet deep going east), mark the four property lines, sketch your house, and then draw where you want the pergola. Note the dimensions: how wide, how deep, how tall, how far from each property line. You'll need this for any permit conversation. Free, an afternoon.\n\n3. **Schedule a free 15-minute appointment with PP&D.** Portland Permitting & Development offers free 15-minute virtual appointments with a planner specifically for questions like yours. This is the highest-leverage step in the whole process. Go to portland.gov/ppd/15-min or call 503-823-7300 to book it. Have your sketch ready, plus your address and your property ID (R336087, from the city's records). The planner can confirm in real time whether you need a zoning permit, a building permit, both, or neither. Free, 15 minutes plus scheduling time.\n\n4. **If a tree is in play, call Urban Forestry.** If your pergola posts will be near a sizable tree, call Urban Forestry directly at 503-823-TREE (503-823-8733) before you commit to a design. They can tell you whether the tree counts as regulated, and whether you need a tree review. Free, 10 minutes.\n\n5. **If no permit is needed, build it.** Source: lumber yard, weekend project, or hire a contractor. Make sure your contractor is licensed by the Oregon Construction Contractors Board (CCB), which you can verify at oregon.gov/ccb. Cost varies wildly; a DIY 12x12 cedar pergola runs roughly $1,500 to $3,500 in materials (cost of a decent home appliance), a contractor-built one $5,000 to $15,000 (cost of a used car).\n\n6. **If a zoning permit is needed, apply online.** Go to portland.gov/ppd and look for residential permits. Upload your site plan, pay the fee, and wait for a planner to review and stamp it. Costs roughly $150 to $400 for a small project, takes one to three weeks typically.\n\n7. **If a building permit is needed, the application is more involved.** You'll need a more detailed plan showing dimensions, post sizes, anchoring details, and footing depth. Same online portal. Fees on a $5,000-$10,000 project run roughly $300 to $700 depending on valuation, plus a 12% state surcharge that Oregon adds to all building, plumbing, electrical, and mechanical permits. Plan review typically takes two to four weeks for something this small.\n\n8. **Schedule inspections if a building permit was issued.** You'll usually have a footing inspection (before you pour concrete in the post holes) and a final inspection (when you're done). The inspector is the friendly part; their job is to make sure it's safe, not to find reasons to fail you.\n\n## What to actually say when you call PP&D\n\nYou can paste this straight into an email or read it on the phone.\n\n\"Hi, my name is [your name]. I own a single-family home at 4773 SE Fifty-Second Avenue in Portland, ZIP 97206. The property ID is R three three six zero eight seven, and I'm in the R Five zone with no overlays. I'd like to put up a freestanding pergola in my back yard. It would be about [X] feet by [Y] feet, no taller than [Z] feet, with an open lattice roof and no electrical or plumbing. It would be at least [N] feet from each property line. Can you confirm whether I need a zoning permit, a building permit, both, or neither for this project? And can you tell me whether there are any special site conditions I should know about, like trees, sewer easements, or right-of-way concerns?\"\n\nFor email, send it to permits@portlandoregon.gov or use the contact form on portland.gov/ppd. They typically respond within a few business days.\n\nIf you talk to anyone about the trees specifically, here's a cleaner version of that:\n\n\"Hi, I'm planning to build a backyard pergola at 4773 SE Fifty-Second Avenue, property ID R three three six zero eight seven. I've got [a tree of about X inches diameter] on the property near where the pergola would go, and I want to make sure my post holes won't run into Title 11 issues. Can you walk me through what you'd need to see, and whether this rises to a tree review?\"\n\n## What people most often get wrong\n\nThese are the ones that actually trip up Portland homeowners on pergola projects. I'll give you the real-life version of each.\n\n**Putting it too close to the property line.** Most people eyeball it. Their fence isn't always on the actual property line; sometimes it's a foot or two over. Before you set posts, get a survey, or at minimum measure carefully from any existing reference points (and assume you're wrong by a foot). The penalty for being too close is having to move it.\n\n**Attaching to the house \"just for stability\" without realizing that triggers a permit.** A free-standing pergola near the house is one thing; bolting a ledger board to your siding is another. The bolt pattern, flashing, and load transfer all matter to the building code. If you want it close to the house, build it freestanding with its own posts unless you're prepared to permit it.\n\n**Adding a solid roof \"later.\"** Lots of homeowners build an open pergola, then a year later add corrugated panels or shingles to keep the rain off. That conversion turns the pergola into a \"patio cover\" under both Title 24 and PCC 33.110.245. The new impervious roof can also push you into stormwater rules (BES \u2014 the Bureau of Environmental Services, which runs sewers and stormwater \u2014 cares about anything that adds runoff). Best to decide on the roof before you build.\n\n**Building over the sewer cleanout or a buried utility.** Your property has a sewer lateral running roughly south from the house out to the main line in SE Long Street, and there's a documented sewer backup history at the address. Setting a 4-foot-deep concrete post on top of a sewer line is a real way to ruin a Saturday. **Call 811** before you dig (Oregon Utility Notification Center, free, 48 hours notice required). They send out crews who mark gas, water, electric, cable, and sometimes sewer for free. This is the single most important thing on this whole list.\n\n**Removing or seriously trimming a tree without checking.** Title 11 protects regulated trees. Even on your own property, taking down a 14-inch maple without a tree permit can result in mitigation fees in the thousands. The 2016 tree code permit on your property suggests you (or the previous owner) already went through this once. If anything is going to come out, talk to Urban Forestry first.\n\n**Forgetting about easements.** Easements are legal rights other parties have to use part of your property \u2014 utility companies, the city, sometimes neighbors. Pergolas built on top of an easement can be required to come down. Your title report should list any easements; the city's records show none on your lot, which is a good sign, but verify with your closing documents from when you bought the place.\n\n**Treating \"no permit needed\" as \"no rules apply.\"** Permit-exempt structures still have to meet the building code, the zoning code, and the tree code. A neighbor complaint can trigger an inspection even after the fact, and \"I didn't pull a permit\" doesn't get you out of a code violation if the structure isn't compliant.\n\n## Cost and timeline reality check\n\nFor a normal backyard pergola in your situation, here's what to plan around financially.\n\nIf you stay under all the permit thresholds (under 200 square feet, under 15 feet tall, freestanding, 3+ feet from property lines), permit fees can be **zero to about $200** for a quick zoning permit if one is needed. About the cost of a nice dinner out.\n\nIf you need a building permit because the pergola is bigger or attached, expect roughly **$300 to $700** in city fees for a project of $5,000-$10,000 valuation, plus the 12% state surcharge (so add another $35-$80). The minimum permit fee in Portland for FY 2025-26 is $153. About the cost of a nice power tool.\n\n**System Development Charges** (the city's term for one-time fees the city charges for new construction that adds load to sewers, streets, parks, and water systems \u2014 abbreviated SDCs) generally **do not apply** to a pergola. SDCs are tied to new dwelling units (new houses, new ADUs, new apartments), not accessory structures like pergolas. The one edge case is if you add a lot of impervious roof area; very large solid-roof patio covers can trigger a small stormwater SDC from BES. An open-slat pergola in your size range will be exempt.\n\nThe **1% Affordable Housing Construction Excise Tax** kicks in only at $100,000 valuation or more, so you don't need to worry about it.\n\nFor timeline: a permit-exempt project is whenever you and the lumber are ready. A zoning permit usually clears in **one to three weeks**. A building permit for a small accessory structure typically clears in **two to four weeks** for the review, then there's the build itself plus inspections (usually two: footing and final, scheduled with about a week of lead time each). Roughly one summer's worth of weekends if you DIY.\n\n## Friendly accuracy check\n\nA few honest caveats so you don't go spend money on something I got wrong.\n\nI pulled your zoning, lot size, and overlay status straight from PortlandMaps using the city's API, but **the city updates that data periodically**, and your situation could have changed. **Look it up yourself** at portlandmaps.com before you spend money on plans or materials. It takes five minutes and is the difference between being right and being mostly right.\n\nSetback distances and permit thresholds in this answer reflect the current version of the Portland City Code as I read it today, but **codes get amended**, and the ones around residential infill, ADUs, and trees have been changing every couple of years. The version I cited (Title 33 Chapter 33.110, accessed via portland.gov/code/33) was current as of late 2024 / 2025. The 15-minute appointment with a PP&D planner exists specifically to give you the current answer, and it's free. Use it.\n\nI'm a friendly explainer, not your zoning officer. If your project is borderline (bigger pergola, attached, near a tree, near a property line), get the question in writing from PP&D \u2014 usually an email reply from a planner is enough \u2014 before you build. That's the shield that protects you if a neighbor complains later.\n\nIf something I said about your specific lot doesn't match what you see on the ground (the property line is in a different place, there's a tree I didn't know about, the back fence is on a strange angle), trust your eyes and verify before building. The city's records are usually right but not always.\n\n## Glossary\n\n**BDS** \u2014 Bureau of Development Services, the old name for the city bureau that handled permits. Renamed PP&D in July 2024. You may still see \"BDS\" on older documents and signs.\n\n**BES** \u2014 Bureau of Environmental Services, the city bureau that runs the sewers and stormwater system. Phone 503-823-7740.\n\n**DBH** \u2014 Diameter at Breast Height, how the city measures tree trunks (about 4.5 feet off the ground).\n\n**FAR** \u2014 Floor Area Ratio, the total floor area of all buildings on a lot divided by the lot size. Pergolas don't have enclosed floor area, so they don't count toward FAR.\n\n**Lot coverage** \u2014 The share of your lot covered by buildings, measured as the footprint divided by the lot area.\n\n**Overlay** \u2014 An extra set of rules layered on top of the base zoning, used for historic districts, environmental zones, design review areas, and certain neighborhoods. Your lot has none.\n\n**PBOT** \u2014 Portland Bureau of Transportation, the bureau that owns streets and sidewalks. They get involved when you're working in the public right-of-way.\n\n**PCC** \u2014 Portland City Code, the official rule book. Title 11 is trees. Title 24 is building regulations. Title 33 is zoning.\n\n**PF&R** \u2014 Portland Fire & Rescue, the fire bureau. They mostly care about access and clearances around buildings, which doesn't typically come up for backyard pergolas.\n\n**PP&D** \u2014 Portland Permitting & Development, the city bureau that handles building permits, zoning permits, tree permits, and inspections (formerly BDS, plus permit functions absorbed from Urban Forestry, BES, PBOT, and Water as of July 2024). 1900 SW Fourth Avenue, phone 503-823-7300.\n\n**Regulated tree** \u2014 A tree the city tracks under Title 11. Private tree at 12+ inches DBH, City tree at 6+ inches, or street tree at 3+ inches.\n\n**ROW** \u2014 Right-of-Way, the public strip along your property that the city owns (street, sidewalk, and the planting strip between them). You can't build on it.\n\n**RPZ** \u2014 Root Protection Zone, the protected circle around a regulated tree. Roughly 1 foot of radius for every inch of trunk diameter.\n\n**R5** \u2014 Residential 5,000 zone, single-family neighborhoods with minimum lots around 5,000 square feet. Your zone.\n\n**SDC** \u2014 System Development Charge, the city's one-time fees for new construction that adds load to sewers, streets, parks, and water. Doesn't apply to typical pergolas.\n\n**Setback** \u2014 The strip along each property line where you can't normally build. Your setbacks are 10 feet front, 5 feet sides, 5 feet rear.\n\n**Urban Forestry** \u2014 The city group that handles tree code review, tree permits, and street trees. Phone 503-823-TREE (503-823-8733).\n\n---\n\nIf you want, I can save this as a markdown file you can keep on your computer for the permit conversation, or I can sketch a more detailed version of the diagram showing exactly where you're thinking of putting the pergola if you tell me roughly where on the lot you want it. Happy to keep going.",
