      "enrichedQuestion": "I want to know whether I can put up a pergola in my yard at 4773 SE 52nd Ave, Portland, OR 97206, and what I have to do to make it legal. I'm a regular homeowner \u2014 I don't know anything about permits, zoning, or building codes, so please answer like a friendly neighbor or city employee explaining this to me over coffee, not like a lawyer or a contractor talking to another contractor.\n\nPlease write for a Portland resident with no code or permitting background. Aim for an 8th-to-10th grade reading level. Treat me as smart but unfamiliar with city processes. Lead with a plain-English summary that answers my question directly in 3\u20135 sentences before any tables, citations, or code language. Define every acronym and technical term the first time you use it (BDS, BES, PBOT, PP&D, PF&R, PCC, ADU, FAR, SDC, ROW, etc.). If you wouldn't use a word talking to a neighbor over the fence, define it. Say \"how far the pergola has to sit from my property line\" before saying \"setback.\" Say \"fees the city charges for new construction\" before saying \"System Development Charges.\" Keep paragraphs short. Use bolded keywords inside sentences instead of dense tables. Only use a table if you're comparing three or more options on the same dimensions, and put a one-sentence plain-English summary above it. Translate dollar figures and timelines into something I can plan around \u2014 \"about the cost of a nice dishwasher,\" \"roughly one summer's worth of weekends.\"\n\nHere's everything I want you to cover:\n\n1. **The plain-English answer first.** Can I put up a pergola at this address? In a normal residential yard in Portland, what are the basic rules \u2014 how big can it be, how tall, how close to the property line, attached vs. freestanding, covered vs. open-top? Answer that in everyday language in the first paragraph, with no citations or jargon.\n\n2. **What's specific to my property at 4773 SE 52nd Ave (Foster-Powell area).** What's the most likely zoning for this address (probably a single-dwelling residential zone like R5 or R2.5, but please verify on PortlandMaps), and how does the zone change what I'm allowed to build? Are there overlays I should check for \u2014 historic district, environmental zone, design overlay, tree preservation? Walk me through what each overlay would mean for a pergola in plain terms.\n\n3. **Permits \u2014 what I likely need and what triggers them.** Will I need a building permit, a zoning permit, both, or neither? Specifically explain when a pergola crosses the line from \"no permit needed\" into \"permit required\" \u2014 square footage, height, whether it's attached to the house, whether it has a solid roof, whether it's over a deck or patio that's itself permitted. Cite the relevant Titles (Title 24 Building Regulations, Title 33 Zoning Code, and any others that apply) as parenthetical references after the plain-English explanation, not as the lead.\n\n4. **Trees.** Will building a pergola disturb any trees, and if so, what does Title 11 (Trees) require? What counts as a \"regulated tree\" in Portland, and what should I check before digging post holes? Who is Urban Forestry and when do I have to call them?\n\n5. **Setbacks, lot coverage, and yard rules \u2014 in plain words.** How far does the pergola have to sit from the front property line, side property lines, and back property line? Does it count toward \"lot coverage\" (the share of my lot that can be covered by buildings)? Does it matter if it's in the front yard vs. back yard? Cite PCC 33.110 sections after the plain-English explanation.\n\n6. **A numbered \"what to do next\" list, in the order I should do it.** For each step, tell me:\n   - Who to call or what website to visit (with the actual bureau name spelled out \u2014 Bureau of Development Services (BDS), Permitting & Development (PP&D), Bureau of Environmental Services (BES), Portland Bureau of Transportation (PBOT), Urban Forestry, Portland Fire & Rescue (PF&R))\n   - What I should bring or have ready (site plan, photos, measurements, address)\n   - Roughly what it costs (and mark which steps are free)\n   - Roughly how long it takes (in human terms \u2014 \"an afternoon,\" \"a couple of weeks\")\n\n7. **A \"what to ask the city\" script** I can literally read out loud on the phone or paste into an email to BDS or PP&D. Not \"call BDS\" \u2014 give me the actual sentences to say, including my address, what I want to build, and what I'm trying to find out.\n\n8. **A \"what you might get wrong\" / common gotchas section** in plain language. What specific mistakes do Portland homeowners make with pergolas? (Examples I'd guess at: building too close to the property line, attaching to the house without realizing that triggers a permit, adding a solid roof later, blocking sewer cleanouts or utility easements, taking out a tree without checking with Urban Forestry first.) Tell me the ones that actually happen.\n\n9. **Cost and timeline reality check.** Roughly what range of permit fees should I expect if a permit is required? Are there System Development Charges (fees the city charges for new construction that adds load to sewers, streets, parks) for a pergola, or is it usually exempt? How long does the permit process typically take from application to approval for something this small?\n\n10. **Friendly accuracy caveats.** Remind me that the zoning and overlays for my exact address may differ from what's typical for the neighborhood, and tell me to verify on **PortlandMaps** (portlandmaps.com) before I spend money on plans or materials. Frame these as friendly warnings, not legal disclaimers.\n\n11. **A glossary at the end** defining every acronym and technical term you used more than once (BDS, BES, PBOT, PP&D, PF&R, Urban Forestry, PCC, setback, lot coverage, overlay, SDC, ROW, regulated tree, etc.), in case I skipped to a section.\n\nRules for how to write the answer:\n- Do not lead with a property data table. Lead with the answer in words.\n- Do not stack code section numbers without explaining what they mean in plain English right next to them.\n- Do not assume I know the difference between BDS, BES, PBOT, PP&D, Urban Forestry, or PF&R \u2014 name what each one does the first time it shows up.\n- Do not use words like \"shall,\" \"promulgated,\" \"thereunder,\" or other legal-register language. Write the way a friendly city employee would explain it over coffee.\n- Cite specific Portland City Code sections (PCC 33.110.xxx, Title 24, Title 11, etc.) as parentheticals after the plain-English explanation \u2014 never as the lead."
