        "response": "Short answer: yes, you can probably extend it; but at this address, \"yes\" comes with a catch most homeowners don't see coming. Your house sits inside the **Ladd's Addition Conservation District**, and front porches are specifically called out in the design guidelines as character-defining features. So this is less a permit question than a design-review question.\n\n## Why this matters for your address specifically\n\nA few things stack up here:\n\n1. **The whole neighborhood is a Conservation District** (locally designated 1977, on the National Register since 1988). Boundaries: SE 12th to 20th, Hawthorne to Division. You're well inside.\n2. **Ladd Avenue is one of the two diagonal \"boulevards\"** in the wagon-wheel plan; it's one of the most visible streets in the district, so anything on your front facade will get extra scrutiny.\n3. **Your 1924 bungalow was built squarely in the period of significance** (1905-1930), which makes it almost certainly a contributing structure. That raises the bar further.\n4. **The Ladd's guidelines literally name front porches.** From section 5 of the Exterior Rehabilitation guidelines: original entrances, front porches, and projecting features \"should be retained or restored.\" For bungalows, defining elements include \"open porch with square wood posts, multi-pane double-hung windows, simple pipe handrails.\"\n\nSo an extension is doable, but the Historic Landmarks Commission (or staff, depending on size) will want to see that:\n- The original porch isn't being destroyed; it's being added to in a way that's compatible\n- The new portion is differentiated from the old (no faking history)\n- It's reversible in principle, so the historic form could be recovered later\n- Massing, materials, columns, railings, and roofline match the original Craftsman vocabulary\n\n## The two procedural paths\n\nThis is the part most blog posts gloss over. Conservation Districts (unlike full Historic Districts) give you a choice:\n\n**Path A: Historic Resource Review (discretionary).** Type I if the project is small; Type II if it affects more than 150 sq ft of facade elevation. Type I is staff-approved and relatively quick (4-8 weeks); Type II involves notice to neighbors and longer review (8-10 weeks), with fees roughly $991-$6,124 last time the city published them.\n\n**Path B: Community Design Standards (clear and objective).** Conservation Districts in Portland allow you to skip discretionary HRR if your design meets the objective standards in Chapter 33.218. This is the faster, cheaper path if your porch extension fits the box. Most people don't know this option exists; it's worth asking about specifically.\n\n## What I'd actually do, in order\n\n1. **Pull the official record for your address.** Go to [portlandmaps.com](https://www.portlandmaps.com/), enter 2145 SE Ladd Ave, and check the \"Zoning and Districts\" tab. Confirms zoning (likely R5), the Conservation District overlay, and any other overlays (tree code, etc.).\n2. **Read the actual guidelines.** The current document is the [Ladd's Addition Conservation District Design Guidelines (2011 update)](https://www.portland.gov/sites/default/files/2019-07/laddsaddition_conservation_district_guidelines_2011_update.pdf) on portland.gov. It's the approval criteria; the ~25 MB original 1990 PDF is also on the [city's design guidelines page](https://www.portland.gov/bps/planning/design-guideline-documents).\n3. **Request a free pre-application conference** with Portland Permitting & Development (formerly BDS). They'll tell you which review type you fall into and flag issues early; this is the single highest-leverage thing you can do.\n4. **Talk to a designer who has been through Ladd's review specifically.** Arciform is the name that came up most often in my research as a Ladd's Addition specialist; there are others. Worth getting two opinions before committing.\n5. **Loop in HAND** (Hosford-Abernethy Neighborhood Development Association) early. They're the recognized neighborhood association and get notice on Type II reviews; their support smooths things considerably.\n\n## Two things you might not have considered\n\n**Tax credit upside.** Because Ladd's is on the National Register and your house likely contributes, substantial rehabilitation work can qualify for the Oregon Special Assessment of Historic Property program (a 10-year property tax freeze) or federal rehab tax credits if any portion is for income-producing use. If your porch extension is part of a larger rehab, this can change the math meaningfully. Worth asking the State Historic Preservation Office (SHPO) before you finalize scope.\n\n**Sequencing matters.** If the existing porch has any rot or deferred maintenance, framing the project as \"restoration with compatible expansion\" rather than \"addition\" generally lands better in review; restoration is preferred over replacement in the guidelines, and there's a Type Ix restoration track that's faster.\n\nWant me to dig into any of these next: the specific objective standards in 33.218 to see if your project could skip discretionary review, the pre-app process and what to bring, or the SHPO tax-incentive angle?",
