      "enrichedQuestion": "I want to know whether I can extend my front porch at my house at 2145 SE Ladd Ave, Portland, OR 97214, and what that would actually involve. Please walk me through the whole picture as if you were a knowledgeable friend explaining this to me over coffee \u2014 I'm a homeowner with no background in zoning, permitting, or building codes, so please treat me as smart but unfamiliar with how the city works.\n\n**About the property and the project:** My address sits in the Ladd's Addition area of inner Southeast Portland, which I've heard is a historic district \u2014 please check whether that's true and whether it changes what I can do. I'm imagining extending my existing front porch outward toward the street and/or widening it along the front of the house, but I'm open to hearing what's allowed before I commit to a specific design. I don't yet know my zoning, my lot's setbacks, or whether my porch is considered part of the \"main house\" for code purposes. Please tell me what you can figure out from the address and flag what I'd need to verify myself.\n\n**How I need the answer written:**\n\n- Write for a Portland resident with no code or permitting background. Aim for an 8th-to-10th grade reading level. Treat me as smart but unfamiliar with city processes.\n- **Lead with a plain-English summary that answers my question directly in 3\u20135 sentences before any tables, citations, or code language.** No property data table at the top \u2014 answer the question in words first.\n- Define every acronym and technical term the first time you use it (BDS, BES, PBOT, PP&D, PCC, ADU, FAR, ROW, SDC, historic district, setback, lot coverage, etc.). If you wouldn't use the term talking to a neighbor over the fence, define it.\n- Use everyday words instead of code language wherever possible. Say \"how far the house has to sit from the sidewalk\" before saying \"front setback.\" Say \"the percentage of the lot the house can cover\" before saying \"lot coverage.\" Say \"fees the city charges when you add square footage\" before \"System Development Charges.\"\n- Keep paragraphs short. Use **bolded keywords** inside sentences instead of dense tables. Only use a table if you're comparing 3+ options on the same dimensions, and put a one-sentence plain-English summary above any table.\n- Translate dollar figures and timelines into something I can plan around (e.g., \"about the price of a used car,\" \"roughly one summer's worth of weekends,\" \"about as long as a typical kitchen remodel\").\n- Do not use words like \"shall,\" \"promulgated,\" \"thereunder,\" or other legal-register language. Write the way a friendly city employee would explain it over coffee.\n- Cite specific code section numbers (Title 33 Zoning, Title 24 Building, Title 11 Trees, etc.) as **parenthetical citations after the plain-English explanation**, not as the lead. Example: \"Your porch can stick out into the front yard up to 6 feet (PCC 33.110.220)\" \u2014 not the other way around.\n\n**Please specifically cover:**\n\n1. **Can I do this at all?** What zoning is my property in, and what does that zoning say about extending a porch toward the street? Is there a special rule for porches that lets them stick into the front yard further than the rest of the house can? How far forward can it go, how wide can it be, how tall, how enclosed?\n\n2. **Is Ladd's Addition a historic district, and if so, what does that change?** If my house or neighborhood is on the National Register or has a local Historic or Conservation District overlay, walk me through what extra review I'd face \u2014 Historic Resource Review, design guidelines, what gets approved easily and what gets denied, and roughly how much extra time and money that adds.\n\n3. **What other overlays or special rules might apply** to this address (design overlay, environmental overlay, tree preservation, main street overlay, etc.) \u2014 and what each one means in practice for a porch project.\n\n4. **What permits will I likely need**, what triggers each one, and which bureau handles them. Name what each bureau actually does the first time you mention it: **BDS** (Bureau of Development Services \u2014 building permits and zoning checks), **BES** (Bureau of Environmental Services \u2014 sewer and stormwater), **PBOT** (Portland Bureau of Transportation \u2014 anything in the street or sidewalk), **Urban Forestry** (trees), **PP&D** or any historic review body, etc.\n\n5. **Trees.** If extending the porch puts construction near a tree in my yard or the planting strip, what are the rules, who do I call, and what's the worst-case cost (Title 11)?\n\n6. **Right-of-way concerns.** If the porch extension gets close to or over the public sidewalk or planting strip (\"right-of-way\" or **ROW**), explain what that triggers with PBOT.\n\n7. **Cost and timeline expectations** \u2014 rough range for permit fees, design review fees if historic, contractor costs, and how long the whole thing typically takes from \"I want to do this\" to \"I can sit on my new porch.\"\n\n8. **A numbered 'what to do next' list, in the order I should do it.** For each step, tell me:\n   - Who to call or what website to visit (with the actual URL or phone number if you know it)\n   - What to bring or have ready\n   - Roughly what it costs\n   - Roughly how long it takes\n   - **Mark which steps are free.** Start with the free verification steps (PortlandMaps lookup, free 15-minute appointment with a planner, etc.) before anything that costs money.\n\n9. **A \"what to ask the city\" script** I can read aloud on the phone or paste into an email when I contact BDS or the historic review staff. Give me the actual sentences to say, not just \"call BDS.\" Include my address and the specific things I need them to confirm.\n\n10. **A \"what you might get wrong\" / common gotchas section** in plain language \u2014 the specific mistakes Portland homeowners make when they extend a porch in a historic neighborhood. Things like: starting work without realizing historic review is required, assuming a porch doesn't count as \"building footprint,\" not knowing the porch is partly in the right-of-way, removing a street tree without a permit, etc.\n\n11. **Friendly accuracy caveats** \u2014 frame these as \"before you spend money on plans, double-check X\" warnings, not legal disclaimers. Tell me which facts in your answer are most likely to be wrong for my specific address and how to verify them on PortlandMaps or with a free BDS appointment.\n\n12. **A glossary at the end** of every acronym or technical term you used more than once, so if I skipped to a section I can still follow along.\n\nEnd with a one-paragraph honest assessment: based only on the address and what you can reasonably infer, what's your gut read on whether this project is straightforward, moderately complex, or likely to be a long haul \u2014 and why."
