l a permit (ADU, addition, foundation work) within 10 feet of it, at which point you'll need to formally decommission per OAR 340-071-0185.\n\n## What it actually costs if you do need to connect\n\nRoughly, in 2025-2026 dollars:\n\n- **Private plumbing (contractor work)**: $5,000 to $12,000 typical for the lateral install plus cesspool decommissioning; your lot's small frontage on Missouri keeps this on the lower end.\n- **System Development Charge (SDC)**: For a typical residential connection, calculated per drainage fixture unit at ~$343/DFU residential rate (60% of the Tier 1 rate of $572). A standard 3-bath, kitchen, laundry house typically lands in the $4,000 to $7,000 range.\n- **Permits**: Septic decommissioning permit, plumbing trade permit, and a UR/UC right-of-way permit. A few hundred dollars total.\n- **Possible sewer line / branch charges**: Only if BES has to extend a public main; very unlikely at your address since Missouri is fully sewered.\n\nRealistic total: **$12,000 to $20,000**, on the order of a small kitchen remodel.\n\n## Financial assistance you'd actually qualify for\n\nThe City has two loan programs specifically for this scenario, and they're better than most private financing:\n\n- **Private Plumbing Loan**: Up to $20,000 (cap), 6.1% simple interest, 5 or 10-year term, $90 origination fee. Secured as a lien on the property; no income/credit qualification.\n- **Safety Net Private Plumbing Loan**: 1.5% interest, deferred payment option for income-qualified or older homeowners. Significantly cheaper if you qualify.\n- **City Loan Contract for SDCs**: Up to 20 years to finance the connection charges themselves.\n\nYou'd need three bids from CCB-licensed contractors to initiate either loan. The City pays the contractor directly on completion.\n\n## The above-and-beyond move I'd actually recommend\n\nGiven your house's age and the ambiguity in the public records, here's what I'd do this month, regardless of whether your system has shown any symptoms:\n\n1. **Spend the $15 at PP&D Trade Permits** (or via GovQA records request if you don't want to drive downtown) to pull every historic plumbing record on the address. You'll learn for sure whether a cesspool was ever permitted, whether/when it was converted, and whether it was actually decommissioned vs. just abandoned.\n2. **Get a sewer scope in the next 6 to 12 months** ($100 to $200; recommend asking for a recorded video). Pre-failure scoping costs less than 1% of an emergency dig and gives you negotiating leverage if you ever sell.\n3. **If you find an undecommissioned abandoned cesspool**, decide proactively whether to decommission it now (cheaper, on your timeline) or sit on the information (legal, but a future buyer will catch it on their inspection and may discount for the unknown cost).\n\nIf you want, I can help you draft the GovQA records request, compile a short list of vetted Portland sewer scope plumbers who specialize in pre-1930 homes, or sketch out the actual cash flow comparison of paying out of pocket vs. taking the BES Private Plumbing Loan. Just say the word.\n\nTwo contacts worth keeping handy if it does come to a failure: BES Required Sewer Connection at 503-823-7761 (sewer questions) and Portland Permitting & Development Septic Program at septic@portlandoregon.gov (decommissioning permits).",
