      "enrichedQuestion": "I live at 6624 N Missouri Ave, Portland, OR 97217, and my cesspool is starting to fail (or I'm worried it might soon). I want to know: if my cesspool fails, do I have to connect to the City sewer? And if I do, what does that actually look like \u2014 what I have to do, who I have to talk to, what it might cost, and how long it might take?\n\nPlease write your answer for a regular Portland homeowner with no background in plumbing, permits, or city code. Aim for an 8th-to-10th grade reading level. Treat me as smart but unfamiliar with city processes. Write the way a friendly city employee would explain this to a neighbor over coffee \u2014 not the way a code official writes a letter. Do not use words like \"shall,\" \"promulgated,\" or \"thereunder.\" If you would not say a word out loud to a neighbor over the fence, define it the first time you use it. That includes acronyms like BDS, BES, PBOT, PCC, ROW, SDC, ORSC, and any others \u2014 say what each bureau or term actually does in plain words the first time it appears.\n\nStart with a **plain-English summary in 3 to 5 sentences** that answers my actual question directly \u2014 no citations, no code language, no tables in that first paragraph. Just tell me: yes or no, do I have to hook up to City sewer if my cesspool fails, and what that means for me as the homeowner.\n\nThen please cover the related things I probably don't know to ask about, in plain language, with **specific Portland City Code section numbers in parentheses after the plain-English explanation** (not in front of it). For example: \"The City requires you to disconnect a failed cesspool and connect to public sewer if one is available within a reasonable distance (PCC 17.32 / Title 17).\" I'd like you to address:\n\n- **Is my cesspool actually required to be replaced, or can it be repaired?** What counts as \"failed\" in the City's eyes, and who decides \u2014 the Bureau of Environmental Services (BES, the city bureau that runs sewers and stormwater), DEQ (Oregon's Department of Environmental Quality), or someone else?\n- **Is there a public sewer line in front of (or near) my property on N Missouri Ave?** If yes, I almost certainly have to connect. If no, what are my options \u2014 septic system, a sewer extension, a private line through a neighbor's property?\n- **What permits will I need and from which bureau?** Specifically call out: Bureau of Development Services (BDS, the bureau that issues building and plumbing permits), BES (sewer connection permit and System Development Charges \u2014 the fees the city charges to tap into public infrastructure), and PBOT (Portland Bureau of Transportation, which handles anything in the right-of-way \u2014 the strip of public land between my property and the street, including the sidewalk and street itself).\n- **Which Titles of Portland City Code govern this?** Title 17 (Public Improvements / sewer connection rules), Title 25 (Plumbing), Title 21 (Water), and any administrative rules under BES's Sewer, Stormwater & Erosion Control policies. Explain in one sentence what each Title covers before citing it.\n- **What does the work itself involve?** A licensed plumber decommissioning the cesspool (pumping, filling, abandoning per Oregon rules), trenching from the house to the sewer main in the street, possibly cutting and patching the street and sidewalk, hooking up a new lateral line, and inspections.\n- **Rough cost and timeline.** Translate dollar figures into something I can plan around \u2014 \"about the cost of a used car,\" \"roughly one summer's worth of weekends,\" etc. Include the cesspool decommissioning, the plumber's work, the BES connection fee / SDCs, the street-cut permit fee, and any inspection fees. Tell me which line items are typically the biggest and which are small.\n- **Are there financial assistance programs?** Portland has historically had a cesspool conversion loan or fee deferral program through BES \u2014 please check whether anything like that is currently available and how I'd apply.\n- **Phasing and sequencing.** What has to happen first, second, third? (e.g., do I get the BES sewer connection permit before or after the plumbing permit? When does the cesspool actually get decommissioned in the sequence?) A numbered list works best here.\n- **Common gotchas Portland homeowners hit on cesspool-to-sewer conversions** \u2014 things like discovering the sewer main is on the far side of the street and needing a much longer (and more expensive) trench, finding out a neighbor's lateral runs through your yard, DEQ rules on cesspool abandonment that out-of-area plumbers don't know, the sewer line being deeper or shallower than expected, or trees in the right-of-way that Urban Forestry has to weigh in on (Urban Forestry is the city group, under Portland Parks & Recreation, that protects street trees under Title 11).\n- **Zoning and overlays at my address.** 6624 N Missouri Ave is in the Arbor Lodge neighborhood \u2014 please flag any zoning overlays, historic designations, or environmental overlays (like flood, landslide, or environmental conservation zones) that could complicate the trenching or the connection. If anything is unclear, tell me to verify on PortlandMaps before spending money on plans.\n\nThen please give me, in this exact order:\n\n1. **A numbered \"what to do next\" list**, in the order I should actually do things. For each step, tell me: who to call or what website to visit, what to bring or have ready, what it roughly costs, how long it takes, and **mark which steps are free**. The first step should be something I can do today for free (like looking up my property on PortlandMaps or calling BES to ask if there's a sewer main on my street).\n\n2. **A \"what to ask the city\" script** I can literally read aloud on the phone or paste into an email. Give me one short script for BES (about whether sewer is available and what the connection process is) and one short script for BDS (about plumbing permits for cesspool decommissioning and the new sewer lateral). Use first person, written the way a normal person talks. Include the specific question I'm trying to get answered and my address.\n\n3. **A \"what you might get wrong\" section** in plain language \u2014 4 to 6 specific mistakes Portland homeowners make on this kind of project, written as warnings to me, not as code commentary.\n\n4. **Accuracy caveats** as friendly warnings, not legal disclaimers. Things like: \"Zoning and sewer availability for your specific address may vary; check PortlandMaps and call BES before you pay anyone for plans,\" and \"Cesspool rules are partly state (DEQ) and partly city (BES) \u2014 make sure your plumber knows both.\"\n\n5. **A short glossary at the end** defining every acronym and technical term used more than once (BDS, BES, PBOT, DEQ, PCC, ROW, SDC, lateral, cesspool, decommissioning, etc.), in case I skipped to a section.\n\nFormatting rules: keep paragraphs short. Use **bolded keywords** inside sentences instead of dense tables. Only use a table if you're comparing 3 or more options on the same dimensions (for example, repair vs. connect to sewer vs. install septic), and if you do use a table, put a one-sentence plain-English summary right above it. Don't lead with a property data table \u2014 lead with the answer in words. Don't stack code section numbers without an explanation in plain English right next to them."
