        "response": "I'll dig into this carefully. \"Tiny house\" can mean a few different things in Portland's code, so I want to figure out what's actually possible on your specific lot before answering. Let me first check that I can reach the city's GIS layer, then pull your property data.This is interesting - I'm finding that 174th Avenue is right on the boundary between Portland and Gresham city limits. The exact line matters a lot here because it changes which code applies. Let me dig deeper.I have a strong picture now, but I want to make sure I'm giving you the most current ADU rules and the THOW (tiny house on wheels) policy, since those have changed in recent years. Let me verify those.I have enough now to give you a substantive answer; the short version is that \"tiny house\" maps to three very different code paths in Portland, and which one fits depends on details about your lot. I'll lay out all three, but first there's a wrinkle worth flagging.\n\n## First: confirm which city you're in\n\nSE 174th Ave is literally the city boundary between Portland and Gresham in your stretch. The City of Portland's official zip-code description for 97233 says Portland extends only \"west of 174th, south to Division\"; the east side of 174th Ave in the 800 block is Gresham. Your address (831, odd) is most likely on the west side and therefore in Portland, but please don't take my word for that; pull up <https://www.portlandmaps.com/search/?query=831+SE+174th+Ave+Portland+OR> and confirm. If the Property panel returns a base zone like R5 / R7 / R2.5, you're in Portland and everything below applies. If it returns \"Gresham\" or shows no Portland zoning, the rules are stricter and we'd need a different approach. (Gresham allows permanent foundation tiny homes but treats THOWs as RVs only, with no long-term backyard occupancy.)\n\n## Path 1: tiny house on wheels (by far the easiest)\n\nPortland is unusually permissive here, and this is probably the answer most people don't realize they have. Under the Occupied RV / THOW guidelines tied to Title 33.262, you can place one occupied tiny house on wheels on a residential lot that already has a primary dwelling (you have one). Wheels stay on; it must sit behind the front wall of your house; minimum 5 ft from the main dwelling; RV-style hookups (20-amp GFCI electrical, potable water, sewer tie-in by a licensed plumber). It does not count against density, no SDCs, no big permit set; you can host family or rent long-term (no short-term rentals). This is the path that delivers a livable second unit fastest and cheapest.\n\n## Path 2: detached ADU (permanent backyard cottage)\n\nTitle 33.205 governs this. The size cap for your specific property is the gotcha: maximum is the lesser of 800 sq ft or 75% of your primary dwelling's living area. Your house is reportedly 960 sq ft (per public records; verify), so 75% = **720 sq ft** would be your detached-ADU ceiling. Two exceptions worth knowing: (a) basement conversions in a primary dwelling that's been on the site at least 5 years aren't subject to the size cap (yours easily qualifies on age, but a 1947 home may not have a usable basement); (b) recent code updates allow ADUs up to 1,000 sq ft on lots over 5,000 sq ft in some configurations, and an Adjustment review can push beyond 800 sq ft. Other key rules: 20 ft height (15 ft within setbacks), 5 ft side/rear setbacks, must sit behind the rear wall of the main house, and SDC waivers are available if you record a 10-year covenant against short-term rentals (saves ~$15K-$25K).\n\n## Path 3: middle housing (the path most people miss)\n\nUnder Portland's Residential Infill Project, R2.5 / R5 / R7 lots can have **up to four units** total (counting the existing house). So instead of one ADU, you might be able to add a triplex-style configuration, or two ADUs plus a duplex conversion of your existing structure. This is the highest-value path if your lot supports it, and the FAR bonus actually grows as you