        "response": "I pulled the public data for your lot, then cross-referenced it against the current Title 33 zoning code. Here's what I found, what it means, and a path you may not have considered.\n\n## Your lot in numbers\n\n| Field | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Base zone | **R7** (single-dwelling, 7,000 sq ft min) | PortlandMaps Zoning layer |\n| Overlay | **`h`** (Aircraft Landing) | PortlandMaps Zoning layer |\n| Plan district / Historic / Conservation | None | PortlandMaps Zoning layer |\n| Lot area | **8,083 sq ft** (0.186 acres) | Multnomah taxlot record |\n| Approximate dimensions | ~75 ft frontage on 174th \u00d7 ~108 ft deep | Computed from parcel geometry |\n| Existing house | 960 sq ft, built 1947, 1 unit | Multnomah assessor |\n| Natural hazards on parcel | None (no flood, landslide, or 10%+ slope polygons hit) | PortlandMaps Natural Hazards layer |\n\nYes, you can build something here. The interesting question is **which kind** of \"tiny house,\" because Portland has three different legal paths and they have very different costs, timelines, and tradeoffs.\n\n## Path 1: Detached ADU (foundation-built tiny house)\n\nThis is what most people mean by \"build a tiny house in the yard.\" Permanent structure, real foundation, full residential code compliance.\n\n**Maximum size on your lot: 720 sq ft.** The rule is \"lesser of 800 sq ft or 75% of primary dwelling living area.\" Your primary is 960 sq ft, so 75% \u00d7 960 = 720 sq ft caps you. There's one workaround: a **basement ADU inside the existing 1947 house** is exempt from the 75% rule (since the house is more than 5 years old) and can go up to 800 sq ft (Title 33.205.040.C). That's not \"in the yard\" but it's a legitimate way to get to the full 800.\n\n**Other R7 standards that will matter** (verify each on the current chapter at portland.gov/code/33/100s/110 before you design; section numbers drift):\n- Front setback: 20 ft (the 1947 house likely already defines this)\n- Side setbacks: 5 ft\n- Rear setback: 5 ft\n- Detached ADU must sit at least 40 ft from the front lot line, OR behind the rear wall of the main house (33.205.040.C.3); on a 108 ft deep lot this is easy\n- Height: 25 ft for a detached accessory structure (per current 33.110)\n- Building coverage and FAR: well within limits for adding ~720 sq ft on this lot\n- One ADU is allowed by right; **two** are allowed if 174th Ave is a city-maintained street (very likely yes for a named arterial, but confirm at portland.gov/transportation/development/maintenance-rip)\n\n**Permitting:** Full BDS building permit, design review against the Community Design Standards (33.218), system development charges (which Portland may waive if you commit not to use it as a short-term rental for 10 years).\n\n## Path 2: Tiny House on Wheels (THOW) as an occupied RV\n\nThis is the **easier and cheaper** path; most people don't realize it's available. Portland treats THOWs as occupied RVs under Title 33.262, **not** as ADUs, so you skip the building permit and SDC entirely.\n\n**What's required:**\n- One occupied RV/THOW per residential lot, and the lot must already have a primary dwelling (you do)\n- Parked **behind the front fa\u00e7ade** of your house (i.e., not in the front yard)\n- At least **5 ft from the main house**\n- If non-motorized (most THOWs), can sit on compacted gravel; if motorized RV, must be on paved surface\n- 20-amp GFCI electrical hookup, potable water connection, and approved sewage disposal (sewer hookup, holding tank pump-out, or composting toilet under specific rules)\n- Must remain **mobile** (wheels stay on, on its chassis); does not count toward density\n- **Long-term occupancy is allowed; short-term rentals are not** under this program\n\n**Caveat to double-check:** the city's policy guidance document on this (separate from Title 33) is updated periodically. Search portland.gov for \"Guidelines for Occupied RVs and Tiny Homes on Wheels on Private Property\" before committing. The version in force when you apply is what matters; some details (sewage handling especially) have moved over the last few years.\n\n## Path 3: The one most people miss \u2014 a cottage cluster\n\nYour 8,083 sq ft R7 lot is a textbook candidate for a **cottage cluster** (Title 33.110.265 references), which is a development of **3 to 16 small units around shared open space**, allowed by right in R5/R7/R2.5/R10 on sites under 40,000 sq ft. This is a route to multiple tiny houses on one lot, not just one.\n\nThe catch: it's a **redevelopment**, not an addition; the site usually gets planned as one project rather than added to incrementally. The 1947 house's role would need a careful design pass (sometimes existing structures can stay, sometimes they're demolished). This path requires real architectural and planner involvement, but it's how you'd get from \"one tiny house\" to \"three or four tiny houses generating rental income or housing extended family.\" Worth knowing about before you commit to Path 1.\n\n## The aircraft landing overlay is mostly a red herring here\n\nThe `h` overlay flags your lot as being in the PDX flight path. For **residential zones**, Title 33.400.030 says the base zone height limit governs, not the overlay's height surface. So the practical effect on a single-story or two-story tiny house is **zero**. The overlay would only bite if you tried to build something tall enough to trigger FAA review (you won't).\n\n## What I'd verify before spending money\n\n1. **City-maintained street status of 174th Ave** at portland.gov/transportation/development/maintenance-rip. Affects whether a second ADU is on the table.\n2. **Sewer connection** (BES). Public data confirms sewer mains in the area but not your specific connection; check your utility records or call BES.\n3. **Current setback and ADU figures** in the live Title 33.110 and 33.205 chapters; section numbers shift across code updates and what I cited above is current as of recent updates but moves.\n4. **Free 15-minute planner consultation** at PP&D (503-823-7300). Genuinely useful; they'll tell you about constraints public data doesn't show (e.g., easements, prior land use decisions, neighbor disputes on file). For your specific lot this is the highest-leverage 15 minutes you can spend before drawing anything.\n\n## Quick comparison\n\n| | Foundation ADU | THOW (RV path) | Cottage cluster |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Max size per unit | 720 sq ft (or 800 if basement) | ~399 sq ft typical THOW | Varies by design |\n| Permits | Full BDS building permit | None (RV, not building) | Full land use review |\n| Cost order of magnitude | $150K-$300K+ | $60K-$150K | $500K+ |\n| Timeline | 6-18 months | Weeks (after pad/hookups) | 12-24+ months |\n| Counts as a dwelling unit | Yes | No | Yes |\n| Reversible | No | Yes | No |\n\nIf \"tiny house\" to you means a movable, simple, fast solution, **Path 2 is the best-kept secret**. If you want a real second dwelling that adds long-term value to the property, **Path 1**. If you're thinking bigger picture (income property, family compound, a small infill project), **Path 3** is genuinely on the table for this lot in a way it isn't for most Portland properties.\n\nWant me to dig deeper into any of these \u2014 for example, sketch out where on the lot a detached ADU could actually sit given the setbacks, or pull the specific sewer/water proximity data for utility hookup planning?",
