        "response": "# Tiny House Feasibility: 831 SE 174th Ave, Portland, OR 97233\n\n*Prepared with current PortlandMaps data and a check against current Title 33 chapters on portland.gov. Effective date of this snapshot: May 1, 2026. Code amends multiple times per year; verify any rule before relying on it.*\n\n---\n\n## Your lot, confirmed from city data\n\n| Field | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Address | 831 SE 174TH AVE, Portland, OR 97233 | PortlandMaps geocode |\n| Property ID | R337949 | PortlandMaps assessor |\n| State ID (taxlot) | 1S3E06AB 8800 | PortlandMaps |\n| Neighborhood | Centennial (East Portland) | BDS Property layer |\n| Council District | 1 | BDS Property layer |\n| Base zone | R7 (Single-Dwelling 7,000) | PortlandMaps Zoning |\n| Overlay | `h` (Aircraft Landing) | PortlandMaps Zoning |\n| Plan district | None | PortlandMaps Zoning |\n| Historic / Conservation district | None | PortlandMaps Zoning |\n| Comp Plan designation | R7 (matches zone, no pending change) | PortlandMaps Zoning |\n| Lot area | 8,083 sq ft (BDS) / 0.19 ac (assessor) | BDS Property + assessor |\n| Existing dwelling | 960 sq ft, built 1947 | Multnomah assessor |\n| FEMA Special Flood Hazard Area | No | BDS Property |\n| FEMA Flood Way | No | BDS Property |\n| Earthquake Liquefaction Hazard | No | BDS Property |\n| Regulated Landslide Hazard | No | BDS Property |\n| Twenty Percent Steep Slope | No | BDS Property |\n| Drainage district | None | BDS Property |\n| Permit history | 2000 electrical (100 A service); 2003 zoning confirmation; 2009 weeds complaint (closed) | PortlandMaps permits |\n| Listed owner of record | KARAM, CHAFEK & JANOURA, ANESA | BDS Property layer |\n\n**One thing to verify before you do anything else.** The assessor / BDS Property layer lists the owner of record as \"KARAM, CHAFEK & JANOURA, ANESA\" with the mailing address at the property itself. You described 831 SE 174th as \"my property\"; assessor records sometimes lag, transfers occasionally fail to record, or the property may be held in a name you do not recognize at first glance (e.g., spouse's pre-marriage name, family member, LLC). If the listed owner is not you or someone you control, stop reading and resolve that first; nothing below matters until ownership is confirmed.\n\n## Quick read (the headline answers)\n\nYou have a clean lot for either an **ADU on a permanent foundation** (the conventional path; up to ~720 sq ft here) or an **occupied tiny house on wheels** (the much faster, much cheaper path; not a permanent dwelling, but legal long-term). All FEMA, landslide, liquefaction, and steep-slope flags are clear; the only overlay (`h`, Aircraft Landing) does not restrict residential height in R zones; the lot exceeds the 7,000 sq ft R7 minimum; and there is no plan district or historic overlay to navigate. The fastest, cheapest path by far is a tiny house on wheels in the back yard. The path that produces a permanent, financeable dwelling that adds resale value is a detached ADU. The two are governed by entirely different parts of the code.\n\n---\n\n## 1. What kind of \"tiny house\" can you build?\n\nPortland treats these as three completely different things. The law sees no overlap.\n\n### A. Accessory Dwelling Unit (ADU) on a permanent foundation\n\n**Governing chapter: Title 33.205 (Accessory Dwelling Units).** Live link: `https://www.portland.gov/code/33/200s/205`. City plain-language page: `https://www.portland.gov/ppd/zoning-land-use/zoning-code-overview/adu-zoning`.\n\nA real, permanent dwelling unit; counts as a building under Title 24; permitted, inspected, financeable, taxed as part of the property. Allowed by right in R7 on a lot with an existing house.\n\nKey rules that bind your project:\n\n- **Maximum size: the lesser of 800 sq ft, or 75% of the primary dwelling's living area** (33.205.040). With your existing house at 960 sq ft assessor-reported, your ADU cap is **720 sq ft** (75% \u00d7 960). Worth confirming the 960 figure with BDS or your county tax record before designing; if your house is actually larger than the assessor shows (additions, finished basement that did or did not get permits), the cap can move up to 800.\n- ADUs are allowed in R2.5, R5, R7, R10, R20 by right.\n- After Portland's 2025 RIP2-related code update, **two ADUs may be allowed** on a single lot if the lot meets the minimum size in Table 205-2 and fronts a city-maintained street. Your lot fronts SE 174th Ave (a city street); whether you qualify for two units depends on the table values and the 40-foot placement rule, which the city consolidated into 33.205 in 2025. For a single detached ADU in R7 you are not in question; for two units, ask BDS to confirm.\n- Cannot be in the `z` (Constrained Sites) overlay. You are in `h` (Aircraft Landing) only, so that exclusion does not apply.\n- Use as primary residence: yes. Long-term rental: yes. Short-term rental (STR): yes, as a Type A accessory short-term rental under **33.207**, but using STRs forfeits the ADU-SDC waiver (see \u00a75).\n\n### B. Tiny House on Wheels (THOW) / occupied recreational vehicle\n\n**Governing material: Title 33 RV / Tiny House on Wheels provisions** (currently linked from city plain-language page; the legacy chapter pointer was 33.262, the 2021 Shelter-to-Housing-Continuum amendments updated the placement rules, and the city's authoritative reference today is the policy page at `https://www.portland.gov/ppd/zoning-land-use/zoning-code-overview/occupied-rvs-and-tiny-houses-wheels`). Verify the current code section number with that page; section numbers have moved.\n\nA vehicle, not a building. Not a Title 24 structure, no ADU permit, no SDCs, not part of the residential density count. Treated as an occupied RV.\n\nKey rules that bind your project:\n\n- **One occupied RV / THOW per lot** that already has a primary dwelling (your 1947 house qualifies). Vacant lots: not allowed.\n- Must be parked **behind the front architectural plane of the primary dwelling**.\n- **At least 5 feet from the main dwelling** (per current city guidance).\n- Motorized vehicles must park on a paved surface; non-motorized THOWs may park on compacted gravel or similar stable ground.\n- If the unit has internal plumbing, the site needs a **permitted RV sewer dump (cleanout) and a permitted water connection**; if the unit draws power, it needs a **permitted electrical hookup**. The hookups need permits, not the THOW itself.\n- **Long-term occupancy: yes.** Use as primary residence: legally allowed. Long-term rental income: yes. **Short-term rental: NOT permitted under this program.**\n- Does **not** count toward the lot's residential density. You can have your house plus a THOW plus an ADU, in principle, on the same lot.\n- No certifications or inspections required of the THOW itself; ANSI A119.5 / RVIA-built units are typical.\n\n### C. \"Tiny home\" as primary (or only) dwelling\n\n**Governing material: Title 33.110 single-dwelling standards + Oregon Residential Specialty Code (ORSC) Appendix Q (small homes \u2264 400 sq ft) or the standard ORSC for larger units.** State code, not city code, governs the actual building specs; Title 33 governs siting, setbacks, height.\n\nA \"tiny home\" built on a permanent foundation, occupied as the only dwelling on the lot, is just a small single-family house. There is no separate \"tiny home\" zoning category; it is a house, and 33.110 applies to it identically. ORSC Appendix Q allows small homes \u2264 400 sq ft with a relaxed code (one loft, ladder access, smaller stair / ceiling allowances). Above 400 sq ft, full ORSC applies. There is no minimum house size in Portland's code that would block a small primary dwelling, but you would still meet R7 setbacks, height, and FAR.\n\nYou already have a primary dwelling, so this option is not relevant to you unless you demolish the existing house.\n\n### Comparison\n\n| | ADU (foundation) | THOW (wheels) | Tiny home as primary dwelling |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Code | 33.205 | Title 33 occupied-RV provisions + city guidance | 33.110 + ORSC |\n| Building permit | Yes (Title 24) | No (vehicle) | Yes |\n| SDCs | Yes (waiver available) | No | Yes |\n| Max size on your lot | ~720 sq ft (75% of 960) | Limited by ANSI / DMV class | R7 standards |\n| Primary residence | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n| Long-term rental | Yes | Yes | Yes |\n| Short-term rental | Yes (loses SDC waiver) | **No** | Yes |\n| Counts toward density | Yes | No | Yes |\n| Typical timeline | 4-9 months | weeks | 6-12 months |\n| Rough cost (Portland 2026) | $150K-$300K+ | $30K-$120K incl. hookups | varies, ~$200/sf+ |\n\n---\n\n## 2. Zoning detail: R7 + `h` overlay\n\n### Base zone R7 (Single-Dwelling 7,000)\n\n**Chapter 33.110.** Live link: `https://www.portland.gov/code/33/100s/110`. PDF: `https://www.portland.gov/sites/default/files/code/33.110-sd-zones.pdf`.\n\nR7's development standards live in tables in Chapter 33.110 (typically referenced as Table 110-2 et al.). The values that drive a tiny-house project are:\n\n- **Minimum lot size for development: 7,000 sq ft.** Your lot is 8,083 sq ft (over).\n- **Maximum building height: 30 feet** for a primary dwelling. Detached accessory structures (and detached ADUs) are typically capped lower per 33.110.250 and 33.205; the long-running practical cap for a detached ADU is around 20-24 ft, but the exact current number must be read off the live chapter (Portland updated accessory structure / ADU height rules during the 2024-2025 amendment cycle).\n- **Setbacks (typical R7):** front 10 ft; sides 5 ft; rear 5 ft for accessory structures, larger for primary structures. Confirm the table values when you fetch 33.110, since RIP changed several of these.\n- **Maximum building coverage and FAR:** check Table 110-3 / 110-5 in the live chapter. With a 960 sq ft existing footprint plus a ~720 sq ft ADU footprint on an 8,083 sq ft lot, you are well under any plausible coverage ratio.\n- **Detached accessory structures:** see **33.110.250** for the per-zone rules and **33.205** for ADU-specific siting (which often relaxes the accessory structure height cap for ADUs).\n\n### `h` Aircraft Landing Overlay\n\n**Chapter 33.400.** Live link: `https://www.portland.gov/code/33/400s/400`.\n\nPlain reading of 33.400 confirms that **in residential, commercial/mixed-use, IR, and CI1 zones, structures are regulated by the base zone height limits, not the overlay's heights**; the overlay only applies its own height limits in employment, industrial, CI2, and open-space zones. So `h` is informational here. It does not change what you can build at this lot. (If you ever wanted to put a ham radio tower or similar structure that approached the overlay cap, the overlay would matter; for an ADU or THOW, it does not.)\n\n### Density: how many units?\n\nYou are not in a plan district, so 33.110 governs density. With the post-RIP and post-RIP2 framework, your R7 lot allows:\n\n- 1 house (existing) + 1 ADU: yes, by right.\n- 1 house + 2 ADUs: possibly, after the 2025 update; depends on lot size threshold in 33.205 Table 205-2 and the 40-ft placement rule. Confirm with BDS.\n- Duplex / triplex / fourplex via RIP: middle-housing options under 33.110 are theoretically open in R7, but the practical economics on a 1947 single-family lot of 8,083 sq ft usually do not pencil unless you are demolishing or doing a middle-housing land division (33.644). Outside scope of a tiny-house question, but worth knowing the door exists.\n\nA THOW is not counted toward density, so it stacks on top of any of the above.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Permits and approval order\n\n### Likely permits (ADU path)\n\n| Permit | Bureau | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| Building permit (NSFR / ADU) | Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D, formerly BDS) | Title 24; structural, ORSC, energy code |\n| Zoning review | PP&D Land Use Services | 33.205, 33.110 standards check |\n| Plumbing permit | PP&D | Title 25 |\n| Electrical permit | PP&D | Title 26 |\n| Mechanical / HVAC permit | PP&D | Title 27 |\n| Sewer connection / Branch | Bureau of Environmental Services (BES) | side-sewer connection, may require a new lateral |\n| Stormwater review | BES Site Development | 2020 Stormwater Management Manual; small-site form path is typical for an ADU |\n| Water service | Portland Water Bureau | meter sizing, possible new tap |\n| Driveway / curb cut (only if changing access) | PBOT | encroachment / curb-cut permit |\n| Tree review | Urban Forestry (under PP&D; Title 11) | required if the ADU footprint or grading is within a regulated tree's root protection zone, or any street tree is affected |\n| Fire / Title 31 review | Portland Fire & Rescue | typically rolled into building permit; access and water flow checks |\n| Address assignment | PP&D | a new ADU gets its own address (e.g., 831A) |\n\n### Likely permits (THOW path)\n\nFar simpler; the unit itself needs no city permit. You need:\n\n- **Electrical permit** (Title 26) for the dedicated outdoor hookup.\n- **Plumbing permit** (Title 25) for the water spigot and the RV-style sewer cleanout / dump.\n- Possibly a **mechanical permit** if you tie in propane / gas.\n- No zoning / building permit; the zoning check is informal verification that the placement (behind front plane, 5 ft from house, paved or compacted-gravel pad) complies.\n\n### Sequence (ADU path)\n\n1. **Free 15-minute PP&D consultation** (do this first; details in \u00a76). Walk in with your address and a one-page sketch.\n2. (Optional) **Early Assistance** meeting if you want a written summary; small fee.\n3. **Pick a design.** Strongly consider Portland's free pre-approved detached ADU plans (`https://www.portland.gov/ppd`; search \"ADU pre-approved plans\"). They cut weeks off review and reduce design costs.\n4. **Submit building permit + zoning review** through Portland Permitting Online (DevHub).\n5. **Submit trade permits** (plumbing, electrical, mechanical) at the same time or after; one set of inspections is easier if filed together.\n6. **BES / Water / PBOT / Urban Forestry** reviews run in parallel during the building permit review.\n7. **Permit issuance.** Pay SDCs (or record the SDC-waiver covenant; see \u00a75).\n8. **Construction with inspections at framing, plumbing rough-in, electrical rough-in, mechanical rough-in, insulation, drywall, final.**\n9. **Final inspection / Certificate of Occupancy.** ADU now legal to occupy.\n\n### Type II / III review possibility\n\nAlmost no chance for a standard detached ADU on this lot. Type II (Adjustment, 33.805) is only triggered if you cannot meet a development standard and need a discretionary deviation (e.g., a setback you cannot meet because of an existing structure). Type III (Conditional Use, design review) is not in play in R7 for an ADU. Environmental review (33.430) does not apply because you have no `c` or `p` overlay.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Site-specific gotchas for THIS lot\n\nThe good news first; the city's data on your parcel says:\n\n- **No FEMA flood hazard, no flood way.** Johnson Creek is south of you but does not reach this lot.\n- **No regulated landslide hazard, no liquefaction hazard, no >20% steep slope.** Unusual cleanliness for east Portland; treat it as a gift.\n- **No environmental zone (`c` or `p`).** No environmental review path triggered.\n- **No historic / conservation district, not a contributing structure.** No design review.\n- **No plan district.** 33.110 + 33.205 are the ruling chapters, full stop.\n- **No drainage district.** No special stormwater jurisdiction.\n- **Permit history is light** (electrical service upgrade in 2000, a zoning confirmation, a weed complaint). No prior unpermitted ADU work to clean up; the property looks straightforward in this respect.\n\nNow the things that warrant active attention:\n\n- **Trees (Title 11).** The PortlandMaps data layer I queried does not include private trees on the parcel; it only shows public street trees. Any tree \u2265 12\" DBH on the lot, or any street tree in the right-of-way along SE 174th Ave, can pull Title 11 into the project. Walk the lot, measure trunks at 4.5 ft above grade, and bring the count to your PP&D consultation. Mitigation can require replanting or fee-in-lieu if removal is unavoidable.\n- **Stormwater (BES SWMM).** New impervious area triggers stormwater management. For a typical ADU under ~1,500 sq ft of new impervious (footprint + driveway extension), the **Simplified Approach** in the 2020 Stormwater Management Manual usually applies: a sized soakage trench or drywell on-site. If you can avoid expanding the driveway, the rule gets easier.\n- **Sewer.** SE 174th Ave is built-out; the city sewer main is almost certainly in the street. Confirm via PortlandMaps' Utilities panel or by asking BES Permit Center (503-823-7740). Expect a Sewer Branch Permit for either a new lateral (if the ADU is too far from the existing house lateral to share) or a re-tap. If the existing house is on a private septic system (uncommon at this address but worth checking), the rules change materially; you would need to confirm or extend public sewer service first.\n- **Foundation.** A detached ADU requires a permanent foundation per Title 24 / ORSC. If you build on a permanent foundation, you have an ADU (33.205). If you build on a trailer with wheels remaining attached, you have a THOW. The foundation/no-foundation distinction is the legal hinge between the two paths; you cannot \"convert\" a THOW to an ADU later without going back through the full ADU permit and effectively rebuilding to building code.\n- **Setback between dwellings.** For an ADU, the setback to the existing house follows accessory-structure standards in 33.110.250 plus any 33.205-specific separation. Typical practical minimum: 6 ft, sometimes 10 ft when one structure has windows facing the other (fire code Title 31 also drives this). For a THOW: 5 ft minimum from the main dwelling per current city guidance.\n- **Parking.** Portland eliminated minimum off-street parking requirements citywide in 2022. No on-site parking is required for an ADU at this address. Existing parking serving the primary house can remain, but it does not need to be replaced or augmented for the ADU.\n- **Utilities: separate vs. shared meters.** ADUs may share or have separate water and electrical meters. Separate metering enables sub-metered tenant billing but adds significant cost ($5-15K typical). Sewer is always one connection per parcel.\n- **Existing 100 A electrical service.** The 2000 permit shows your house has a 100 A service. A new ADU typically requires a service upgrade to 200 A or a separate ADU subpanel fed from an upgraded main; budget $4-10K for that work plus PGE coordination. This is a common surprise; you read it here first.\n- **Address assignment.** PP&D will assign a unit address (probably 831A SE 174th Ave) at permit issuance.\n- **Aircraft Landing overlay (`h`).** As covered, no restriction on residential structures here. Mentioning only because PortlandMaps will show it and it can look alarming until you read 33.400.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Cost and timeline reality check (Portland 2026)\n\nThese are typical ranges, not quotes for your project. Real numbers come from a contractor walk-through and current PP&D fee schedules.\n\n**SDCs (System Development Charges) for a new ADU.** Portland has historically waived ADU SDCs entirely if the owner records a 10-year covenant against using the unit as a Type A short-term rental (`https://www.portland.gov/ppd`; search \"ADU SDC waiver\"). Without the waiver, expect SDCs in the **$15K-$25K** range across BES, Water, Parks, and Transportation. Confirm waiver mechanics and current covenant form at intake; the waiver has been periodically extended by city council.\n\n**Permit fees.** Building, plumbing, electrical, mechanical, and zoning fees on an ADU typically total **$6K-$12K** including plan review. Add ~$1,500-$3,500 for sewer branch permit and ~$500-$2,000 for water service work depending on whether a new tap is needed.\n\n**Plan review timeline.** Pre-approved-plan ADU: roughly **6-10 weeks** start to permit issuance once a complete application is submitted. Custom-design ADU: **3-6 months** typical. THOW hookup permits: **a few weeks**.\n\n**Common reasons projects get stuck.**\n\n1. Incomplete site plan; missing existing structure dimensions, tree locations, or grading information.\n2. Stormwater approach not specified or inappropriate to the soils (drywell sizing).\n3. Sewer lateral location unknown; BES asks for an as-built or a video inspection.\n4. Setback off by inches; a survey would have caught it.\n5. Tree-protection-zone overlap with the proposed footprint.\n6. Existing unpermitted work on the primary house surfaced during review (records check often catches this).\n\n---\n\n## 6. Who to call, in what order\n\n1. **Portland Permitting & Development (PP&D), General Information: 503-823-7300.** Hours Monday-Friday 8 AM - 5 PM. Schedule a **free 15-minute planning consultation** before doing anything else. Ask specifically about: ADU vs. THOW for this lot, two-ADU eligibility, current SDC waiver status, and whether your lot needs a survey before design.\n2. **PP&D Inspections: 503-823-7388** (PPDinspections@portlandoregon.gov). For inspection scheduling once you have permits.\n3. **BES Permit Center: 503-823-7740** (sewer branch and stormwater questions, 1900 SW 4th Ave).\n4. **Portland Water Bureau Customer Service: 503-823-7770** (meter sizing, new tap for ADU).\n5. **PBOT Development Permitting: 503-823-7002** (only if you change the curb cut; for sharing the existing driveway, not needed).\n6. **Urban Forestry: 503-823-8733** (tree permits, regulated trees on the parcel or in the ROW; Title 11).\n7. **Portland Fire & Rescue Plan Review:** typically routed through PP&D; a separate call is rarely needed for a single ADU.\n\nThe free 15-minute appointment is the single most valuable thing you can do before spending a dollar on plans. Bring: address, lot dimensions, a hand-sketched site plan showing the existing house and proposed ADU / THOW location, and your questions. They will tell you within those 15 minutes whether anything in your plan kills it. Schedule via `https://www.portland.gov/ppd` (search \"schedule appointment\").\n\n---\n\n## 7. Plain-language next steps\n\nNumbered. Do them in this order. Items 1-5 are free or near-free.\n\n1. **Confirm ownership.** Pull a Multnomah County tax statement (`https://multcoproptax.com`) for parcel R337949 / 1S3E06AB 8800 and confirm the listed owner is you. If not, resolve before doing anything else.\n2. **Verify on PortlandMaps yourself.** Go to `https://www.portlandmaps.com/search/?query=831+SE+174th+Ave` and click the parcel. Spot-check the zoning (R7), overlay (`h`), and the hazard flags (all \"No\") against this document. Save screenshots or print the property report.\n3. **Decide ADU vs. THOW.** ADU = financeable, permanent, ~$200K+, 4-9 months. THOW = ~$30-100K, weeks not months, but not a permanent dwelling. This is the single biggest decision; everything else flows from it.\n4. **Walk the lot with a tape measure and a notebook.** Note: setbacks from existing house to lot lines, dimensions of the existing house footprint, location and approximate trunk diameter of every tree, location of the existing driveway, location of the sewer cleanout (often a white plastic cap near the house), location of the electrical meter and main panel, slope of the back yard.\n5. **Schedule the free 15-minute PP&D consultation** at 503-823-7300 (also book Early Assistance if you want it in writing). Bring the items from step 4 plus this document; ask the planner to confirm the 720 sq ft ADU cap, the two-ADU eligibility for this lot, and the current SDC waiver status.\n6. **(ADU path only) Survey the lot.** $1.5K-$3K. A current survey eliminates the most common review delay (setbacks off by inches).\n7. **(ADU path only) Choose between pre-approved plans and custom design.** Pre-approved saves weeks and design fees; custom gets you exactly what you want.\n8. **Get bids from at least two contractors.** Look specifically at: experience with Portland ADU permitting, electrical service upgrade scope, sewer connection scope.\n9. **Submit the building permit application** (DevHub) with full plan set, site plan, and trade permits if filing concurrently. Pay intake fees.\n10. **Plan review correction loop.** Expect one or two correction cycles. Respond fast; reviewers move on if you delay.\n11. **Permit issuance.** Pay SDCs or record the SDC-waiver covenant.\n12. **Construction with inspections** at each milestone (framing, rough plumbing, rough electrical, rough mechanical, insulation, drywall, final).\n13. **Final inspection and Certificate of Occupancy.** ADU is now legal to occupy.\n\nTHOW path replaces steps 6-13 with: build or buy the unit, prep the pad, file electrical and plumbing hookup permits, install hookups, pass inspections on the hookups only, move in.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Accuracy caveats\n\n### What is verified from authoritative city data (Path A: PortlandMaps ArcGIS)\n- Address geocoding, property ID, state ID\n- Base zone R7\n- Overlay `h` (Aircraft Landing) only\n- No plan district\n- No historic / conservation district\n- No environmental zone\n- All hazard flags (FEMA flood, flood way, liquefaction, landslide, steep slope) returning \"No\"\n- Lot area 8,083 sq ft per BDS, 0.19 ac per assessor\n- Existing dwelling 960 sq ft, built 1947\n- Permit history (3 records since 2000)\n- Owner of record (KARAM, CHAFEK & JANOURA, ANESA)\n\n### What is cited from current Title 33 / city pages on portland.gov\n- 33.205 ADU sizing rule (lesser of 800 sq ft or 75% of primary dwelling)\n- 33.205 zone eligibility (R2.5 through R20)\n- 33.205 Constrained Sites (`z`) overlay exclusion\n- 33.205 short-term-rental allowance via 33.207\n- 33.400 Aircraft Landing overlay non-application to residential height\n- City's \"Occupied RVs and Tiny Houses on Wheels\" guidance page (current rules; the underlying code section number for THOWs has moved between 33.262 and other locations across amendments; verify the current section at the city's policy page)\n- 2025 RIP2 update introducing two-ADU allowance\n\n### What you must verify with the city before relying on it\n1. **The specific 33.110 R7 standards table values** (front/side/rear setbacks, height, FAR, building coverage, accessory structure rules at 33.110.250) at the time you apply. I have given typical numbers; the live chapter is the source of truth and amendments do happen mid-year.\n2. **The current ADU-SDC waiver mechanism and whether it is still active.** Council renews this; status can change.\n3. **The current 33.205 minimum lot sizes** in Tables 205-1 and 205-2 (drives whether your lot qualifies for one ADU or two).\n4. **The current code section governing occupied RVs / THOWs.** The city's plain-language policy page is the authoritative reference; it will name the current section number.\n5. **Whether your existing house is actually 960 sq ft or has unpermitted additions** that change the 75% calculation.\n6. **Whether you are on city sewer** (the BDS Property layer does not directly answer this; PortlandMaps' Utilities panel or a BES inquiry will).\n7. **Tree inventory on the parcel.** I cannot see private trees; you need to walk the lot.\n8. **Current PBOT requirements** if you ever change the curb cut.\n9. **Pre-approved plan availability and current list.** Portland updates this catalog periodically.\n\n### General disclosure\nNone of this is legal advice; I am not a lawyer or a permit consultant. Code amendments ship multiple times per year. Any rule cited here should be verified against the live chapter on portland.gov before you commit money to plans or construction. The free 15-minute PP&D consultation exists exactly for this purpose; use it before spending a dollar.\n\n---\n\n*Sources: PortlandMaps ArcGIS (Public/Zoning, Public/BDS_Property, Public/Natural_Hazards), PortlandMaps assessor + permit APIs (R337949), Title 33 chapters via portland.gov, City \"Accessory dwelling unit (ADU) zoning requirements\" page, City \"Occupied Recreational Vehicles and Tiny Houses on Wheels\" page. Snapshot date: May 1, 2026.*",
