al Infill Project / RIP \u2014 cite 33.110.240 and related)?\n\n**3. What permits will I need, and in what order?**\n- List every permit type likely triggered: Zoning permit / Type I land use review, Building permit (Title 24), Plumbing (Title 25), Electrical (Title 26), Mechanical/HVAC (Title 27), Sewer connection, Stormwater (BES requirements), Driveway/curb cut if needed, Tree permit (Title 11) if any tree is within reach of the build.\n- Which bureau handles each: Bureau of Development Services (BDS), Bureau of Environmental Services (BES), Portland Water Bureau, PBOT, Urban Forestry, Fire Bureau (Title 31).\n- What is the typical sequence: pre-application \u2192 zoning confirmation \u2192 site plan \u2192 building permit \u2192 inspections \u2192 final occupancy?\n- Are there any Type II or Type III land use reviews that could be triggered (adjustment, variance, environmental review)?\n\n**4. Site-specific gotchas I should ask about:**\n- Trees: any regulated trees on the lot trigger Title 11 review and possible mitigation/replanting.\n- Stormwater: does my lot fall under simplified or full stormwater management (BES Stormwater Manual)?\n- Sewer: am I on city sewer or a private system? Is a sewer line extension or capacity charge (\"System Development Charges\" / SDCs) likely?\n- Floodplain, landslide hazard, or environmental zone overlays (especially relevant in east Portland with Johnson Creek nearby).\n- Setback from existing house: minimum separation between primary dwelling and ADU.\n- Parking: is on-site parking still required for an ADU at this address?\n- Utilities: separate vs. shared meters, address assignment.\n- Foundation requirement: is a permanent foundation required to count as a dwelling (vs. a THOW)?\n\n**5. Cost and timeline reality check:**\n- Typical SDCs (System Development Charges) for a new ADU in Portland and any current waivers/discounts.\n- Typical permit fee ranges and review timelines (weeks vs. months).\n- Common reasons projects g